{"title_page": "Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira\n|image = \n|caption = \n|birth_name = \n|birth_date = c. 1580\n|birth_place = [[Torres Vedras]], [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]]\n|death_date = 1650 (aged c. 70)\n|death_place = [[Nagasaki]], [[Japan]]\n|nationality = [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]]\n|citizenship =\n|occupation = Catholic priest and Jesuit missionary\n|known_for = \n|signature = \n}}\n[[image:Tombstone with the name of Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira.png|170px|thumb|Ferreira was interred in the gravesite of his son-in-law Sugimoto Ch\u016bkei's family.]]\n'''Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira''' (c. 1580&ndash;1650) was a [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] Catholic priest and [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] missionary who committed [[apostasy]] after being captured and tortured during the [[Martyrs of Japan|anti-Christian purges]] in 17th-century [[Japan]]. During the [[Tokugawa shogunate]], [[Christians|Christian]] missionaries and their Japanese followers were persecuted, arrested and executed. Authorities were concerned that the religion was making followers loyal to [[Jesus]] rather than the [[Emperor of Japan|Emperor]] or the Shogunate.\n\nAfter Ferreira had renounced his faith, he remained in Japan for the rest of his life. He became known as one of the \"fallen priests\" who assisted Japanese authorities with their knowledge of Western philosophies and sciences.\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn around 1580, in [[Torres Vedras]], Portugal, Ferreira was sent to [[Asia]], where he was a missionary from 1609 to 1633 in Japan, which was then ruled by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]].\n\n==Apostate==\nIn 1633, Ferreira was captured and renounced Christianity after being tortured for five hours. He became the most famous of the \"fallen priests\" and changed his name to Sawano Ch\u016ban ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u6ca2\u91ce\u5fe0\u5eb5). He registered at a Buddhist temple in accordance with Japanese law, and called himself \"a member of the [[Zen]] sect\", but his own publications attest that he adopted a philosophy of [[natural law]]:<ref name=\"y\">Cieslik, Hubert (1973). \"[http://pweb.cc.sophia.ac.jp/britto/xavier/cieslik/cie_ferreira.pdf The Case of Christov\u00e3o Ferreira] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221103419/http://pweb.cc.sophia.ac.jp/britto/xavier/cieslik/cie_ferreira.pdf |date=2013-12-21 }}\". Monumenta Nipponica 29</ref>\n:Hubert Cieslik writes:\n{{quote|Viewing the world around we see that everything is endowed with its own nature and merit; bird or beast, insect or fish, grass or tree, earth or stone, air or water, each one has its natural quality and merit. All this is the work of ''Natura''. Man stands at the head of all existence and Heaven has endowed mankind with the natural faculties of charity, justice, propriety, sagacity.<ref name=\"y\"/>}}\n\n==Life after apostasy==\nAfter his apostasy he married a Japanese woman and wrote several books, including treatises on Western [[astronomy]] and [[medicine]], which became widely distributed in the [[Edo period]]. He also is alleged to have privately written a book on religion entitled \u300c\u9855\u507d\u9332\u300d (''The Deception Revealed'') in 1636, but it was not published for 300 years and there is some controversy concerning who wrote it.<ref name=\"y\"/> He participated in government trials of other captured Jesuits.<ref>''The making of an enterprise: the Society of Jesus in Portugal, its empire, and beyond, 1540-1750'', Dauril Alden, Stanford University Press, 1996, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7nVIBhrRb9AC&pg=PA136#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 136]</ref> He was often present during the use of ''[[fumi-e]]'', whereby [[kakure kirishitan|suspected Christians]] were ordered to trample on an image of Jesus Christ.<ref name=\"y\"/>\n\n==Death==\nHe died in [[Nagasaki]] in 1650.<ref>Henrique Leit\u00e3o (2000). [https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/361/36100108.pdf \"Rese\u00f1a de 'La Supercherie D\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Une R\u00e9futation du Catholicisme au Japon au XVIIe Si\u00e9cle' de Jacques Proust,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920193921/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/361/36100108.pdf |date=2012-09-20 }} ''Bulletin of Portuguese / Japanese Studies, December, A\u00f1o/Vol 1, Universidade Nova de Lisboa. Lisboa, Portugal, 131-134</ref> Some reports claim that, just before his death he recanted, was tortured and died as a [[martyr]], while other reports merely note that he died.<ref name=y />\n\n== In popular culture==\n[[Shusaku Endo]]'s novel ''[[Silence (novel)|Silence]]'' is set in the aftermath of Ferreira's apostasy.\nFerreira is played by [[Tetsur\u014d Tamba]] in the [[Silence (1971 film)|1971 film version]] and by [[Liam Neeson]] in the [[Silence (2016 film)|2016 film version]].\nIn the 1996 Portuguese drama film ''[[Os Olhos da \u00c1sia]]'', [[Jo\u00e3o Perry]] plays Ferreira.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Giuseppe Chiara]]\n*[[List of Westerners who visited Japan before 1868]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* George Elison (1988). ''Deus destroyed: the image of Christianity in early modern Japan''.\n*{{in lang|ja}} {{abbr|Miyanaga Takashi|\u5bae\u6c38\u5b5d}} (2004). ''{{abbr|Nihon Y\u014dgakushi: Po, Ra, Ran, Ei, Doku, Futsu, Rogo no juy\u014d|\u65e5\u672c\u6d0b\u5b66\u53f2\u2015\u8461\u30fb\u7f85\u30fb\u862d\u30fb\u82f1\u30fb\u72ec\u30fb\u4ecf\u30fb\u9732\u8a9e\u306e\u53d7\u5bb9}}''. Tokyo: {{abbr|Sansh\u016bsha|\u4e09\u4fee\u793e}}, p.&nbsp;50. {{ISBN|4-384-04011-3}}\n*{{in lang|fr}} ''La Supercherie d\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Une R\u00e9futation du Catholicisme au Japon au XVIIe Si\u00e8cle'', annotated by Jacques Proust, Paris, \u00e9ditions Chandeigne, 2013. {{ISBN|978-2-915540-97-0}}\n*{{in lang|it}} [[Daniello Bartoli]], ''[[Istoria della Compagnia di Gesu|Istoria della Compagnia di Ges\u00f9]]'', ''Il Giappone'' (1660), V, 12, \"Apostasia del Ferreira, suo ravvedimento, e morte\" [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070797513;view=1up;seq=64]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.org/details/THECHRISTIANCENTURYINJAPAN15491650CRBOXER The Christian Century in Japan, by Charles Boxer]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131221103419/http://pweb.cc.sophia.ac.jp/britto/xavier/cieslik/cie_ferreira.pdf The case of Christ\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira, by Hubert Cieslik]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferreira, Cristovao}}\n[[Category:1580 births]]\n[[Category:1650 deaths]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Portuguese torture victims]]\n[[Category:Former Jesuits]]\n[[Category:16th-century Portuguese Jesuits]]\n[[Category:17th-century Portuguese Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Converts to Buddhism from Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Roman Catholic missionaries]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Buddhists]]\n[[Category:People from Torres Vedras]]\n[[Category:Jesuit missionaries in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira\n|image = \n|caption = \n|birth_name = \n|birth_date = c. 1580\n|birth_place = [[Torres Vedras]], [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]]\n|death_date = 1650 (aged c. 70)\n|death_place = [[Nagasaki]], [[Japan]]\n|nationality = [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]]\n|citizenship =\n|occupation = Catholic priest and Jesuit missionary\n|known_for = \n|signature = \n}}\n[[image:Tombstone with the name of Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira.png|170px|thumb|Ferreira was interred in the gravesite of his son-in-law Sugimoto Ch\u016bkei's family.]]\n'''Crist\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira''' (c. 1580&ndash;1650) was a [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] Catholic priest and [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] missionary who committed [[apostasy]] after being captured and tortured during the [[Martyrs of Japan|anti-Christian purges]] in 17th-century [[Japan]]. During the [[Tokugawa shogunate]], [[Christians|Christian]] missionaries and their Japanese followers were persecuted, arrested and executed. Authorities were concerned that the religion was making followers loyal to [[Jesus]] rather than the [[Emperor of Japan|Emperor]] or the Shogunate.\n\nAfter Ferreira had renounced his faith, he remained in Japan for the rest of his life. He became known as one of the \"fallen priests\" who assisted Japanese authorities with their knowledge of Western philosophies and sciences. \n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn around 1580, in [[Torres Vedras]], Portugal, Ferreira was sent to [[Asia]], where he was a missionary from 1609 to 1633 in Japan, which was then ruled by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]].\n\n==Apostate==\nIn 1633, Ferreira was captured and renounced Christianity after being tortured for five hours. He became the most famous of the \"fallen priests\" and changed his name to Sawano Ch\u016ban ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u6ca2\u91ce\u5fe0\u5eb5). He registered at a Buddhist temple in accordance with Japanese law, and called himself \"a member of the [[Zen]] sect\", but his own publications attest that he adopted a philosophy of [[natural law]]:<ref name=\"y\">Cieslik, Hubert (1973). \"[http://pweb.cc.sophia.ac.jp/britto/xavier/cieslik/cie_ferreira.pdf The Case of Christov\u00e3o Ferreira] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221103419/http://pweb.cc.sophia.ac.jp/britto/xavier/cieslik/cie_ferreira.pdf |date=2013-12-21 }}\". Monumenta Nipponica 29</ref>\n:Hubert Cieslik writes:\n{{quote|Viewing the world around we see that everything is endowed with its own nature and merit; bird or beast, insect or fish, grass or tree, earth or stone, air or water, each one has its natural quality and merit. All this is the work of ''Natura''. Man stands at the head of all existence and Heaven has endowed mankind with the natural faculties of charity, justice, propriety, sagacity.<ref name=\"y\"/>}}\n\n==Life after apostasy==\nAfter his apostasy he married a Japanese woman and wrote several books, including treatises on Western [[astronomy]] and [[medicine]], which became widely distributed in the [[Edo period]]. He also is alleged to have privately written a book on religion entitled \u300c\u9855\u507d\u9332\u300d (''The Deception Revealed'') in 1636, but it was not published for 300 years and there is some controversy concerning who wrote it.<ref name=\"y\"/> He participated in government trials of other captured Jesuits.<ref>''The making of an enterprise: the Society of Jesus in Portugal, its empire, and beyond, 1540-1750'', Dauril Alden, Stanford University Press, 1996, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7nVIBhrRb9AC&pg=PA136#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 136]</ref> He was often present during the use of ''[[fumi-e]]'', whereby [[kakure kirishitan|suspected Christians]] were ordered to trample on an image of Jesus Christ.<ref name=\"y\"/>  \n\n==Death==\nHe died in [[Nagasaki]] in 1650.<ref>Henrique Leit\u00e3o (2000). [http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/361/36100108.pdf \"Rese\u00f1a de 'La Supercherie D\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Une R\u00e9futation du Catholicisme au Japon au XVIIe Si\u00e9cle' de Jacques Proust,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120920193921/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/361/36100108.pdf |date=2012-09-20 }} ''Bulletin of Portuguese / Japanese Studies, December, A\u00f1o/Vol 1, Universidade Nova de Lisboa. Lisboa, Portugal, 131-134</ref> Some reports claim that, just before his death he recanted, was tortured and died as a [[martyr]], while other reports merely note that he died.<ref name=y />\n\n== In popular culture==\n[[Shusaku Endo]]'s novel ''[[Silence (novel)|Silence]]'' is set in the aftermath of Ferreira's apostasy.\nFerreira is played by [[Tetsur\u014d Tamba]] in the [[Silence (1971 film)|1971 film version]] and by [[Liam Neeson]] in the [[Silence (2016 film)|2016 film version]].\nIn the 1996 Portuguese drama film ''[[Os Olhos da \u00c1sia]]'', [[Jo\u00e3o Perry]] plays Ferreira.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Giuseppe Chiara]]\n*[[List of Westerners who visited Japan before 1868]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* George Elison (1988). ''Deus destroyed: the image of Christianity in early modern Japan''.\n*{{in lang|ja}} {{abbr|Miyanaga Takashi|\u5bae\u6c38\u5b5d}} (2004). ''{{abbr|Nihon Y\u014dgakushi: Po, Ra, Ran, Ei, Doku, Futsu, Rogo no juy\u014d|\u65e5\u672c\u6d0b\u5b66\u53f2\u2015\u8461\u30fb\u7f85\u30fb\u862d\u30fb\u82f1\u30fb\u72ec\u30fb\u4ecf\u30fb\u9732\u8a9e\u306e\u53d7\u5bb9}}''. Tokyo: {{abbr|Sansh\u016bsha|\u4e09\u4fee\u793e}}, p.&nbsp;50. {{ISBN|4-384-04011-3}}\n*{{in lang|fr}} ''La Supercherie d\u00e9voil\u00e9e. Une R\u00e9futation du Catholicisme au Japon au XVIIe Si\u00e8cle'', annotated by Jacques Proust, Paris, \u00e9ditions Chandeigne, 2013. {{ISBN|978-2-915540-97-0}}\n*{{in lang|it}} [[Daniello Bartoli]], ''[[Istoria della Compagnia di Gesu|Istoria della Compagnia di Ges\u00f9]]'', ''Il Giappone'' (1660), V, 12, \"Apostasia del Ferreira, suo ravvedimento, e morte\" [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433070797513;view=1up;seq=64]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.org/details/THECHRISTIANCENTURYINJAPAN15491650CRBOXER The Christian Century in Japan, by Charles Boxer]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131221103419/http://pweb.cc.sophia.ac.jp/britto/xavier/cieslik/cie_ferreira.pdf The case of Christ\u00f3v\u00e3o Ferreira, by Hubert Cieslik]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferreira, Cristovao}}\n[[Category:1580 births]]\n[[Category:1650 deaths]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Portuguese torture victims]]\n[[Category:Former Jesuits]]\n[[Category:16th-century Portuguese Jesuits]]\n[[Category:17th-century Portuguese Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Jesuits]]\n[[Category:Converts to Buddhism from Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Roman Catholic missionaries]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Buddhists]]\n[[Category:People from Torres Vedras]]\n[[Category:Jesuit missionaries in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Logan", "label": "safe", "comment": "bad link repair", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crist%C3%B3v%C3%A3o_Ferreira"}
{"title_page": "Curitiba", "text_new": "{{for|the plant genus|Curitiba prismatica}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Curitiba\n|settlement_type        = [[Municipalities of Brazil|Municipality]]\n|official_name          = ''Munic\u00edpio de Curitiba''<br>Municipality of Curitiba\n|nickname               = {{lang|pt|Cidade Modelo}} (\"Model City\"); {{lang|pt|Capital Ecol\u00f3gica do Brasil}} (\"Ecological Capital of Brazil\"); {{lang|pt|Cidade Verde}} (\"Green City\"); {{lang|pt|Capital das Arauc\u00e1rias}} (\"Capital of [[Araucaria angustifolia|Araucarias]]\");  {{lang|pt|A Cidade da N\u00e9voa Eterna}} (\"The City of Eternal Fog\")\n|motto                  = {{lang|pt|A Cidade da Gente}} (Our City; The People's City)\n|image_skyline          = Collage Curitiba.png\n|imagesize              = 280px\n|image_caption          = From the top, clockwise: aerial photography of the city; Pa\u00e7o da Liberdade in Pra\u00e7a Generoso Marques; Avenida Palace with the [[Rua XV de Novembro|15th of November Street]]; [[Rua 24 Horas|24 Hour Street]]; [[Oscar Niemeyer Museum]] and [[Botanical Garden of Curitiba|Botanical Garden]].\n|image_flag             = Bandeira de Curitiba.svg\n|flag_link              = Flag of Curitiba\n|image_seal             = Bras\u00e3o de Curitiba.svg\n|image_map              = Brazil Parana Curitiba location map.svg\n|mapsize                = 250px\n|pushpin_map            = Brazil\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n|pushpin_map_caption=Location in Brazil\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Brazil|Region]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[States of Brazil|State]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Brazil}}\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Southern Region, Brazil|South]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[File:Bandeira do Paran\u00e1.svg|border|22px]] [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]]\n|leader_title           = Mayor\n|leader_name            = [[Rafael Greca]] ([[Party of National Mobilization|PMN]])\n|leader_title1          =  <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|leader_title2          =\n|leader_name2           =\n|leader_title3          =\n|leader_name3           =\n|established_title      = Founded\n|established_date       = 29 March 1693\n|established_title2     =  <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2      =\n|established_title3     = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date3      = 1842\n|area_magnitude         =\n|area_total_km2         = 430.9\n|area_total_sq_mi       = 166.4\n|area_land_km2          =\n|area_land_sq_mi        =\n|area_water_km2         =\n|area_water_sq_mi       =\n|area_water_percent     =\n|area_urban_km2         = 319.4\n|area_urban_sq_mi       =\n|area_metro_km2         = 15416.9\n|area_metro_sq_mi       = 5952\n|population_as_of       = 2017\n|population_footnotes   = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://agenciadenoticias.ibge.gov.br/en/agencia-news/2185-news-agency/releases-en/16134-ibge-releases-population-estimates-of-municipalities-for-2017.html|title=IBGE releases population estimates for municipalities in 2017. Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics (IBGE) (August 30, 2017).|publisher=Ibge.gov.br|accessdate=30 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143904/https://agenciadenoticias.ibge.gov.br/en/agencia-news/2185-news-agency/releases-en/16134-ibge-releases-population-estimates-of-municipalities-for-2017.html|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|population_total       =  1,908,359 ([[List of cities in Brazil by population|8th]])\n|population_density_km2 = 4062\n|population_density_sq_mi = 10523\n|population_metro       = 3,400,100 ([[List of cities in Brazil by population|7th]])\n|population_density_metro_km2 = 210.9\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi = 546.2\n|population_urban       =\n|timezone               = [[UTC-3]]\n|utc_offset             = -3\n|coordinates            = {{coord|25|25|S|49|15|W|region:BR|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = 934.6\n|elevation_ft           = 3066.3\n|postal_code_type       = CEP\n|postal_code            = 80000-000 to 82999-999\n|area_code              = +55 (41)\n|website                = [http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/ Curitiba, Paran\u00e1]\n}}\n\n'''Curitiba''' ({{IPA-pt|ku\u027ei\u02c8t\u0283ib\u0250|br}})<ref>The [[European Portuguese]] pronunciation is {{IPA-pt|ku\u027ei\u02c8ti\u03b2\u0250|}}.</ref> is the capital and largest city in the [[States of Brazil|Brazilian state]] of [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]]. The city's population was 1,879,355 {{As of|2015|lc=y}}, making it the [[List of cities in Brazil by population|eighth most populous city in Brazil]] and the largest in Brazil's [[South Region, Brazil|South Region]]. The Curitiba [[Metropolitan area]] comprises 26 [[Municipalities of Brazil|municipalities]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba-parana.com/geografia-mapas/mapa-regiao-curitiba.htm |title=Mapa da Regi\u00e3o Metropolitana de Curitiba&nbsp;\u2013 Paran\u00e1 |publisher=Curitiba-parana.com |accessdate=22 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070410131340/http://www.curitiba-parana.com/geografia-mapas/mapa-regiao-curitiba.htm |archive-date=10 April 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with a total population of over 3.2&nbsp;million ([[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics|IBGE]] estimate in 2010),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/estatistica/populacao/censo2010/populacao_por_municipio.shtm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614165617/http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/estatistica/populacao/censo2010/populacao_por_municipio.shtm|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 June 2011|title=IBGE :: Instituto Brasileiro de Geografia e Estat\u00edstica|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> making it the seventh most populous metropolitan area in the country.\n\nThe city sits on a [[plateau]] at {{convert|932|m|ft}} [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]]. It is located west of the seaport of [[Paranagu\u00e1]] and is served by the [[Afonso Pena International Airport|Afonso Pena International]] and [[Bacacheri Airport|Bacacheri]] airports. Curitiba is an important cultural, political, and economic center in [[Latin America]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnestrangeiros.com.br/#!location/galleryPage|title=Curitiba|website=Rnestrangeiros.com.br|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227011053/http://www.rnestrangeiros.com.br/#!location/galleryPage|archive-date=27 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and hosts the [[Federal University of Paran\u00e1]], established in 1912.\n\nIn the 1700s Curitiba's favorable location between [[cattle]]-breeding countryside and marketplaces led to a successful cattle trade and the city's first major expansion. Later, between 1850 and 1950, it grew due to [[logging]] and [[agricultural expansion]] in Paran\u00e1 State (first [[Araucaria angustifolia]] logging, later [[mate (beverage)|mate]] and [[coffee]] cultivation and in the 1970s wheat, corn and [[soybean]] cultivation). In the 1850s, waves of [[European Brazilian|European immigrants]] arrived in Curitiba, mainly [[German Brazilian|Germans]], [[Italian Brazilian|Italians]], [[Polish Brazilian|Poles]] and [[Ukrainians of Brazil|Ukrainians]], contributing to the city's economic and cultural development.<ref name=\"curitiba-parana\">{{cite web|url=http://www.curitiba-parana.net/tradicoes.htm|title=Tradi\u00e7\u00f5es Culturais|publisher=Curitiba-parana.net|accessdate=7 March 2011|language=portuguese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211165316/http://www.curitiba-parana.net/tradicoes.htm|archive-date=11 February 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Nowadays, only small numbers of immigrants arrive, primarily from [[Middle East]]ern<ref name=\"paimeas\">{{cite web |title=A imigra\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e1rabe mu\u00e7ulmana em Curitiba |publisher=Etni-cidade |language=Portuguese |accessdate=3 October 2008 |url=http://www.etni-cidade.net/2008/a_imigracao_arabe.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205114702/http://www.etni-cidade.net/2008/a_imigracao_arabe.htm |archive-date=5 December 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and other South American countries.\n\nCuritiba's biggest expansion occurred after the 1960s, with innovative [[urban planning]] that allowed the population to grow from some hundreds of thousands to more than a million people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dados do IBGE sobre Curitiba |publisher=IBGE |language=Portuguese |accessdate=31 July 2011 |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/cidadesat/painel/painel.php?codmun=410690# |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602180952/http://www.ibge.gov.br/cidadesat/painel/painel.php?codmun=410690 |archive-date=2 June 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Curitiba's economy is based on industry and services and is the fourth largest in [[Economy of Brazil|Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cidades Brasileiras, Curitiba |publisher=SuaPesquisa |language=Portuguese |accessdate=31 July 2011 |url=http://www.suapesquisa.com/cidadesbrasileiras/cidade_curitiba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918054320/http://www.suapesquisa.com/cidadesbrasileiras/cidade_curitiba.htm |archive-date=18 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Economic growth occurred in parallel to a substantial inward flow of Brazilians from other parts of the country, as approximately half of the city's population was not born in Curitiba.<ref name=\"estra\">{{cite web |title=Quase metade de Curitiba \u00e9 dos \"estrangeiros\" |publisher=Bem Paran\u00e1 |language=Portuguese |accessdate=6 August 2008 |url=http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=23799&t=quase-metade-de-curitiba-e-dosestrangeiros |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922092532/http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=23799&t=quase-metade-de-curitiba-e-dosestrangeiros |archive-date=22 September 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCuritiba is one of the few Brazilian cities with a very high [[Human Development Index]] (0.856) and in 2010 it was awarded the Global Sustainable City Award, given to cities and municipalities that excel in sustainable urban development.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://globeaward.org/winner-city-2010.html |title=The Brazilian city Curitiba awarded the Globe Sustainable City Award 2010 |publisher=globeforum.com |accessdate=7 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714212832/http://globeaward.org/winner-city-2010.html |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> According to US magazine ''[[Reader's Digest]]'', Curitiba is the best \"Brazilian Big City\" in which to live.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nearshoreamericas.com/brazil-outsourcing-curibita-comes-on-strong-as-silicon-valley-south/ |title=Brazil Outsourcing: Curitiba Comes on Strong as 'Silicon Valley South' |publisher=Nearshore Americas |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014133919/http://nearshoreamericas.com/brazil-outsourcing-curibita-comes-on-strong-as-silicon-valley-south/ |archive-date=14 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bestcitiestolivein.net/curitiba-brazil-the-best-city-to-live-in-south-america-a-melhor-cidade-do-brasil.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723101730/http://www.bestcitiestolivein.net/curitiba-brazil-the-best-city-to-live-in-south-america-a-melhor-cidade-do-brasil.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 July 2012 |title=Bestcitiestolivein.net |publisher=Bestcitiestolivein.net |accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref> Curitiba's crime rate is considered low by Brazilian standards and the city is considered one of the safest cities in Brazil for youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planetasustentavel.abril.com.br/album/10-capitais-mais-seguras-jovens-brasil-indice-vulnerabilidade-violencia-734424.shtml?&foto=4|title=As 10 capitais mais seguras para os jovens do Brasil|website=Planetasustentavel.abril.com.br|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102042801/http://planetasustentavel.abril.com.br/album/10-capitais-mais-seguras-jovens-brasil-indice-vulnerabilidade-violencia-734424.shtml?&foto=4|archive-date=2 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The city is also regarded as the best in which to invest in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/noticias/economia/20150918/curitiba-eleita-melhor-cidade-brasil-pelo-ranking-istoe-austin-ratings/300248|title=Curitiba \u00e9 eleita a melhor cidade do Brasil pelo ranking Isto\u00e9/Austin Ratings \u2013 ISTO\u00c9 DINHEIRO|date=18 September 2015|website=Istoedinheiro.com.br|accessdate=9 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201145311/https://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/noticias/economia/20150918/curitiba-eleita-melhor-cidade-brasil-pelo-ranking-istoe-austin-ratings/300248|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Curitiba was one of the host cities of the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]], and again for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]. Despite its good social indicators, the city has a higher unemployment rate than other cities in the state.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/economia/pos-e-carreira/por-que-o-mercado-de-trabalho-de-curitiba-ainda-continua-demitindo-868i7lb2m3rmofjytl3yhy1l5 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714193243/https://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/economia/pos-e-carreira/por-que-o-mercado-de-trabalho-de-curitiba-ainda-continua-demitindo-868i7lb2m3rmofjytl3yhy1l5 |archive-date=14 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Name==\n[[File:Curitiba Centro.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial view of Batel and \u00c1gua Verde neighborhoods]]\nOne theory is that the name \"Curitiba\" comes from the [[Tupi language|Tupi]] words ''kur\u00ed tyba'', \"many pine seeds\" due to the large number of pinecones of [[Araucaria angustifolia|Paran\u00e1 pines]] in the region prior to its founding.<ref name=autogenerated2>Fenianos, E. (2003) ''Almanaque Kur'yt'yba'', Curitiba: Univer Cidade, p.6</ref> Another version, also using words from the Tupi language, is that it originates in the combination of ''kurit'' (pine tree) and ''yba'' (large amount).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inf.ufpr.br/sibgrapi2004/site.html |title=Curitiba name origin |publisher=Inf.ufpr.br |date=20 October 2004 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162138/http://www.inf.ufpr.br/sibgrapi2004/site.html |archive-date=6 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Portuguese, who founded a settlement on the site in 1693, named it \"Vila da Nossa Senhora da Luz dos Pinhais\" (Village of \"Our Lady of the Light\" of the Pines). The name was changed to \"Curitiba\" in 1721. Curitiba officially became a town in 1812, spelling its name as \"Curityba.\" An alternative spelling was \"Coritiba.\" This was used in press and state documents. A state decree in 1919 settled the dispute by adopting \"Curitiba.\"<ref name=autogenerated2/>\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Timeline of Curitiba}}\n[[File:Mapa Curitiba 1894 CR493.jpg|thumb|left|Map of Curitiba in 1894 (Portuguese edition).]]\nAt the end of the 17th century, Curitiba's agriculture was only for subsistence and its main economic activities were mineral extraction.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} Waves of European immigrants arrived after 1850, mainly Poles, Italians, Germans (mostly from Russia) and Ukrainians.<ref name=\"curitiba-parana\"/>\n\nCattlemen drove their herds from [[Rio Grande do Sul]] to the state of [[State of S\u00e3o Paulo|S\u00e3o Paulo]], turning Curitiba into an important intermediate trading post.<ref name=\"pr2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/idioma/ingles/historia|title=History of the City|publisher=Curitiba|accessdate=24 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425122309/http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/idioma/ingles/historia|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Curitiba-view.jpg|thumb|right|Nossa Senhora da Luz Cathedral and Downtown Curitiba in 1900.]]\nThe [[Paranagu\u00e1]]-Curitiba railroad was opened in 1885.<ref name=\"pr2\"/>\n\nAround the beginning of the 20th century, Curitiba benefited from the wealth of the [[yerba mate]] mills. The owners (known as ''\"bar\u00f5es da erva-mate\"'') built mansions in the capital. These have mostly been preserved in the districts of Batel and Alto da Gl\u00f3ria.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/haus/estilo-cultura/as-casas-dos-baroes-curitibanos/|title=Palacetes suntuosos do in\u00edcio do s\u00e9culo foram inspirados em refer\u00eancias trazidas pelos ervateiros de suas viagens \u00e0 Europa|date=2015-11-03|work=[[Gazeta do Povo]]|publisher=grp.com|access-date=2018-05-21|language=pt-BR|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412224516/http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/haus/estilo-cultura/as-casas-dos-baroes-curitibanos/|archive-date=12 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1940s and 1950s, [[Alfred Agache (architect)|Alfred Agache]], co-founder of the French Society for Urban Studies, was hired to produce its first [[city plan]]. It emphasized a \"star\" of [[boulevard]]s, with public amenities downtown, an industrial district and sanitation. It was followed in part, but the plan was too expensive to complete.<ref name=\"agac\">{{cite web |title=The Agache Plan|publisher=Prefeitura Municipal de Curitiba|accessdate=12 August 2008 |url=http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/Paginas/ENG/Default.aspx?idf=532&servico=40}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Climate===\n[[File:AmorMaternoJBCuritiba.JPG|thumb|Fog in the Botanical Garden.]]\nCuritiba has an always humid [[subtropical highland climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Cfb),'' with some characteristics of the [[oceanic climate]] due to its abundant precipitation all year round and the relatively warm, but not hot, summer. The city's mild winters, due to its low latitude, differentiate its climate from typically [[Temperate climate|temperate]] ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=4838&cityname=Curitiba-Parana-Brazil|title=Curitiba, Parana Travel Weather Averages (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase|access-date=2019-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013639/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=4838&cityname=Curitiba-Parana-Brazil|archive-date=1 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It is located on a plateau and the flat terrain with flooded areas<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://multimidia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/2017/00211750.pdf|title=Plano Diretor de Drenagem Urbana de Curitiba. Volume II \u2013 Volume T\u00e9cnico.: Tomo 2 \u2013 Politicas e A\u00e7\u00f5es N\u00e3o Estruturais|year=2012|publisher=City Hall of Curitiba|access-date=31 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013608/http://multimidia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/2017/00211750.pdf|archive-date=1 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://multimidia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/2018/00238308.pdf|title=Plano Diretor de Drenagem Urbana de Curitiba. Volume II \u2013 Volume T\u00e9cnico; Tomo 4: Caracteriza\u00e7\u00f5es e Medidas de Controle Estruturais|year=2012|publisher=City Hall of Curitiba|access-date=31 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013642/http://multimidia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/2018/00238308.pdf|archive-date=1 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> contribute to its mild and damp winter, with an average minimum temperature of {{convert|7|C|F}} in the coldest month, occasionally falling below {{convert|0|C|F}} on the coldest nights. During summertime, the average temperature is around {{convert|25|C|F}} at daytime, but it can get above {{convert|30|C|F}} on the hottest days. Snowfall was experienced in 1889, 1892, 1912, 1928 (two days), 1942, 1955, 1957, 1962, 1975, 1988 and again in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=SYNOP: SUMMARIZED DATA FOR CURITIBA|url=http://www.mundomanz.com/meteo_p/byind?countr=BRASIL&ind=83840&year=2013&month=07&day=24&n_days=3&time=all&l=1&trans=PA&action=display|publisher=Mundomanz|accessdate=25 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712081521/http://www.mundomanz.com/meteo_p/byind?countr=BRASIL&ind=83840&year=2013&month=07&day=24&n_days=3&time=all&l=1&trans=PA&action=display|archive-date=12 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=METAR: Weather History for Curitiba, Brazil|url=http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/SBCT/2013/7/23/DailyHistory.html?theprefset=SHOWMETAR&theprefvalue=1|publisher=Weather Underground|accessdate=25 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202235705/http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/SBCT/2013/7/23/DailyHistory.html?theprefset=SHOWMETAR&theprefvalue=1|archive-date=2 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe terrain's flatness hinders water drainage after rain, therefore providing water vapor for the atmosphere. Cold fronts come year round, often from [[Antarctica]] and Argentina, bringing tropical storms in summer and cold winds in the winter. They can move very quickly, with no more than one day between the start of the southern winds and the start of rain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=75493&t=frente-fria-traz-chuva-ao-parana-e-aumenta-taxas-de-umidade |title=Frente fria traz chuva ao Paran\u00e1 e aumenta taxas de umidade |publisher=Bemparana.com.br |accessdate=7 March 2011 |language=Portuguese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706151735/http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=75493&t=frente-fria-traz-chuva-ao-parana-e-aumenta-taxas-de-umidade |archive-date=6 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Curitiba's weather is also influenced by the dry air masses that dominate Brazil's midwest most of the year, bringing hot and dry weather, sometimes even in winter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.rpc.com.br/gazetadopovo/vidaecidadania/conteudo.phtml?tl=1&id=778839&tit=Inverno-vai-ser-mais-seco-e-mais-frio-que-o-do-ano-passado |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120731124345/http://portal.rpc.com.br/gazetadopovo/vidaecidadania/conteudo.phtml?tl=1&id=778839&tit=Inverno-vai-ser-mais-seco-e-mais-frio-que-o-do-ano-passado |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |title=Winter of Curitiba is dry and cold |publisher=Portal.rpc.com.br |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location = Curitiba (Downtown), elevation: 923.5 m, 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1885\u2013present\n|metric first = yes\n|width = 100%\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 34.3\n|Feb record high C = 34.8\n|Mar record high C = 33.9\n|Apr record high C = 32.6\n|May record high C = 29.4\n|Jun record high C = 28.2\n|Jul record high C = 28.2\n|Aug record high C = 31.6\n|Sep record high C = 33.7\n|Oct record high C = 33.1\n|Nov record high C = 35.2\n|Dec record high C = 33.6\n|year record high C = 35.2\n|Jan high C = 26.8\n|Feb high C = 26.8\n|Mar high C = 26.0\n|Apr high C = 24.0\n|May high C = 20.8\n|Jun high C = 20.1\n|Jul high C = 19.7\n|Aug high C = 21.5\n|Sep high C = 21.4\n|Oct high C = 23.1\n|Nov high C = 25.0\n|Dec high C = 26.2\n|year high C = 23.5\n|Jan mean C = 20.9\n|Feb mean C = 21.0\n|Mar mean C = 20.1\n|Apr mean C = 18.3\n|May mean C = 15.1\n|Jun mean C = 13.9\n|Jul mean C = 13.5\n|Aug mean C = 14.6\n|Sep mean C = 15.3\n|Oct mean C = 17.1\n|Nov mean C = 18.9\n|Dec mean C = 20.2\n|year mean C = 17.4\n|Jan low C = 17.2\n|Feb low C = 17.4\n|Mar low C = 16.5\n|Apr low C = 14.6\n|May low C = 11.2\n|Jun low C = 9.7\n|Jul low C = 9.0\n|Aug low C = 9.6\n|Sep low C = 11.1\n|Oct low C = 13.2\n|Nov low C = 14.9\n|Dec low C = 16.2\n|year low C = 13.4\n|Jan record low C = 8.2\n|Feb record low C = 6.8\n|Mar record low C = 3.9\n|Apr record low C = -4.0\n|May record low C = -2.3\n|Jun record low C = -4.0\n|Jul record low C = -5.2\n|Aug record low C = -5.2\n|Sep record low C = -5.4\n|Oct record low C = -1.5\n|Nov record low C = -0.9\n|Dec record low C = 3.6\n|