dex.php?r=clima%2Fnormaisclimatologicas\n| archive-date = 22 September 2019\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref><ref name=INMET2>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.inmet.gov.br/projetos/rede/pesquisa/\n| title = Banco de Dados Meteorol\u00f3gicos para Ensino e Pesquisa\n| publisher = [[Instituto Nacional de Meteorologia|INMET]]\n| language = Portuguese\n| accessdate = 14 October 2018\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181008145218/http://www.inmet.gov.br/projetos/rede/pesquisa/\n| archive-date = 8 October 2018\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref> Meteo Climat (record highs and lows)<ref name = meteoclimat>\n{{cite web \n| url = http://meteo-climat-bzh.dyndns.org/station-1281-Curitiba.php\n| title = Station Curitiba\n| publisher = Meteo Climat \n|language = French \n| accessdate = 14 October 2018}}</ref> and Weather Atlas (UV index)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weather-atlas.com/en/brazil/curitiba-climate|title=Curitiba, Brazil \u2013 Detailed climate information and monthly weather forecast|last=d.o.o|first=Yu Media Group|website=Weather Atlas|language=en|access-date=2019-06-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627172446/https://www.weather-atlas.com/en/brazil/curitiba-climate|archive-date=27 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Weather box    \n| width        = 100%\n| collapsed    = y \n| open         = \n| metric first = y\n| single line  = y\n| location     = Curitiba ([[Civic Center (Curitiba)|Civic Center]]), elevation: 924 m, 1961\u20131990 normals       \n| Jan mean C  =19.6\n| Feb mean C  =19.9\n| Mar mean C  =19.0\n| Apr mean C  =16.7\n| May mean C  =14.6\n| Jun mean C  =12.2\n| Jul mean C  =12.8\n| Aug mean C  =14.0\n| Sep mean C  =15.0\n| Oct mean C  =16.5\n| Nov mean C  =18.2\n| Dec mean C  =19.3\n| Jan high C  =25.6\n| Feb high C  =25.8\n| Mar high C  =24.9\n| Apr high C  =22.3\n| May high C  =21.1\n| Jun high C  =18.3\n| Jul high C  =19.4\n| Aug high C  =20.9\n| Sep high C  =21.3\n| Oct high C  =22.6\n| Nov high C  =24.5\n| Dec high C  =25.4\n| Jan low C  =15.8\n| Feb low C  =16.3\n| Mar low C  =15.4\n| Apr low C  =12.8\n| May low C  =10.2\n| Jun low C  =7.8\n| Jul low C  =8.1\n| Aug low C  =9.2\n| Sep low C  =10.8\n| Oct low C  =12.5\n| Nov low C  =14.0\n| Dec low C  =15.4\n| precipitation colour  = green       \n| Jan precipitation mm  =165.0\n| Feb precipitation mm  =142.1\n| Mar precipitation mm  =126.6\n| Apr precipitation mm  =90.0\n| May precipitation mm  =99.2\n| Jun precipitation mm  =98.1\n| Jul precipitation mm  =89.0\n| Aug precipitation mm  =74.5\n| Sep precipitation mm  =115.4\n| Oct precipitation mm  =134.2\n| Nov precipitation mm  =123.8\n| Dec precipitation mm  =150.1\n| Jan humidity    =79.0\n| Feb humidity    =80.0\n| Mar humidity    =80.0\n| Apr humidity    =79.0\n| May humidity    =82.0\n| Jun humidity    =76.0\n| Jul humidity    =81.0\n| Aug humidity    =79.0\n| Sep humidity    =82.0\n| Oct humidity    =82.0\n| Nov humidity    =80.0\n| Dec humidity    =82.0\n| Jan sun  =159.8\n| Feb sun  =135.0\n| Mar sun  =142.0\n| Apr sun  =137.2\n| May sun  =152.2\n| Jun sun  =129.7\n| Jul sun  =147.6\n| Aug sun  =148.3\n| Sep sun  =122.1\n| Oct sun  =137.2\n| Nov sun  =152.2\n| Dec sun  =150.9\n| source = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]<ref name = noaa>{{cite web\n| url = ftp://ftp.atdd.noaa.gov/pub/GCOS/WMO-Normals/TABLES/REGIII/BZ/83842.TXT\n| title = Curitiba (83842) \u2013 WMO Weather Station\n| accessdate = 27 December 2018\n| publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]}} [https://archive.org/details/19611990NormalsNOAACuritiba Archived] 27 December 2018, at the [[Wayback Machine]].\n</ref>\n}}\n\n===Vegetation===\n[[File:CuritibaGeadaFrost.jpg|thumb|left|[[Frost]] in Curitiba.]]\n[[File:Estufa-Jardim-Botanico-Curitiba-out.JPG|thumb|Botanical gardens greenhouse in Curitiba]]\nCuritiba is located in the area of the Ombrophilous Mixed Forest (also known as [[Araucaria moist forests]]), a sub-type of the [[Atlantic Forest]]. In Curitiba it is possible to find steppes, forests and other formations. The local vegetation consists of remnants of the Paran\u00e1 (or Brazilian) pine (''[[Araucaria angustifolia]]''), which resisted the efforts of settlers. The Paran\u00e1 pines are in private and public areas and are protected from logging. The Municipal Secretariat of the Environment maintains a [[botanical garden]] and three [[greenhouse]]s that produce 150,000 native and exotic seedlings: 16,000 fruit trees, 260,000 flowers, foliage and underbrush specimens and the maintenance of another 350,000 seedlings.<ref name=\"casecwb\">{{cite web |title= City of Curitiba, Brazil|publisher=Convention on Biological Diversity |accessdate=23 May 2008 |url=http://www.cbd.int/authorities/casestudy/curitiba.}} {{Dead link|date=May 2018}}</ref>\n\nCuritiba's green area itself matches the size of other large Brazilian cities. The vegetation of Curitiba encompasses a large population of purple and yellow ''ip\u00eas'' ([[tabebuia]]s), making a beautiful sight during flowering at winter's end. The yellow ip\u00ea is the city's most common tree.<ref name=\"arvct\">{{cite web |title=Livro mostra roteiros das \u00e1rvores de Curitiba/Pr |publisher=Ambiente Brasil |language=Portuguese |accessdate=25 May 2005 |url=http://www.ambientebrasil.com.br/noticias/index.php3?action=ler&id=18883 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019045953/http://www.ambientebrasil.com.br/noticias/index.php3?action=ler&id=18883 |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Barigui Panorama.JPG|1200px|Panoramic view of Barigui Park.}}\n\n===Hydrography===\n[[File:Rio igua\u00e7u curitiba.jpg|thumb|Igua\u00e7u River, running by the south region of the city.]]\nThe [[drainage basin|catchment area]] of Curitiba consists of rivers and streams that cross the city in different directions, grouped in six river basins. The main rivers that form the city's [[Drainage basin|watershed]] are: Atuba River, Bel\u00e9m River, Barig\u00fci River, Passa\u00fana River, Ribeir\u00e3o dos Padilhas and the [[Igua\u00e7u River]], all with characteristics of [[dendritic drainage]]. Curitiba has been working since the 1970s on alternatives to minimize the negative impacts of [[wikt:urbanization|urbanization]] on rivers. An example is the construction of parks along the rivers with artificial lakes, which absorb and retain water for longer periods of time, minimizing floods.<ref name=\"casecwb\"/>\nAfter many studies of local water flows, most rivers were found to be subject to a [[Canalized|canalization]] process. Other alternatives developed to minimize the negative effects of urbanization are the implementation of programs for environmental education, inspection and monitoring, elaboration and application of legislation and infrastructure works.<ref name=\"casecwb\"/>\n\n===Topography===\n[[File:Curitiba vista serra do mar.jpg|thumb|left|The Mountain Range of the Sea, ''\"Serra do Mar.\"'']]\n\nThe city covers {{convert|432.17|km2|2|abbr=out}} on the First Plateau of Paran\u00e1. Curitiba has a [[topography]] of smooth, rounded hills, giving it a relatively regular shape. The city has an average altitude of {{convert|934.6|m|ft}} above sea level. The highest point is to the north at {{convert|1021|m|ft}}, and with lower altitudes at {{convert|864|m|ft}} to the south. Mountain ranges and sets of rocky hills surround parts of the city, including the ''[[Serra do Mar]]'', a hill range between the shore of the Atlantic Ocean and the First Plateau in Paran\u00e1.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n==Government==\n[[File:Pal\u00e1cio 29 de Mar\u00e7o Curitiba Paran\u00e1 Brasil.jpg|thumb|right|The Curitiba City Hall]]\n{{As of|2017}}, the mayor is Rafael Greca, who replaced Gustavo Fruet. The [[City Council]] of Curitiba has 38 councillors elected since 2004. Curitiba is divided into nine regional governments (equivalent to [[subprefecture]]), who manage the municipality's 75 districts. The ''Rua da Cidadania'' (\"Street of Citizenship\") is the symbol of administrative decentralization; it is a reference point and a meeting place. Several units are annexed to public transport terminals. Their nuclei offer services in the local, [[States of Brazil|state]] and [[Federal republic|federal]] areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zoohara.com/travel-guide-curitiba-parana-state-vacations-government|title=Curitiba, Brazil Travel Guide \u2013 Government \u2013 Zoohara|website=Zoohara.com|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203011834/http://www.zoohara.com/travel-guide-curitiba-parana-state-vacations-government|archive-date=3 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Jaime Lerner]] is perhaps Curitiba's best-known mayor. He has been mayor three times, the first time in the early 1970s. His leadership was crucial to some major changes in the city. Curitiba has built parks instead of canals to reduce flooding; used parks to make the city more liveable; pedestrianised the downtown area; invented and built Bus Rapid Transit (BRT), a bus system that works like a light rail system but is 10 times cheaper; and started a massive recycling scheme that included giving people bus tokens in return for waste.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citiesforpeople.net/cities/curitiba.html|title=Sitemap \u2013 \u30c0\u30dd\u30ad\u30bb\u30c1\u30f3\u3067\u65e9\u6f0f\u6539\u5584\uff01|website=Citiesforpeople.net|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312113008/http://citiesforpeople.net/cities/curitiba.html|archive-date=12 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Time magazine]] listed this former [[mayor]] among the world's most influential thinkers of 2010. In the days before free direct elections, mayors were political appointees who were no more than pawns in the game of power politics and were subject to replacement at any time. For an idealistic young architect like Lerner, retaining the mayor's office was particularly precarious. Those holding the reins of power at the time were under the mistaken impression that Lerner's youth would make him easy to control. As it turned out, he was no [[wikt:milquetoast|milquetoast]], and subsequently set about enthusiastically pursuing reform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cw.com.tw/article.do?action=show&id=13718&offset=0|title=Former Curitiba Mayor Jaime Lerner|website=English.cw.com.tw|accessdate=9 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055505/http://english.cw.com.tw/article.do?action=show&id=13718&offset=0|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Cerimonia de bencao dos alimentos.jpg|thumb|left|Brazilians of [[Ukrainian Brazilian|Ukrainian]] descent celebrating Easter in Curitiba.]]\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | align  = right\n | width = 220\n | footer = \n | image1 = Curitiba - Bosque do Papa - Casa de Colono Polones.jpg\n | caption1 = Old [[Polish Brazilian|Polish]] house at Jo\u00e3o Paulo II park (\"Pope's Park\").\n | image2 = Curitiba Parque Tingui.jpg\n | caption2 = Ukrainian memorial at [[Tingui Park]].\n | image3 = CuritibaPracaDoJapaoCerejeira.JPG\n | caption3 = Memorial of Japanese immigrants at Japan's Square.\n}}\nAccording to the [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics|2010 IBGE Census]], 1,678,965 people resided in the city of Curitiba.<ref>[http://www.censo2010.ibge.gov.br:80/dados_divulgados/index.php?uf=41 2010 IGBE Census]  {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502213333/http://www.censo2010.ibge.gov.br/dados_divulgados/index.php?uf=41 |date=2 May 2012 }} {{in lang|pt}}</ref> The census revealed 1,381,938 [[White Brazilian|White]] people (78.9%), 294,127 [[Pardo]] ([[Multiracial#Brazil|Multiracial]]) people (16.8%), 49,978 [[Afro-Brazilians|Afro-Brazilian]] people (2.9%), 23,138 [[Asian Brazilian|Asian]] people (1.4%), 2,693 [[Indigenous peoples in Brazil|Amerindian]] people (0.2%).<ref name=\"ibge\">[http://www.censo2010.ibge.gov.br/painel/?nivel=mn 2010 IGBE Census] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514145708/http://www.censo2010.ibge.gov.br/painel/?nivel=mn |date=14 May 2012 }} {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Curitiba was Brazil's 8th most populous city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noticias.uol.com.br/cotidiano/2010/11/04/maiores-cidades-do-brasil-crescem-menos-do-que-resto-do-pais-aponta-censo.jhtm|title=Maiores cidades do Brasil crescem menos do que m\u00e9dia nacional, aponta Censo \u2013 Not\u00edcias \u2013 Cotidiano|website=Noticias.uol.com.br|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106193624/http://noticias.uol.com.br/cotidiano/2010/11/04/maiores-cidades-do-brasil-crescem-menos-do-que-resto-do-pais-aponta-censo.jhtm|archive-date=6 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the city had 359,201 opposite-sex couples and 974 [[same-sex couple]]s. The population of Curitiba was 52.3% female and 47.7% male.<ref name=\"ibge\"/>\n\nAs with most of [[Southern Brazil]]'s population, Curitiba is mostly inhabited by European descendants. The first Europeans to arrive were of [[Portuguese Brazilian|Portuguese]] origin, during the 17th century. They [[interracial marriage|intermarried]] with the [[Indigenous peoples in Brazil|native people]] and with the African [[slave]]s.<ref name=\"pr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/pmc/curitiba/index.asp?noframe=sim&conteudo=imigra/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703141121/http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/pmc/curitiba/index.asp?noframe=sim&conteudo=imigra%2Findex.html |archivedate=3 July 2007 |title=Internet Archive Wayback Machine |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=3 July 2007 |accessdate=16 September 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nUp until the 19th century, the inhabitants of the city of Curitiba were natives and mixed-race, Portuguese and Spanish immigrants. In 1808 foreigners were granted the right to ownership of land, and in 1853 Parana became an independpent province, and these events resulted in a substantial number so of immigrants from Europe.<ref name=\"pr2\"/>\n\nThe first non-[[Iberian Peninsula|Iberian]] (Portuguese and Spaniard) immigrants to come to the city were [[German Brazilian|German]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/idioma/ingles/curitibano|title=The 'Curitibano|publisher=Prefeitura de Curitiba|accessdate=19 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323164759/http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/idioma/ingles/curitibano|archive-date=23 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Memorial of Polish Immigration was inaugurated on 13 December 1980, after the visit of [[Pope John Paul II]] in June. Its area is {{convert|46000|m2}} and was part of the former Candles plant. The seven wooden log houses are parts of this memorial area, as a memento of the Polish immigrants' struggles and faith. Objects like an old wagon, pipe of cabbage and a print of the [[Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]] (patron saint of the [[Polish people]]), form parts of the memorial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parques-curitiba.com/bosque-papa-joao-paulo.htm|title=Polish Memorial of Curitiba|publisher=Parques-curitiba.com|accessdate=7 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715044611/http://www.parques-curitiba.com/bosque-papa-joao-paulo.htm|archive-date=15 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> The first group of Poles arrived in Curitiba around 1871. Curitiba has the biggest colony of Polish immigrants in Brazil.\n\n[[Italian Brazilian|Italian immigrants]] started arriving in Brazil in 1875 and in Curitiba in 1878, coming mainly from the [[Veneto]] and [[Trento]] regions of [[Northern Italy]]. They settled mostly in the ''Santa Felicidade'' neighborhood, still a centre of the Italian community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba-parana.net/italianos.htm |title=Imigra\u00e7\u00e3o e Cultura Italiana |publisher=Curitiba-parana.net |accessdate=7 March 2011 |language=Portuguese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501092246/http://www.curitiba-parana.net/italianos.htm |archive-date=1 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNearly 20,000 [[Ukrainians of Brazil|Ukrainian]] immigrants settled there between 1895 and 1897, consisting mostly of peasants from [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galicia]] who emigrated to Brazil to become farmers. Around 300,000 Ukrainian-Brazilians live in Paran\u00e1.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba-parana.net/parques/memorial-ucraniano.htm |title=Ukrainian memorial in the city of Curitiba |publisher=Curitiba-parana.net |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224160856/http://www.curitiba-parana.net/parques/memorial-ucraniano.htm |archive-date=24 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.pr.gov.br/e-parana/pg_etnias.php |title=Paran\u00e1 Government (Ukrainian community in the State) |publisher=.pr.gov.br |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712140342/http://www3.pr.gov.br/e-parana/pg_etnias.php |archivedate=12 July 2010}}</ref> The State of Paran\u00e1 has the largest [[Ukrainians of Brazil|Ukrainian community]] and [[Slavic people|Slavic community]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brasil.kiev.ua/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=45&layout=blog&Itemid=30&9856877558d17ec206d1a87e99fb1dce=3fab537243dff8dbaf45e8c8619a395b |title=Slavic community in Curitiba |publisher=Brasil.kiev.ua |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203110425/http://www.brasil.kiev.ua/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=45&layout=blog&Itemid=30&9856877558d17ec206d1a87e99fb1dce=3fab537243dff8dbaf45e8c8619a395b |archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nCuritiba has a Jewish community<ref>[http://www.jewishbrazil.com/englishsp.htm Jews of Brazil site] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815021641/http://www.jewishbrazil.com/englishsp.htm |date=15 August 2007 }} Source listing Curitiba as one of the important Jewish communities. [https://www.scribd.com/doc/101125/Beis-Moshiach-604 A Habad article] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307025844/https://www.scribd.com/doc/101125/Beis-Moshiach-604 |date=7 March 2016 }} gives the number of 844 religious participating families there in the year 2007{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishbrazil.com/englishsp.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-06-05 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815021641/http://www.jewishbrazil.com/englishsp.htm |archivedate=15 August 2007}}</ref> that was originally established in the 1870s.<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/3512913 Brazil's Jews during the Vargas Era and After] by [[Robert M. Levine]] 1968. This is a book about early Jewish settlers in Brazil</ref> Much of the early Jewish congregation has been assimilated.<ref>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=Steven A.|title=Alternative Routes to the Sustainable City: Austin, Curitiba, and Frankfurt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OnweHjc-zx4C&pg=PA122|year=2007|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-1534-3|page=122}}</ref> In 1937 with the rise of [[Nazi]] Germany, notable German Jewish academics migrated to Brazil, some settling in Curitiba.<ref>A research paper about the [http://www.escholarship.org/editions/view?docId=ft367nb2gm;brand=ucpress Jewish immigration to Brazil] during the second world war.</ref> Physicist [[C\u00e9sar Lattes]] and former mayors [[Jaime Lerner]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heschel.org.il/eng/jgen |title=Jewish in Curitiba |publisher=Heschel.org.il |date=18 April 2007 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017062111/http://www.heschel.org.il/eng/jgen |archivedate=17 October 2010}}</ref> and Saul Raiz were Jewish. A Holocaust memorial is present in the city. The [[Centro Israelita do Paran\u00e1|community centre]], a [[Jewish school]], a [[Chabad house]] (Beit Chabad),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chabadcuritiba.com/ |title=Beit Chabad |publisher=Chabadcuritiba.com |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128222539/http://www.chabadcuritiba.com/ |archive-date=28 January 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> a synagogue,<ref>[http://www.raoulwallenberg.net/?en/about/reports/report-activities-7-2003.1296.htm Israel Synagogue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922145014/http://www.raoulwallenberg.net/?en%2Fabout%2Freports%2Freport-activities-7-2003.1296.htm |date=22 September 2009 }} in addition to the Hevra Kadisha Synagogue and the Habad Synagogue mentioned in the Chabad reference</ref> and two Jewish cemeteries are there,<ref>[http://www.jewishgen.org/Cemetery/southamerica/brazil.html Jewish Genealogy site] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421011042/http://www.jewishgen.org/Cemetery/southamerica/brazil.html |date=21 April 2008 }} lists cemeteries.</ref> one of which was defiled in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tau.ac.il/Anti-Semitism/asw2004/brazil.htm |title=Stephen Roth Institute: Antisemitism And Racism |publisher=Tau.ac.il |date=28 August 2004 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807221758/http://www.tau.ac.il/Anti-Semitism/asw2004/brazil.htm |archivedate=7 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Japanese-Brazilian|Japanese]] immigrants began arriving in 1915, with a larger contingent arriving in 1924. Curitiba received a significant Japanese influx. They settled mostly between Paran\u00e1 and S\u00e3o Paulo state. The city has the second largest Japanese community in Brazil, behind only S\u00e3o Paulo, according to [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics|IBGE]]. Although both cities have around the same proportion of Japanese descendants, other large cities in the countryside, such as Maring\u00e1 and Londrina, have an even higher rate. Some estimates suggest that more than 40,000 Japanese-Brazilians live in Curitiba.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba-parana.net/japao.htm |title=Japan Square in Curitiba |publisher=Curitiba-parana.net |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301095258/http://www.curitiba-parana.net/japao.htm |archive-date=1 March 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n{{further|Economy of Brazil|Tourism in Brazil}}\n[[File:Brasil Telecom Panoramic Tower Curitiba Brasil.jpg|thumb|left|Oi Panoramic Tower.]]\n[[File:CuritibaTradeCenterSkyline.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Downtown Curitiba skyline.]]\nSince it was declared capital of the State of Paran\u00e1 in 1853, the city has gone through several major urban planning projects to avoid uncontrolled growth and thus has become an international role model in dealing with issues including transportation and the environment.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/brazil2014/destination/cities/city=35400/index.html Curitiba Economy \u2013 FIFA report]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505083751/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/brazil2014/destination/cities/city%3D35400/index.html |date=5 May 2010 }}</ref> The city is Brazil's second largest car manufacturer. Its economy is based on industry, commerce and services. For that reason, Curitiba is considered by many investors to be the best location for investment in Brazil.\n\nThe city receives more than two million tourists every year. Most arrive via [[Afonso Pena International Airport]], where almost 60,000 flights land annually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brasilprimedesign.com/eng/lernoticia.asp?cod=56 |title=Curitiba \u2013 Economic ranks |publisher=Brasilprimedesign.com |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708091133/http://www.brasilprimedesign.com/eng/lernoticia.asp?cod=56 |archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAccording to IPEA data, the GDP in 2006 was 32&nbsp;billion [[Brazilian real|reals]], without including agriculture and livestock (0.03%). Industry represented 34.13% and the commerce and service sectors 65.84%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ipardes.gov.br/cadernos/Montapdf.php?Municipio=80000&btOk=ok |title=GDP \u2013 Curitiba |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524004629/http://www.ipardes.gov.br/cadernos/Montapdf.php?Municipio=80000&btOk=ok |archive-date=24 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cidade Industrial de Curitiba, the industrial district, is home to many multinational industries, such as [[Nissan]], [[Renault]], [[Volkswagen]], [[Philip Morris International|Philip Morris]], [[Audi]], [[Volvo]], [[HSBC]], [[Siemens]], [[ExxonMobil]], [[Electrolux]] and [[Kraft Foods]], as well as many well-known national industries, such as [[Sadia]], O Botic\u00e1rio and Positivo Inform\u00e1tica.\n\nCuritiba's infrastructure makes bus travel fast and convenient, effectively creating demand for bus use in the same way that the infrastructure of traditional cities creates demand for private motor vehicles. In July 2001, Curitiba became Brazil's first city to receive the prize \"Pole of Information Technology\", granted by ''InfoExame'' magazine. According to the magazine, the companies of \"Technology and Information Technology\" based in Curitiba in 2001 achieved {{USD|1.2&nbsp;billion}} in revenues, representing a growth of 21% over the previous year.<ref name=\"RTI\">{{cite web|title=A capital do Paran\u00e1 se destaca na \u00e1rea de TI e oferece oportunidades para profissionais do setor.|publisher=Revista TI|language=Portuguese|accessdate=11 October 2003|url=http://www.timaster.com.br/revista/materias%5Cmain_materia.asp?codigo=648|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030912101441/http://www.timaster.com.br/revista/materias/main_materia.asp?codigo=648|archive-date=12 September 2003|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Shopping Estacao 1 Curitiba Brasil.jpg|thumb|right|Esta\u00e7\u00e3o Mall.]]\n\nThe city's 30-year economic growth rate is 7.1%, higher than the national average of 4.2%, and per capita income is 66% higher than the Brazilian average. Between 1975 and 1995, Curitiba's domestic product grew by some 75% more than the entire State of Paran\u00e1, and 48% more than Brazil as a whole. In 1994, tourism generated {{USD|280&nbsp;million}}, 4% of the city's net income. Curitiba has municipal health, education and day care networks, neighborhood libraries shared by schools and citizens and Citizenship Streets, where buildings provide essential public services, sports and cultural facilities near transportation terminals. At the Open University, residents can take courses in subjects such as mechanics, hair styling and environmental protection for a small fee. Policies for job creation and income generation became part of the city's [[strategic planning]] in the 1990s, for the metropolitan area as well as the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hopebuilding.pbworks.com/Brazilian-city-of-Curitiba-may-be-most-livable-city-in-the-world |title=Economy \u2013 City of Curitiba |publisher=Hopebuilding.pbworks.com |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:PacoDaLiberdadeCuritiba1.JPG|thumb|left|The \"Pa\u00e7o Municipal\" built in 1916.]]\n\nSince 1990, the Municipal Housing Fund has provided financial support to housing for lower income populations. After national housing finance collapsed in 1985, just as people from the countryside poured into Curitiba, the city's [[public housing]] program bought one of the few remaining large plots of land, \"Novo Bairro\" (New Neighborhood), as home for 50,000 families. While landowners built the houses themselves, each received a pair of trees and an hour's consultation with an architect to help them develop their plan. COHAB also built Technology Street, an avenue of 24 homes in the centre of Novo Bairro, each built using different construction techniques.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hopebuilding.pbworks.com/Brazilian-city-of-Curitiba-may-be-most-livable-city-in-the-world |title=Housing Program Curitiba |publisher=Hopebuilding.pbworks.com |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nSeven massive shopping malls are found in Curitiba shopping: Mueller, Esta\u00e7\u00e3o, Curitiba, Crystal, Palladium, Patio Batel and Park Barig\u00fci. The [[Rua das Flores]] (Street of Flowers) is home to the majority of stores. The area is pedestrianized, with no cars around the centre. An essential element of Curitiba shopping is the Feira do Largo da Ordem, or Largo da Ordem Street Fair.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba.info/curitiba-shopping.html |title=Shopping in Curitiba, Brazil |publisher=Curitiba.info |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324041831/http://www.curitiba.info/curitiba-shopping.html |archive-date=24 March 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, according to [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics|IBGE]] Curitiba's nominal [[GDP]] was {{BRL|45.7 billion}} (or about of {{USD|22.5 billion}})<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/estatistica/economia/pibmunicipios/2004_2008/ |title=Instituto Brasileiro de Geografia e Estat\u00edstica |publisher=IBGE |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6347Asftj?url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/estatistica/economia/pibmunicipios/2004_2008/ |archive-date=9 November 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> (with {{BRL|25,934}}, or {{USD|13,000}}, by nominal GDP per capita, about of {{USD|5,000}} more than Brazilian 2008 nominal GDP per capita), making it the fourth richest city in the country, after only [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Rio de Janeiro]] and the capital [[Bras\u00edlia]].\n\nCuritiba is the 2nd Pole on Technological Innovation in Brazil, according to IPEA (Applied Economic Research Institute). The\n2nd Brazil's Best City for Business and 5th [[South American]] Best City for Business, according to America Economia Magazine/2005 and 2006. The Best Destination for Business, according to [[Veja Magazine]] of 2007. The 3rd position among the Champions of Infrastructure, [[Exame (magazine)|Exame Magazine]] of 2006. The 2nd Best City to Work in [[Southern Brazil]], according to Voc\u00ea S.A. Magazine of 2005. The 49th Position, MasterCard Worldwide Centers of Commerce: Emerging Markets Index of 2008. One of the highlights according to the survey Offshoring Horizons performed by Watson Wyatt of 2007. One of the 10 global [[sustainability]] centres, according to [[Ethisphere Institute]] of 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agencia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/publico/conteudo.aspx?codigo=82|title=Invest in Curitiba \u2013 Ag\u00eancia Curitiba S/A|website=Agencia.curitiba.pr.gov.br|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701015625/http://www.agencia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/publico/conteudo.aspx?codigo=82|archive-date=1 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Curitiba is also home to the largest cancer hospital in the South of Brazil, [[Erasto Gaertner Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://erastogaertner.com.br/pagina/historico|title=Hospital Erasto Gaertner, Historico Institucional|website=erastogaertner.com.br|accessdate=26 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226211602/https://erastogaertner.com.br/pagina/historico|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Attractions==\n[[File:Curitiba Botanic Garden.jpg|thumb|left|[[Botanical Garden of Curitiba]].]]\n[[File:Bosque de Portugal, Curitiba.JPG|thumb|right|Portugal Park]]\n\nAttractions in the city include:\n*[[Shrine]] of the [[Divine Mercy]]: established by the [[Congregation of Marian Fathers of the Immaculate Conception|Marian Fathers]] near Estrada do Ganchinho in the district of Umbar\u00e1.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://misericordia.org.br/santuario/ |title=Santu\u00e1rio da Divina Miseric\u00f3rdia |access-date=26 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426181342/https://misericordia.org.br/santuario/ |archive-date=26 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Municipal Market: Located near the city's central bus station, it houses numerous shops selling imported goods, organic products, and vegan food. The food court has a lot of Asian food, vegan food and organic meals.\n* Italian Woods: Hosts local celebrations.<ref name=wguide>{{cite web|url=http://www.curitiba.world-guides.com/curitiba_attractions.html|title=Curitiba Tourist Attractions and Sightseeing|work=World Guides|publisher=TravelSmart|accessdate=19 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128060921/http://www.curitiba.world-guides.com/curitiba_attractions.html|archive-date=28 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Wire Opera House: Built on the site of an abandoned quarry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://curitibainenglish.com.br/current-affairs/the-wire-opera-house-curitibas-most-original-theatre/|title=The Wire Opera House: Curitiba\u2019s Most Original Theatre|date=1 November 2010|publisher=Curitiba in English|accessdate=18 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203030834/http://curitibainenglish.com.br/current-affairs/the-wire-opera-house-curitibas-most-original-theatre/|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Oscar Niemeyer Museum]]: Artists from Paran\u00e1 and other parts of Brazil have their work represented in the museum. Three rooms in the Eye are dedicated exclusively to [[photography]].<ref name=\"gobrazil.about.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gobrazil.about.com/od/braziliancities/tp/Top-10-Curitiba-Attractions.htm|title=Curitiba Rocks the Brazilian Winter as a World Cup Host City|website=Gobrazil.about.com|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BlV6Bt5E?url=http://gobrazil.about.com/od/braziliancities/tp/Top-10-Curitiba-Attractions.htm|archive-date=29 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Panoramic Tower: The 360-foot tall lookout tower allows travelers a 360\u00b0 view of Curitiba and has a telephone museum on the ground floor.<ref name=\"gobrazil.about.com\"/>\n* Portugal Wood: Homage to the [[Portuguese-Brazilian]] bonds, this space is highlighted by a track following a small brook, where one can see drawn on tiles excerpts from famous Portuguese language poets, as well as a tribute to the great Portuguese navigators and their discoveries.<ref name=\"gobrazil.about.com\"/> Families are often seen picnicking on the grounds.\n* Curitiba International Ecological Marathon: The Maratona Ecol\u00f3gica Internacional de Curitiba (\"Curitiba International Ecological [[marathon]]\") is held in November and is known as the hardest in Brazil,<ref name=\"meic\">{{cite web|title=Maratona Ecol\u00f3gica de Curitiba \u2013 Ladeiras e incentivos do povo curitibano|publisher=Copacabana Runners|language=Portuguese|accessdate=7 August 2008|url=http://www.copacabanarunners.net/maracur.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080901234414/http://www.copacabanarunners.net/maracur.html|archive-date=1 September 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> because it happens in the end of the year in the summer heat, and because of the hilly course.\n* Tourism Line: The ''Linha Tourismo'' bus stops at key tourist attractions across the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curitiba.world-guides.com/curitiba_travel.html|title=Getting Around, Curitiba Travel, Transport and Car Rental|work=World Guides|publisher=TravelSmart|accessdate=19 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128060932/http://www.curitiba.world-guides.com/curitiba_travel.html|archive-date=28 January 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nMore than 183 universities operate in the state of Paran\u00e1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seruniversitario.com.br|title=Ser Universit\u00e1rio \u2013 Tudo sobre o mundo universit\u00e1rio e estudantil!|website=Seruniversitario.com|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613055510/http://www.seruniversitario.com.br/|archive-date=13 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Universidade Federal do Parana 4 Curitiba Parana.jpg|thumb|right|[[Federal University of Paran\u00e1]] was the first university opened in Brazil.<ref>[http://www.superclickmonografias.com/monografiaufprmonografiaprontaufpr.html UFPR \u2013 History]{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924045847/http://www.superclickmonografias.com/monografiaufprmonografiaprontaufpr.html |date=24 September 2008 }}</ref>]]\n[[File:CPM 1.jpg|thumb|right|Military School of Curitiba.]]\n\n===Tertiary educational institutions===\n* [[Universidade Federal do Paran\u00e1]] (UFPR) \u2013 Federal University of Paran\u00e1 \u2013 This federal university is the largest of Paran\u00e1, with more than 35.000 students. The first university of Brazil;\n* [[Universidade Tecnol\u00f3gica Federal do Paran\u00e1]] (UTFPR) \u2013 Federal Technologic University of Parana is the first university of technology from Brazil;\n* [[Paran\u00e1 Federal Institute of Education, Science and Technology|Instituto Federal de Educa\u00e7\u00e3o, Ci\u00eancia e Tecnologia do Paran\u00e1]] \u2013 Paran\u00e1 Federal Institute of Education, Science and Technology;\n* [[Universidade Positivo]] (UP) \u2013 ''Positivo University'', private institution;\n* [[Universidade Estadual do Paran\u00e1]] (UNESPAR) \u2013 State University of Paran\u00e1, which includes EMBAP (Paran\u00e1 School of Fine Arts);\n* [[Pontif\u00edcia Universidade Cat\u00f3lica do Paran\u00e1]] (PUCPR) \u2013 Pontifical Catholic University of Parana \u2013 A major private university;\n* ESIC Business and Marketing School \u2013 International Website [https://web.archive.org/web/20100918135726/http://www.esic.es/ ESIC]\n* [[Centro Universit\u00e1rio Curitiba]] (UNICURITIBA) \u2013 University Center Curitiba, old Law School of Curitiba.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unicuritiba.edu.br/ |title=Unicuritiba |publisher=Unicuritiba |accessdate=30 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131128050531/http://www.unicuritiba.edu.br/ |archive-date=28 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Centro Universit\u00e1rio Internacional]] (UNINTER)\n* [[Funda\u00e7\u00e3o de Estudos Sociais do Paran\u00e1]] (FESPPR) \u2013 The First Economy Graduation in Paran\u00e1, since 1938\n\n===Educational system===\nIn the 1990s, the city started a project called ''Far\u00f3is do Saber'' (\"Lighthouses of Knowledge\"). These [[lighthouse]]s are free educational centres that include [[library|libraries]], Internet access and other cultural resources. Libraries work with municipal schools, offering a collection of approximately 5000 books, and provide cultural reference and leisure.<ref name=\"ecofanit\">{{cite web|title=CURITIBA, UNA CITT\u00c0 DA FANTASCIENZA |publisher=Eco Fantascienza |language=Italian |accessdate=18 October 2008 |url=http://www.ecofantascienza.it/articoli/curitiba.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501143512/http://www.ecofantascienza.it/articoli/curitiba.html |archivedate=1 May 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAmong Brazilian capitals, Curitiba has the highest literacy rate,<ref name=\"analf\">{{cite web |title=S\u00f3 1% das cidades est\u00e1 livre de analfabetismo|publisher=O Estado de S. Paulo |language=Portuguese|accessdate=23 June 2007 |url=http://www.estado.com.br/editorias/2007/06/20/ger-1.93.7.20070620.3.1.xml}}</ref> and ranks number 1 in education among the Brazilian capitals.<ref name=\"n1\">{{cite web |title=\u00cdndice da Educa\u00e7\u00e3o B\u00e1sica|publisher=Jornal da Globo|language=Portuguese|accessdate=28 April 2007 |url=http://jg.globo.com/JGlobo/0,19125,VTJ0-2742-20070426-278406,00.html}}</ref>\n\n==Urban planning==\n[[File:Rua 24 horas 2 Curitiba Basil.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Entrance of [[Rua 24 Horas|24 Hours Street]].]]\nCuritiba has a planned transportation system, which includes lanes on major streets devoted to a [[bus rapid transit]] system. The buses are split into three sections ([[Bi-articulated bus|bi-articulated]]) and stop at designated elevated tubes, complete with access for disabled riders. Buses charge one price regardless of distance.<ref>Jonas Rabinovitch and Josef Leitman, \"Urban Planning in Curitiba\", ''Scientific American'', vol. 274, no. 3 (March 1996), pp. 46\u201353</ref>\n\nThe city preserves and cares for its green areas, boasting {{convert|51.5|m2|sqft}} of green space per inhabitant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noticias.terra.com.br/ciencia/interna/0,,OI1926962-EI299,00.html|title=Curitiba busca recupera\u00e7\u00e3o de biodiversidade local Terra \u2013 Ambiente|publisher=Noticias.terra.com.br|accessdate=22 July 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606025238/http://noticias.terra.com.br/ciencia/interna/0,,OI1926962-EI299,00.html|archive-date=6 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1940s and 1950s, [[Alfred Agache (architect)|Alfred Agache]], cofounder of the [[French Society for Urban Studies]], was hired to produce the first city plan. It emphasised a star of boulevards, with public amenities downtown, an industrial district and sanitation. The plan was too expensive to complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/Paginas/ENG/Default.aspx?idf=532&servico=40 |title=Prefeitura ENG |publisher=Curitiba.pr.gov.br |accessdate=22 July 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1960s, Curitiba's population had reached 430,000. Some residents feared that the growth in population threatened to damage the character of the city. In 1964, Mayor Ivo Arzua solicited proposals for urban design. Architect [[Jaime Lerner]], who later became mayor, led a team from the [[Universidade Federal do Paran\u00e1]] that suggested strict controls on urban sprawl, reduced traffic in the downtown area, preservation of Curitiba's Historic Sector and a convenient and affordable public transit system.<ref>[http://www.mcachicago.org/massivechange/timelines/urban.pdf About Curitiba] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125170008/http://mcachicago.org/massivechange/timelines/urban.pdf |date=25 November 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThis plan, known as the Curitiba Master Plan, was adopted in 1968. Lerner closed [[Rua XV de Novembro|XV de Novembro St.]] to vehicles, because it had high pedestrian traffic. The plan had a new road design to minimise traffic: the Trinary Road System. This used two one-way streets moving in opposite directions that surround a smaller, two-lane street where the express buses have an exclusive lane. Five of these roads form a star that converges on the city centre. Land farther from these roads is zoned for lower density development, to pull traffic away from the main roads. In a number of areas subject to floods, buildings were condemned and the land became parks.<ref>[http://www.pescacommosca.com.br/noticia/lernoticia.php?IdtNoticia=869 Parks of Curitiba and floods]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012061522/http://www.pescacommosca.com.br/noticia/lernoticia.php?IdtNoticia=869 |date=12 October 2006 }}</ref>\n\nToday, Curitiba is considered one of the world's best examples of urban planning.<ref>Iraz\u00e1bal, Clara Elena (2002) ''Curitiba and Portland: Architecture, City Making, and Urban Governance in the Era of Globalization'', PhD Dissertation in Architecture, University of California, Berkeley, p.112</ref> In June 1996, the chairman of the [[Habitat II]] summit of mayors and urban planners in [[Istanbul]] praised Curitiba as \"the most innovative city in the country.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0104-44782001000100007&script=sci_arttext |title=Curitiba \u2013 urban plannig |doi=10.1590/S0104-44782001000100007 |publisher=Scielo.br |date=31 March 1993 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104201952/http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?pid=S0104-44782001000100007&script=sci_arttext |archive-date=4 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Rua xv curitiba.jpg|thumb|right|180px|15 November Street.]]\nCuritiba was recently recommended by [[UNESCO]] as a model for the reconstruction of the cities of [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"afghjp\">{{cite web |script-title=ja:\u30af\u30ea\u30c1\u30d0\u3082\u30e2\u30c7\u30eb\u306b\uff1d\u30ab\u30d6\u30fc\u30eb\u5fa9\u8208\u8a08\u753b\u306b\u53c2\u52a0 |publisher=Nikkey Shimbun|language=Japanese |accessdate=21 October 2008 |url=http://www.nikkeyshimbun.com.br/020615-24brasil.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041103064150/http://www.nikkeyshimbun.com.br/020615-24brasil.html |archivedate=3 November 2004}}</ref> In the 1980s, the RIT ([[Rede Integrada de Transporte]], ''Integrated Transport Network'') was created.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.urbs.curitiba.pr.gov.br/PORTAL/historiadotransportecoletivo.php |title=RIT Curitiba \u2013 Trajetory |publisher=Urbs.curitiba.pr.gov.br |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706155916/http://www.urbs.curitiba.pr.gov.br/PORTAL/historiadotransportecoletivo.php |archive-date=6 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the same time, the city began building the \"Far\u00f3is de Saber\" (''Lighthouses of Knowledge'') educational centres.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmc.pr.gov.br/ass_det.php?not=7004 |title=Social programs in the city |publisher=Cmc.pr.gov.br |date=16 May 2006 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522092748/http://www.cmc.pr.gov.br/ass_det.php?not=7004 |archive-date=22 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The city has more than {{convert|400|km2|0|abbr=out}} of public parks and forests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenplanetmonitor.net/news/2012/12/curitiba-sustainable-city/|title=Curitiba \u2013 Sustainable City|last=Anil Mundra|date=27 December 2012|publisher=Green Planet Monitor|accessdate=19 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423054904/http://www.greenplanetmonitor.net/news/2012/12/curitiba-sustainable-city/|archive-date=23 April 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the city placed third in a list of \"15 Green Cities\" in the world, according to ''[[Grist (magazine)|Grist]]'' magazine, after [[Reykjav\u00edk]] in Iceland and [[Portland, Oregon]] in the United States. As a result, according to one survey, 99% of Curitibans are happy with their hometown.<ref name=\"grist\">{{cite web|title=15 Green Cities|publisher=Grist|accessdate=10 July 2007|url=http://www.grist.org/article/cities3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627053911/http://www.grist.org/article/cities3/|archive-date=27 June 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJaime Lerner suggests [[Urban Acupuncture|urban acupuncture]] as the future solution for contemporary urban issues; focusing on very narrow pressure points in cities, can create positive ripple effects. Urban \"acupuncture\" reclaims land for the public and emphasizes the importance of community development through small interventions in design of cities.<ref>[http://forum.davidson.edu/anthro16/space/urban-acupuncture/ Urban Acupuncture] \u2013 '' Understanding Space'' 2011  {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425152838/http://forum.davidson.edu/anthro16/space/urban-acupuncture/ |date=25 April 2012 }}</ref> It emphasises pinpoint interventions that can be accomplished quickly to create a make an immediate impact.<ref>[http://www.brazilmax.com/news.cfm/tborigem/pl_south/id/10 Curitiba: Jaime Lerner\u2019s Urban Acupuncture] \u2013 ''Bill Hinchberger, Brazilmax'' 2/2006  {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204151632/http://www.brazilmax.com/news.cfm/tborigem/pl_south/id/10 |date=4 December 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe \"capacity building job line\" was created to accelerate economic development. Key initiatives include the South-Circular bus line, which links the southern and eastern regions of town; Entrepreneurial \"Sheds\", business incubators designed to help small companies get established and prosper; and the Crafts Lyc\u00e9e, which trains people for [[profession]]s such as marketing and finance. Specifically, the goal is to provide jobs and income for the unemployed among 400,000 people living in 15 peripheral towns, and to structure and develop the region according to integrated planning principles. About 15,000 new jobs were generated by 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.iclei.org/localstrategies/summary/curitiba2.html|title=Curitiba a green city|website=3.iclei.org|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100509210814/http://www3.iclei.org/localstrategies/summary/curitiba2.html|archive-date=9 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Jonas Rabinovitch, a United Nations senior adviser and former planner at the ''Curitiba Research and Urban Planning Institute'' (IPPUC), up to 8% of Curitiba's population still lived in [[favelas]] as of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adler|first1=David|title=Story of cities #37: how radical ideas turned Curitiba into Brazil's 'green capital'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2016/may/06/story-of-cities-37-mayor-jaime-lerner-curitiba-brazil-green-capital-global-icon|website=The Guardian|accessdate=2 August 2017|date=6 May 2016|quote=Up to 8% of Curitiba still lives in favelas; it is not a socio-economic island within the Brazilian context.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802134122/https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2016/may/06/story-of-cities-37-mayor-jaime-lerner-curitiba-brazil-green-capital-global-icon|archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> According to 2010 census data collected by [[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics|IBGE]], 49.7 thousand homes in Curitiba form part of irregular settlements.<ref name=\"Gira pelos Bairros\">{{cite web|title=9,3% dos curitibanos moram em favelas \u2013 Giro pelos Bairros|url=http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/blogs/giro-pelos-bairros/93-dos-curitibanos-moram-em-favelas/|website=Giro pelos Bairros|publisher=Gazeta do Povo|accessdate=2 August 2017|language=pt-BR|date=6 September 2012|quote=Em Curitiba, h\u00e1 49,7 mil domic\u00edlios nesta situa\u00e7\u00e3o. Isso \u00e9 equivalente a 163,3 mil pessoas. O crescimento populacional das favelas cresceu 12,4% entre 2000 e 2010, ritmo mais acelerado do que a popula\u00e7\u00e3o como um todo (10,3%).|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827033352/http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/blogs/giro-pelos-bairros/93-dos-curitibanos-moram-em-favelas/|archive-date=27 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> This is equivalent to 163.3 thousand people.<ref name=\"Gira pelos Bairros\"/> The population growth of favelas was 12.4% between 2000 and 2010, higher than the population in general (10.3%).<ref name=\"Gira pelos Bairros\"/>\n\nThe transit service is used by more than 2&nbsp;million people a day. Curitiba has more car owners per capita than anywhere else in Brazil. The population has doubled since 1974, yet auto traffic declined by 30%, and [[atmospheric pollution]] is the lowest in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.iclei.org/localstrategies/summary/curitiba2.html|title=Curitiba \u2013 low pollution|website=3.iclei.org|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100509210814/http://www3.iclei.org/localstrategies/summary/curitiba2.html|archive-date=9 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Curitiba - Feira do Largo da Ordem - Grupo de Chorinho.JPG|thumb|left|Musicians in [[Feirinha do largo da ordem]].]]\nIn January 1973 the Funda\u00e7\u00e3o Cultural de Curitiba was set up, with the aim of promoting culture.<ref name=\"pr2\"/>\n\n[[File:Opera de Arame Interior.jpg|thumb|left|[[Wire Opera House]].]]\n\nThe Cultural Complex Solar do Bar\u00e3o features the Photography Museum, the Engravings Museum and the Posters Museu. The MuMA \u2013 Museu Metropolitano de Arte (Museum of Metropolitan Art) displays artists from the state of Paran\u00e1 as well as renowned Brazilian [[painter]]s such as Pancetti, Guignard and [[Di Cavalcanti]]<ref name=\"pr2\"/>\n\nThe Polish Immigrants Memorial, also known as The Pope's Woods, offers an enjoyable area surrounded by trees, which makes it a perfect choice for a stroll. The Pope himself blessed the first [[replica]] of the traditional Polish houses that beautifully make up the Bosque do Papa when he visited the city in 1980.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn 2003, Curitiba received the \"[[American Capital of Culture]]\" title, granted by the OAS ([[Organization of American States]]).<ref name=\"pr2\"/>\n[[File:Museu de Arte Contempor\u00e2nea do Paran\u00e1 (MAC).jpg|thumb|right|Museum of Contemporary Art of Paran\u00e1.]]\n\n===Arts and entertainment===\nCuritiba was Brazil's first city to have an [[IMAX]] movie theatre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shoppingpalladium.com.br/ |title=Palladium Shopping Center |publisher=Shoppingpalladium.com.br |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226185145/http://shoppingpalladium.com.br/ |archive-date=26 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Curitiba has many theaters. The largest and most important one is the Gua\u00edra Theater.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tguaira.pr.gov.br/ |title=Teatro Gua\u00edra |publisher=Tguaira.pr.gov.br |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225183531/http://www.tguaira.pr.gov.br/ |archive-date=25 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Every year, in April, it hosts the Curitiba Theater Festival.\n\n===Museums===\nBrazilian architect [[Oscar Niemeyer]] designed the extravagant state museum of Curitiba. Its design includes a gravity-defying construction that was intended to look like a [[Araucaria angustifolia|Paran\u00e1 Pine]], one of the city's symbols, but is widely interpreted by locals as an eye, which gave the Museum its nickname \u2013 ''Museu do Olho'', or Museum of the Eye. In keeping with Curitiba's history and culture of science, the museum offers many science exhibitions, including biennial exhibitions. The Curitiba museum includes the Oscar Niemeyer auditorium.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba.info/curitiba-history.html |title=Museums in the city |publisher=Curitiba.info |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101031014126/http://www.curitiba.info/curitiba-history.html |archive-date=31 October 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n* Museu Paranaense (''\"Paranaense Museum\"'') \u2013 dedicated to arts and history;\n* [[Oscar Niemeyer Museum]] \u2013 the largest museum of South America,<ref name=\"MONy\">{{cite web |title=Museu Oscar Niemeyer|publisher=Descubra Curitiba|language=Portuguese|accessdate=17 January 2008 |url=http://www.descubracuritiba.com.br/?s=exposicao&ss=museu&id=584}}</ref> dedicated to plastic arts;\n* Museu de Arte Sacra (''\"Religious Art Museum\"'') \u2013 the focus is Christian art;\n* Museu do Expedicion\u00e1rio (\"''Museum of the Expeditionary\"'') \u2013 dedicated to Brazilian participation in World War II;\n* Museu de Arte Contempor\u00e2nea (''\"Museum of Contemporary Art\"'');\n* Museu da Imagem e do Som (''\"Image and Sound Museum\"'') \u2013 about cinema and photography;\n* Museu Metropolitano de Arte de Curitiba (''\"Metropolitan Museum of Art in Curitiba\"'') \u2013 modern art;\n* Museu de Hist\u00f3ria Natural (''\"Natural History Museum\"'') \u2013 [[biology]] and [[botany]].\n* Museu do Holocausto (''\"Holocaust Museum\"'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museudoholocausto.org.br|title=Campanha Sobrevivente \u2013 Museu do Holocausto de Curitiba|website=Museudoholocausto.org.br|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212063257/http://www.museudoholocausto.org.br/|archive-date=12 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Festivals===\nCuritiba has yearly festivals related to arts, such as Curitiba Theatre Festival<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entretenimento.uol.com.br/ultnot/2011/03/28/20-edicao-do-festival-de-teatro-de-curitiba-comeca-nesta-terca-29.jhtm |title=Festival de Teatro de Curitiba chega a sua 20\u00aa edi\u00e7\u00e3o com mais de 400 pe\u00e7as \u2013 28/03/2011 \u2013 Da Reda\u00e7\u00e3o |publisher=Entretenimento.uol.com.br |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222071352/http://entretenimento.uol.com.br/ultnot/2011/03/28/20-edicao-do-festival-de-teatro-de-curitiba-comeca-nesta-terca-29.jhtm |archive-date=22 February 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and the Music Workshop of Curitiba.<ref>{{cite web |author=Do G1 PR |url=http://g1.globo.com/parana/noticia/2012/01/oficina-de-musica-de-curitiba-inicia-neste-domingo-com-musica-erudita.html |title=G1 \u2013 Oficina de M\u00fasica de Curitiba inicia neste domingo com m\u00fasica erudita \u2013 not\u00edcias em Paran\u00e1 |publisher=G1.globo.com |date=9 January 2012 |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112073032/http://g1.globo.com/parana/noticia/2012/01/oficina-de-musica-de-curitiba-inicia-neste-domingo-com-musica-erudita.html |archive-date=12 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Others celebrate immigrants festivals, such as the Grape Feast (''\"Festa da Uva\"''),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bonde.com.br/?id_bonde=1-33--14-20090107 |title=51\u00aa Festa da Uva de Curitiba \u2013 Gastronomia \u2013 Bonde. O seu portal |publisher=Bonde.com.br |date=6 January 1990 |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509032330/http://www.bonde.com.br/?id_bonde=1-33--14-20090107 |archive-date=9 May 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> which is related to [[Italian Brazilian|Italian]] immigrants, and the four [[Matsuri]], related to [[Japanese Brazilian|Japanese]] immigrants.\n\nThe four Matsuri set in Curitiba are: Imin Matsuri ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u79fb\u6c11\u796d\u308a, \"Immigration Festival\") which celebrates the arrival of Japanese immigrants in Brazil,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parana-online.com.br/editoria/almanaque/news/183378 |title=Governador prestigia Imin Matsuri, tradicional festa da col\u00f4nia japonesa \u2013 Paran\u00e1-Online \u2013 Paranaense como voc\u00ea |publisher=Parana-online.com.br |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205145417/http://www.parana-online.com.br/editoria/almanaque/news/183378/ |archive-date=5 December 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/vidaecidadania/conteudo.phtml?id=778958 |title=Vida e Cidadania |publisher=Gazeta do Povo |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102233559/http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/vidaecidadania/conteudo.phtml?id=778958 |archive-date=2 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Haru Matsuri ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u6625\u796d\u308a, \"Spring Festival\") which celebrates the end of winter and coming of spring,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parana-online.com.br/editoria/almanaque/news/561323 |title=Haru Matsuri comemora chegada da primavera em Curitiba \u2013 Paran\u00e1-Online \u2013 Paranaense como voc\u00ea |publisher=Parana-online.com.br |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205154907/http://www.parana-online.com.br/editoria/almanaque/news/561323/ |archive-date=5 December 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hana Matsuri<ref>{{cite web |author=Tadaima! Curitiba |url=http://www.tadaimacuritiba.com.br/evento-hana-matsuri-2011/ |title=Evento: Hana Matsuri 2011 |publisher=Tadaima! Curitiba |date=25 March 2011 |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031215117/http://www.tadaimacuritiba.com.br/evento-hana-matsuri-2011/ |archive-date=31 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> ([[Japanese language|Japanese]]: \u82b1\u796d\u308a, \"Flower Festival\"), which celebrates the birth of [[Sakyamuni]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturajaponesa.com.br/htm/hanamatsuri.html |title=Hanamatsuri |publisher=Culturajaponesa.com.br |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120408100401/http://culturajaponesa.com.br/htm/hanamatsuri.html |archive-date=8 April 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Seto Matsuri (\"Seto Festival\"), in honor of Cl\u00e1udio Seto,<ref>{{cite web|title=Eventos: Seto Matsuri dias 06 e 07 de novembro|date=15 October 2010|language=Portuguese|publisher=Tadaima \u2013 Cultura Japonesa|author=Myrelle Silva|accessdate=24 January 2012|url=http://www.tadaimacuritiba.com.br/eventos-seto-matsuri-dias-06-e-07-de-novembro|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502031452/http://www.tadaimacuritiba.com.br/eventos-seto-matsuri-dias-06-e-07-de-novembro/|archive-date=2 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> comic artist, precursor of the [[manga]] in Brazil and idealist of the first Matsuri in Curitiba.\n\nCuritiba also hold the famous Psycho Carnival,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://specialparana.com/psycho-carnival-zombie-walk-curitiba|title=Eventos: 2016 Psycho Carnival|date=February 2016|language=Portuguese|access-date=16 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919153533/http://specialparana.com/psycho-carnival-zombie-walk-curitiba/|archive-date=19 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> a three-day festival that happens during the Brazilian Carnival, but devoted to psychobilly and rockabilly genres, attracting people from all over the world. In the same occasion the Zombie Walk also happens. The 2016 edition took more than 20.000 people to the streets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/videos/zombie-walk-leva-20-mil-pessoas-ao-centro-de-curitiba/|title=Eventos: 2016 Zombie Walk|date=February 2016|language=Portuguese|access-date=16 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819181225/http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/videos/zombie-walk-leva-20-mil-pessoas-ao-centro-de-curitiba/|archive-date=19 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===UN Convention on Biodiversity===\nOn 20\u201331 March 2006 the Convention on [[biodiversity]] took place in Pinhais (a city near Curitiba), addressing items of the 1993 [[Convention on Biological Diversity]] adopted by 188 countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cartamaior.com.br/templates/editoriaMostrar.cfm?editoria_id=24&alterarHomeAtual=1 |title=UN Convention on Biodiversity and Biosecurity |publisher=Cartamaior.com.br |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229042526/http://cartamaior.com.br/templates/editoriaMostrar.cfm?editoria_id=24&alterarHomeAtual=1 |archive-date=29 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n[[File:Bus Stops 2 curitiba brasil.jpg|thumb|''Esta\u00e7\u00e3o Tubo Pra\u00e7a Os\u00f3rio'', one of the [[Esta\u00e7\u00e3o Tubo|tube-shaped bus stops in Curitiba]].]]\n[[File:Taxis do Curitiba.jpg|thumb|The orange taxis of Curitiba.]]\n\n===Public transport===\n{{Main|Rede Integrada de Transporte}}\nCuritiba's public transportation consists entirely of buses. It opened the world's first [[bus rapid transit]] (BRT) system, [[Rede Integrada de Transporte]], in 1974.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schneider|first=Keith|title=Putting BRT in Car City, China|url=http://americancity.org/daily/entry/putting-brt-in-car-city-china|newspaper=Next American City|date=23 October 2012|access-date=1 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106120900/http://americancity.org/daily/entry/putting-brt-in-car-city-china|archive-date=6 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The popularity of Curitiba's BRT has effected a [[modal shift]] from automobile travel to bus travel. Based on 1991 traveler survey results, it was estimated that the introduction of the BRT had caused a reduction of about 27&nbsp;million auto trips per year, annually saving about 27&nbsp;million liters of fuel. In particular, 28 percent of BRT riders previously traveled by car. Compared to eight other Brazilian cities of its size, Curitiba uses about 30 percent less fuel per capita, resulting in one of the country's lowest rates of ambient air pollution. Some 1,100 buses make 12,500 trips every day, serving more than 1.3&nbsp;million passengers, 50 times the number from 20 years ago. Eighty percent of travelers use the express or direct bus services. Curitibanos spend only about 10 percent of their income on travel, much below the national average.<ref>{{cite web |last=Goodman |first=Joseph |url=http://www.urbanhabitat.org/node/344 |title=Urban transport of Curitiba |publisher=Urbanhabitat.org |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223215411/http://urbanhabitat.org/node/344 |archive-date=23 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe city government has been planning to introduce an [[metro (rapid transit)|underground metro]] for a number of years and in 2014 announced opened tenders for a 35-year [[public private partnership]] contract to build and operate a {{convert|17.6|km|1|adj=on|abbr=off}}, 14-station north\u2013south line. The cost is estimated at 4.62&nbsp;billion reais.<ref>{{cite web|title=Curitiba re-launches metro concession tender|url=http://www.globalmasstransit.net/archive.php?id=16722|date=8 July 2014|access-date=24 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826133734/http://www.globalmasstransit.net/archive.php?id=16722|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Roads===\nMoving around in a car can be difficult in and around the city centre because of the many one-way streets and frequent traffic jams. The Trinary Road System allows quick access to the city centre for drivers. Some avenues are spacious and laid out in a grid. Apart from some points around the city centre, Munhoz da Rocha Street and Batel Avenue, traffic jams are not severe.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hagah.com.br/mapas |title=Roads in Curitiba |publisher=Hagah.com.br |date=21 February 2011 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609233631/http://www.hagah.com.br/mapas/ |archive-date=9 June 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Air===\n[[File:afonsopenaairport.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of [[Afonso Pena International Airport]].]]\n[[Afonso Pena International Airport]] is Curitiba's main airport. It is located in the nearby city of [[S\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 dos Pinhais]]. All commercial flights operate from this airport.<ref>[http://www.infraero.gov.br/usa/aero_prev_home.php?ai=221 Afonso Pena International Airport] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020001130/http://www.infraero.gov.br/usa/aero_prev_home.php?ai=221 |date=20 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThere is also the [[Bacacheri Airport]], a smaller general aviation facility.\n\n=== Rail ===\nBrazil's transportation and railway company, [[Am\u00e9rica Latina Log\u00edstica|Rumo]], has its headquarters in Curitiba.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pt.all-logistica.com/all/web/default_eni.asp?idioma=1&conta=46|title=Rumo|website=pt.all-logistica.com|access-date=2017-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711010843/http://pt.all-logistica.com/all/web/default_eni.asp?idioma=1&conta=46|archive-date=11 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Serra Verde Express provides a tourist train through scenic country<ref>{{Citation|last=Jim McDaniel|title=Curitiba to Paranagu\u00e1 by Train|date=2010-06-06|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=84KIjcrHYPE|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref> to [[Morretes]] and Paranagu\u00e1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.serraverdeexpress.com.br/site/en/trem/trem-de-luxo-curitiba/|title=Curitiba Luxury Train|website=Serra Verde Express|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414085728/http://www.serraverdeexpress.com.br/site/en/trem/trem-de-luxo-curitiba/|archive-date=2016-04-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nThe city has {{convert|100|km|0|abbr=on}} of bike routes, used by around 30&nbsp;thousand bikers daily. City streets carry almost one million vehicles, of which 2,253 are orange Taxis. To service these vehicles, more than 355 petrol stations serve the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brasilprimedesign.com/eng/lernoticia.asp?cod=56 |title=Curitiba |publisher=Brasilprimedesign.com |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708091133/http://www.brasilprimedesign.com/eng/lernoticia.asp?cod=56 |archivedate=8 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Curitiba public transportation statistics===\nThe average amount of time people spend commuting with public transit in Curitiba, for example to and from work, on a weekday is 72 min. 21% of public transit riders, ride for more than 2 hours every day. The average amount of time people wait at a stop or station for public transit is 17 min, while 33% of riders wait for over 20 minutes on average every day. The average distance people usually ride in a single trip with public transit is 7&nbsp;km, while 12% travel for over 12&nbsp;km in a single direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moovitapp.com/insights/en/Moovit_Insights_Public_Transit_Index_Brazil_Curitiba-942|title=Curitiba Public Transportation Statistics|publisher=Global Public Transit Index by Moovit|accessdate=19 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901063632/https://moovitapp.com/insights/en/Moovit_Insights_Public_Transit_Index_Brazil_Curitiba-942|archive-date=1 September 2017|url-status=live}} [[File:CC-BY_icon.svg|50x50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [[creativecommons:by/4.0/|Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License]].</ref>\n\n==Sports==\n{{Main|2014 FIFA World Cup|Sports in Brazil}}\n[[File:Arenadabaixada2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Arena da Baixada]].]]\nCuritiba have 3 teams in the city, Paran\u00e1 Clube, Coritiba and Athletico. [[Coritiba Foot Ball Club|Coritiba]] plays at [[Est\u00e1dio Major Ant\u00f4nio Couto Pereira]], [[Club Athletico Paranaense]] at [[Arena da Baixada|Est\u00e1dio Joaquim Am\u00e9rico Guimar\u00e3es]]. Both Coritiba and Athl\u00e9tico Paranaense have won [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A]], in 1985 and 2001, respectively. Est\u00e1dio Joaquim Am\u00e9rico Guimar\u00e3es was one of the 12 stadiums to host games of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] held in Brazil. The traditional stadium [[Vila Capanema]] have hosted the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]] which still is home to [[Paran\u00e1 Clube]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba2014.com |title=Curitiba &#124; FIFA World Cup 2014 |publisher=Curitiba2014.com |accessdate=22 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503045915/http://www.curitiba2014.com/ |archive-date=3 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Aut\u00f3dromo Internacional de Curitiba]] (Curitiba International Raceway) is located in nearby [[Pinhais]].\n\nCuritiba has also one of the main [[rugby union]] clubs in Brazil, [[Curitiba Rugby Clube]], national champions in 2014.\n\n==Neighborhoods==\n[[File:Divisao administrativa Curitiba.svg|thumb|180px|Map of Curitiba, with the neighborhoods and boroughs.]]\n:''See also: {{illm|List of bairros of Curitiba|pt|Lista de bairros de Curitiba}}''\n\nMost districts of Curitiba were born of colonial groups, formed by families of European immigrants in the second half of the nineteenth century. The centro (downtown or central business district), where the city was founded, is the most bustling area, housing most of the financial institutions of Curitiba.\n\n''Bairros'' (neighborhoods) of Curitiba define the city's geographical divisions. Administrative powers are not delegated to neighborhoods, although neighborhood associations work to improve their communities.\nCuritiba is divided into 9 regional governments (boroughs) covering the 75 neighborhoods.\n\nCivic Center (In [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''Centro C\u00edvico)'' is where the main government buildings are located. It was the first neighborhood in the municipality of Curitiba, capital of the state of [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]]. The name means 'Center of the Citizen', or with a more direct interpretation, 'center where the subjects related to the citizen are solved'. It was conceived in 1953, with the greater independence which came with the creation of a new state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/idioma/portugues/linhaturismo/centrocivico|title=Centro C\u00edvico \u2013 Prefeitura de Curitiba|last=Curitiba|first=Prefeitura de|website=www.curitiba.pr.gov.br|language=pt-br|access-date=2018-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225225049/http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/idioma/portugues/linhaturismo/centrocivico|archive-date=25 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://partiucuritiba.com/conheca-a-historia-do-centro-civico-de-curitiba/|title=Conhe\u00e7a a Hist\u00f3ria do Centro C\u00edvico de Curitiba|last=Curitiba|first=Partiu|date=2017-05-26|website=Partiu Curitiba|language=pt-BR|access-date=2018-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226035235/http://partiucuritiba.com/conheca-a-historia-do-centro-civico-de-curitiba/|archive-date=26 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2011, the Civic Center was listed as an urban and architectural ensemble. The buildings on the central axis of Avenida C\u00e2ndido de Abreu are protected, including Plaza 19 de Dezembro, Tiradentes State College, Courts of Justice, Accounts and Jury buildings, the Igua\u00e7u Palace, the Oscar Niemeyer Museum and the Square Our Lady of Salette.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/vida-e-cidadania/centro-civico-agora-e-patrimonio-estadual-apmyuk7f0xlhniddhdte8rxou|title=Centro C\u00edvico agora \u00e9 patrim\u00f4nio estadual|website=Gazeta do Povo|language=pt-br|access-date=2018-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226084543/https://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/vida-e-cidadania/centro-civico-agora-e-patrimonio-estadual-apmyuk7f0xlhniddhdte8rxou/|archive-date=26 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Brazil}}\n[[File:Museu Oscar Niemeyer 2 Curitiba Brasil.jpg|thumb|[[Oscar Niemeyer Museum]].]]\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 Sister cities===\nCuritiba is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n*{{flagicon|ISL}} '''[[Akureyri]]''', [[Iceland]]<ref name=\"Akureyri\">{{cite web|url=http://www.icelandreview.com/icelandreview/daily_news/Curitiba_in_Brazil_Adopts_Akureyri_as_Sister_Town_0_403452.news.aspx|title=Curitiba in Brazil Adopts Akureyri as Sister Town|work=Iceland Review Online|date=10 October 2013|accessdate=10 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013225913/http://www.icelandreview.com/icelandreview/daily_news/Curitiba_in_Brazil_Adopts_Akureyri_as_Sister_Town_0_403452.news.aspx|archive-date=13 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|PAR}} '''[[Asunci\u00f3n]]''', [[Paraguay]]<ref name=\"span\">{{cite web|title=Cidades-irm\u00e3s|publisher=C\u00e2mara Municipal de Curitiba|language=Portuguese|accessdate=22 May 2007|url=http://www.cmc.pr.gov.br/ass_det.php?not=7417|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916171455/http://www.cmc.pr.gov.br/ass_det.php?not=7417|archive-date=16 September 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|POR}} '''[[Coimbra]]''', [[Portugal]]<ref name=\"coim\">{{cite web |title=Acordos de Gemina\u00e7\u00e3o |publisher=C\u00e2mara Municipal de Coimbra|language=Portuguese|accessdate=17 February 2008 |url=http://www.cm-coimbra.pt/170.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123100358/http://www.cm-coimbra.pt/170.htm |archivedate=23 January 2008}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|MEX}} '''[[Guadalajara]]''', [[Mexico]]<ref name=\"span\"/><ref name=\"Guadalajara sisters\">{{cite web |url =http://www.guadalajara.gob.mx/dependencias/relacionespublicas/versioningles/sistercities.html |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120302011742/http://www.guadalajara.gob.mx/dependencias/relacionespublicas/versioningles/sistercities.html|archivedate = 2 March 2012  |title = Sister Cities, Public Relations |publisher = Guadalajara municipal government|accessdate = 12 March 2013}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|PRC}} '''[[Hangzhou]]''', [[China]]<ref name=\"span\"/>\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} '''[[Himeji, Hy\u014dgo|Himeji]]''', [[Japan]]<ref name=\"span\"/>\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} '''[[Treviso]]''', [[Italy]]<ref name=\"span\"/>\n*{{flagicon|POL}} '''[[Krak\u00f3w]]''', [[Poland]]<ref name=\"Krak\u00f3w twins\">{{cite web|url=http://www.krakow.pl/otwarty_na_swiat/2531,kat,0,6,miasta_partnerskie.html|title=Krak\u00f3w \u2013 Miasta Bli\u017aniacze|accessdate=10 August 2013|work=Miejska Platforma Internetowa Magiczny Krak\u00f3w|language=Polish|trans-title=Krak\u00f3w \u2013 Twin Cities|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702022307/http://www.krakow.pl/otwarty_na_swiat/2531%2Ckat%2C0%2C6%2Cmiasta_partnerskie.html|archivedate=2 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"krak\">{{cite web |title=Honorowe Miasta Bli\u017aniacze \u2013 Kurytyba (Brazylia) |publisher=Krakow.pl|language=Polish|accessdate=13 January 2006 |url=http://www.krakow.pl/miasto/miasta_partnerskie/?id=honorowe_miasta_blizniacze_01.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221041332/http://www.krakow.pl/miasto/miasta_partnerskie/?id=honorowe_miasta_blizniacze_01.html |archivedate=21 December 2007}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} '''[[Lyon]]''', [[France]]<ref name=\"span\"/>\n*{{flagicon|URU}} '''[[Montevideo]]''', [[Uruguay]]<ref name=\"span\"/>\n*{{flagicon|USA}} '''[[Orlando, Florida]]''', [[United States]]<ref name=\"orla\">{{cite web |title=Online Directory: Florida, USA|publisher=Sister Cities International|accessdate=17 April 2008 |url=http://www.sister-cities.org/icrc/directory/USA/FL |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071218233241/http://www.sister-cities.org/icrc/directory/USA/FL |archivedate=18 December 2007}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|BOL}} '''[[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]]''', [[Bolivia]]<ref name=\"span\"/>\n*{{flagicon|KOR}} '''[[Suwon]]''', [[South Korea]]<ref name=\"span\"/>\n*{{flagicon|USA}} '''[[Columbus, Ohio]]''', [[United States]]\n|}\n\n===Cooperation agreements===\nIn addition Curitiba has cooperation agreements with:\n*{{flagicon|POR}} '''[[Lisbon]]''', [[Portugal]]<ref name=\"Lisbon twinnings 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cm-lisboa.pt/municipio/relacoes-internacionais |title=Acordos de Gemina\u00e7\u00e3o, de Coopera\u00e7\u00e3o e/ou Amizade da Cidade de Lisboa |accessdate=23 August 2013 |work=Camara Municipal de Lisboa |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Lisbon \u2013 Twinning Agreements, Cooperation and Friendship |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031202617/http://www.cm-lisboa.pt/municipio/relacoes-internacionais |archivedate=31 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n[[File:Museu Oscar Niemeyer MON.jpg|thumb|[[Oscar Niemeyer Museum]]]]\n[[File:Alfredo Andersen - Paisagem com Canoa na Margem.jpg|thumb|''Landscape with Canoe on the Margin'' (1922). Painting by Alfredo Andersen ([[S\u00e3o Paulo Museum of Art]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]).]]\n[[File:AraucariasJBCuritiba.JPG|thumb|Arauc\u00e1rias of Botanical Garden.]]\n[[File:Passeio-publico.jpg|thumb|Passeio P\u00fablico.]]\n\n===Architecture===\n\n* [[Jaime Lerner]]\n* [[Jo\u00e3o Batista Vilanova Artigas]]\n\n===Arts===\n\n* [[Alfredo Andersen]] \u2013 Norwegian painter and sculptor<ref>[http://www.masp.art.br/masp2010/acervo_detalheobra.php?id=376 S\u00e3o Paulo Museum of Art] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150618/http://www.masp.art.br/masp2010/acervo_detalheobra.php?id=376 |date=6 July 2011 }}. Retrieved in 25/May/2010.</ref>\n* [[Alexandre Slaviero]] \u2013 actor\n* [[Andrade Muricy]] \u2013 composer and musical and literary critic<ref>[http://www2.academia.org.br/abl/cgi/cgilua.exe/sys/start.htm?from_day=&from_month=&from_year=&infoid=4268&query=advsearch&search_by_authorname=all&search_by_field=tax&search_by_headline=false&search_by_keywords=any&search_by_priority=all&search_by_section=1%2C536%2C2%2C5%2C6%2C7%2C8%2C45%2C693%2C9%2C540%2C10%2C11%2C12%2C13%2C545%2C14%2C467%2C15%2C16%2C618%2C633%2C636%2C653%2C655%2C635%2C637%2C640%2C641%2C644%2C645%2C647%2C638%2C639%2C642%2C643%2C646%2C684%2C685%2C686%2C688%2C689%2C700%2C17%2C537%2C18%2C19%2C20%2C21%2C22%2C23%2C24%2C569%2C649%2C25%2C538%2C26%2C27%2C28%2C573%2C29%2C30%2C31%2C32%2C479%2C480%2C481%2C482%2C483%2C484%2C485%2C486%2C487%2C488%2C489%2C490%2C491%2C492%2C493%2C494%2C33%2C35%2C670%2C676%2C677%2C678%2C681%2C682%2C691%2C692%2C701%2C629%2C630%2C631%2C648%2C652%2C657%2C658%2C659%2C660%2C663%2C596%2C597%2C607%2C598%2C600%2C599%2C601%2C603%2C604%2C605%2C610%2C615%2C558%2C559%2C560%2C561%2C562%2C563%2C446%2C472%2C473%2C474%2C475%2C525%2C447%2C476%2C519%2C477%2C478%2C526%2C448%2C495%2C496%2C520%2C497%2C498%2C499%2C527%2C449%2C500%2C521%2C501%2C502%2C503%2C528%2C450%2C504%2C522%2C505%2C506%2C507%2C529%2C451%2C509%2C510%2C511%2C512%2C513%2C530%2C452%2C515%2C524%2C516%2C517%2C518%2C531%2C34%2C671%2C650%2C602%2C572%2C453%2C550%2C454%2C455%2C543%2C456%2C457%2C458%2C534%2C459%2C36%2C539%2C37%2C38%2C535%2C544%2C39%2C40%2C41%2C42%2C672%2C624%2C593%2C557%2C460%2C461%2C462%2C463%2C464%2C465%2C466%2C43%2C44%2C675%2C679%2C680%2C687%2C695%2C626%2C627%2C628%2C632%2C634%2C651%2C654%2C656%2C662%2C664%2C665%2C667%2C582%2C594%2C595%2C606%2C611%2C612%2C613%2C614%2C617%2C619%2C622%2C623%2C565%2C566%2C567%2C568%2C570%2C571%2C574%2C576%2C577%2C578%2C579%2C580%2C368%2C369%2C370%2C371%2C372%2C548%2C549%2C552%2C553%2C554%2C555%2C556%2C373%2C374%2C375%2C376%2C377%2C378%2C379%2C380%2C381%2C382%2C383%2C384%2C445%2C386%2C387%2C388%2C389%2C390%2C391%2C392%2C393%2C394%2C395%2C396%2C397%2C398%2C399%2C400%2C401%2C402%2C403%2C404%2C405%2C406%2C407%2C408%2C409%2C410%2C411%2C412%2C413%2C414%2C415%2C416%2C417%2C418%2C419%2C420%2C421%2C422%2C423%2C424%2C425%2C426%2C427%2C428%2C429%2C430%2C431%2C432%2C433%2C434%2C435%2C436%2C437%2C438%2C439%2C440%2C441%2C442%2C443%2C444%2C468%2C471%2C470%2C469%2C532%2C533%2C541%2C542%2C575&search_by_state=all&search_text_options=all&sid=531&text=Muricy&to_day=&to_month=&to_year= Brazilian Academy of Letters: ''Essay'' by Eduardo Portela (Portuguese)]. Retrieved on 25 May 2010.</ref>\n* [[Dalton Trevisan]] \u2013 writer\n* [[Dinho Ouro Preto]] \u2013 rock musician \n* [[Em\u00edlio de Meneses]] \u2013 poet and journalist, \"immortal\" of the [[Brazilian Academy of Letters]]<ref>[http://www2.academia.org.br/abl/cgi/cgilua.exe/sys/start.htm?sid=220 Brazilian Academy of Letters (Portuguese)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104202257/http://www2.academia.org.br/abl/cgi/cgilua.exe/sys/start.htm?sid=220 |date=4 January 2012 }}. Retrieved on 25 May 2010.</ref>\n* [[Fernanda Machado]] \u2013 actress\n* [[Florian Essenfelder]], piano maker\n* [[Francisco Lachowski]] \u2013 super model\n* [[Guido Viaro]] \u2013 Italian painter and teacher<ref>[http://www.itaucultural.org.br/aplicExternas/enciclopedia_IC/index.cfm?fuseaction=artistas_biografia&cd_verbete=1970&cd_item=1&cd_idioma=28555 Ita\u00fa Cultural Encyclopedia: ''Viaro, Guido (1897\u20131971)'' ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104202303/http://www.itaucultural.org.br/aplicExternas/enciclopedia_IC/index.cfm?fuseaction=artistas_biografia&cd_verbete=1970&cd_item=1&cd_idioma=28555 |date=4 January 2012 }}. Retrieved on 25 May 2010.</ref>\n* [[Guilherme Weber]] \u2013 actor\n* [[Guta Stresser]] \u2013 actress\n* [[Icarius De Menezes]] \u2013 creative director\n* [[Isabeli Fontana]] \u2013 super model\n* [[Isadora Ribeiro]] \u2013 actress\n* [[Jaime Lerner]] \u2013 architect and urbanist\n* [[Katiuscia Canoro]] \u2013 actress\n* [[Lu\u00eds Melo]] \u2013 actor\n* [[Luiz Carlos Alborghetti]] \u2013 TV host\n* [[Marjorie Estiano]] \u2013 actress and singer\n* [[Paulo Leminski]] \u2013 poet and writer\n* [[Simone Spoladore]] \u2013 actress\n* [[Tasso da Silveira]] \u2013 poet, journalist, deputy and professor<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OmVQe6YnpaAC&pg=PA48&dq=%22hist%C3%B3ria+da+literatura+brasileira%22+%22massaud+moises%22+%22tasso+da+silveira%22&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ei=p4T5TuCSHYm2twfDgp3TAw&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false MOIS\u00c9S, Massaud.''History of Brazilian Literature: Modernism''. 6th Ed. S\u00e3o Paulo: Cultrix, 2001.] Retrieved on 27 December 2011.</ref>\n\n===Aviation===\n* [[Pierre Clostermann]] \u2013 World War II French pilot, engineer\n* [[Egon Albrecht]] \u2013 World War II German flying ace\n\n===Science===\n* [[Alex Kipman]] \u2013 scientist\n* [[C\u00e9sar Lattes]] \u2013 [[physicist]]\n* [[Ned Kock]] \u2013 [[information systems|systems]] scientist\n* [[Newton da Costa]] \u2013 [[mathematician]]\n* [[Ricardo Ramina]] \u2013 physician\n\n===Sports===\n; Football\n* [[Alexandro de Souza]]\n* [[Adriano Correia]]\n* [[Paulo Rink]]\n* [[Thiago Cionek]]\n* Fabiano, the Fabigoal\n\n; Mixed martial arts\n* [[Cristiane Justino|Cristiane \"Cyborg\" Justino]]\n* [[Mauricio \"Shogun\" Rua]]\n* [[Murilo Rua|Murilo \"Ninja\" Rua]]\n* [[Wanderlei Silva]]\n* [[Anderson Silva]]\n; Motorsports\n* [[Augusto Farfus]] \u2013 [[Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|DTM]] driver for [[BMW]]\n* [[Enrique Bernoldi]] \u2013 [[Formula One]] driver \u2013 [[IndyCar Series|IndyCar]] driver\n* [[Raul Boesel]] \u2013 Formula One driver, [[IndyCar Series|IndyCar]] driver, [[1987 World Sportscar Championship season|1987]] [[World Sportscar Championship]] champion\n* [[Ricardo Zonta]] \u2013 Formula One driver, [[1998 FIA GT Championship season|1998]] [[FIA GT Championship]] champion\n\n; Basketball\n* [[Rolando Ferreira]] \u2013 (Gold medalist at the [[1987 Pan American Games]]), former [[Portland Trail Blazers]] player\n; Beach Volleyball\n* [[Emanuel Rego]] (Gold medalist in [[2004 Olympics]], Bronze in [[2008 Olympics]] and Silver in [[2012 Olympics]])\n* [[Agatha Bednarczuk]] (Silver medalist in [[2016 Olympics]])\n; Horse Racing\n* [[Jo\u00e3o Moreira (jockey)|Jo\u00e3o Moreira]] \u2013 Jockey\n; Poker\n* [[Alexandre Gomes]] (WSOP and WPT world champion 2008\u20132009)\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Brazil}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{See also|Timeline of Curitiba#Bibliography|l1=Bibliography of the history of Curitiba}}\n\n==External links==\n{{EB1911 poster|Curityba}}\n {{Sister project links|Curitiba|voy=Curitiba|d=Q4361}}\n\n*{{in lang|pt}} [http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/ Official homepage]\n\n===Tourism===\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Articles Related to Curitiba\n|list  =\n{{Brazil topics|state=expanded}}\n{{Capitals of Brazilian states}}\n}}\n{{American Capital of Culture}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Curitiba| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Planned cities in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1693]]\n[[Category:1693 establishments in the Portuguese Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the plant genus|Curitiba prismatica}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Curitiba\n|settlement_type        = [[Municipalities of Brazil|Municipality]]\n|official_name          = ''Munic\u00edpio de Curitiba''<br>Municipality of Curitiba\n|nickname               = {{lang|pt|Cidade Modelo}} (\"Model City\"); {{lang|pt|Capital Ecol\u00f3gica do Brasil}} (\"Ecological Capital of Brazil\"); {{lang|pt|Cidade Verde}} (\"Green City\"); {{lang|pt|Capital das Arauc\u00e1rias}} (\"Capital of [[Araucaria angustifolia|Araucarias]]\");  {{lang|pt|A Cidade da N\u00e9voa Eterna}} (\"The City of Eternal Fog\")\n|motto                  = {{lang|pt|A Cidade da Gente}} (Our City; The People's City)\n|image_skyline          = Collage Curitiba.png\n|imagesize              = 280px\n|image_caption          = From the top, clockwise: aerial photography of the city; Pa\u00e7o da Liberdade in Pra\u00e7a Generoso Marques; Avenida Palace with the [[Rua XV de Novembro|15th of November Street]]; [[Rua 24 Horas|24 Hour Street]]; [[Oscar Niemeyer Museum]] and [[Botanical Garden of Curitiba|Botanical Garden]].\n|image_flag             = Bandeira de Curitiba.svg\n|flag_link              = Flag of Curitiba\n|image_seal             = Bras\u00e3o de Curitiba.svg\n|image_map              = Brazil Parana Curitiba location map.svg\n|mapsize                = 250px\n|pushpin_map            = Brazil\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n|pushpin_map_caption=Location in Brazil\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Brazil|Region]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[States of Brazil|State]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Brazil}}\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Southern Region, Brazil|South]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[File:Bandeira do Paran\u00e1.svg|border|22px]] [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]]\n|leader_title           = Mayor\n|leader_name            = [[Rafael Greca]] ([[Party of National Mobilization|PMN]])\n|leader_title1          =  <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|leader_title2          =\n|leader_name2           =\n|leader_title3          =\n|leader_name3           =\n|established_title      = Founded\n|established_date       = 29 March 1693\n|established_title2     =  <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2      =\n|established_title3     = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date3      = 1842\n|area_magnitude         =\n|area_total_km2         = 430.9\n|area_total_sq_mi       = 166.4\n|area_land_km2          =\n|area_land_sq_mi        =\n|area_water_km2         =\n|area_water_sq_mi       =\n|area_water_percent     =\n|area_urban_km2         = 319.4\n|area_urban_sq_mi       =\n|area_metro_km2         = 15416.9\n|area_metro_sq_mi       = 5952\n|population_as_of       = 2017\n|population_footnotes   = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://agenciadenoticias.ibge.gov.br/en/agencia-news/2185-news-agency/releases-en/16134-ibge-releases-population-estimates-of-municipalities-for-2017.html|title=IBGE releases population estimates for municipalities in 2017. Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics (IBGE) (August 30, 2017).|publisher=Ibge.gov.br|accessdate=30 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143904/https://agenciadenoticias.ibge.gov.br/en/agencia-news/2185-news-agency/releases-en/16134-ibge-releases-population-estimates-of-municipalities-for-2017.html|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|population_total       =  1,908,359 ([[List of cities in Brazil by population|8th]])\n|population_density_km2 = 4062\n|population_density_sq_mi = 10523\n|population_metro       = 3,400,100 ([[List of cities in Brazil by population|7th]])\n|population_density_metro_km2 = 210.9\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi = 546.2\n|population_urban       =\n|timezone               = [[UTC-3]]\n|utc_offset             = -3\n|coordinates            = {{coord|25|25|S|49|15|W|region:BR|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = 934.6\n|elevation_ft           = 3066.3\n|postal_code_type       = CEP\n|postal_code            = 80000-000 to 82999-999\n|area_code              = +55 (41)\n|website                = [http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/ Curitiba, Paran\u00e1]\n}}\n\n'''Curitiba''' ({{IPA-pt|ku\u027ei\u02c8t\u0283ib\u0250|br}})<ref>The [[European Portuguese]] pronunciation is {{IPA-pt|ku\u027ei\u02c8ti\u03b2\u0250|}}.</ref> is the capital and largest city in the [[States of Brazil|Brazilian state]] of [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]]. The city's population was 1,879,355 {{As of|2015|lc=y}}, making it the [[List of cities in Brazil by population|eighth most populous city in Brazil]] and the largest in Brazil's [[South Region, Brazil|South Region]]. The Curitiba [[Metropolitan area]] comprises 26 [[Municipalities of Brazil|municipalities]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.curitiba-parana.com/geografia-mapas/mapa-regiao-curitiba.htm |title=Mapa da Regi\u00e3o Metropolitana de Curitiba&nbsp;\u2013 Paran\u00e1 |publisher=Curitiba-parana.com |accessdate=22 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070410131340/http://www.curitiba-parana.com/geografia-mapas/mapa-regiao-curitiba.htm |archive-date=10 April 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with a total population of over 3.2&nbsp;million ([[Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics|IBGE]] estimate in 2010),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/estatistica/populacao/censo2010/populacao_por_municipio.shtm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614165617/http://www.ibge.gov.br/home/estatistica/populacao/censo2010/populacao_por_municipio.shtm|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 June 2011|title=IBGE :: Instituto Brasileiro de Geografia e Estat\u00edstica|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> making it the seventh most populous metropolitan area in the country.\n\nThe city sits on a [[plateau]] at {{convert|932|m|ft}} [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]]. It is located west of the seaport of [[Paranagu\u00e1]] and is served by the [[Afonso Pena International Airport|Afonso Pena International]] and [[Bacacheri Airport|Bacacheri]] airports. Curitiba is an important cultural, political, and economic center in [[Latin America]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rnestrangeiros.com.br/#!location/galleryPage|title=Curitiba|website=Rnestrangeiros.com.br|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227011053/http://www.rnestrangeiros.com.br/#!location/galleryPage|archive-date=27 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and hosts the [[Federal University of Paran\u00e1]], established in 1912.\n\nIn the 1700s Curitiba's favorable location between [[cattle]]-breeding countryside and marketplaces led to a successful cattle trade and the city's first major expansion. Later, between 1850 and 1950, it grew due to [[logging]] and [[agricultural expansion]] in Paran\u00e1 State (first [[Araucaria angustifolia]] logging, later [[mate (beverage)|mate]] and [[coffee]] cultivation and in the 1970s wheat, corn and [[soybean]] cultivation). In the 1850s, waves of [[European Brazilian|European immigrants]] arrived in Curitiba, mainly [[German Brazilian|Germans]], [[Italian Brazilian|Italians]], [[Polish Brazilian|Poles]] and [[Ukrainians of Brazil|Ukrainians]], contributing to the city's economic and cultural development.<ref name=\"curitiba-parana\">{{cite web|url=http://www.curitiba-parana.net/tradicoes.htm|title=Tradi\u00e7\u00f5es Culturais|publisher=Curitiba-parana.net|accessdate=7 March 2011|language=portuguese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211165316/http://www.curitiba-parana.net/tradicoes.htm|archive-date=11 February 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Nowadays, only small numbers of immigrants arrive, primarily from [[Middle East]]ern<ref name=\"paimeas\">{{cite web |title=A imigra\u00e7\u00e3o \u00e1rabe mu\u00e7ulmana em Curitiba |publisher=Etni-cidade |language=Portuguese |accessdate=3 October 2008 |url=http://www.etni-cidade.net/2008/a_imigracao_arabe.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205114702/http://www.etni-cidade.net/2008/a_imigracao_arabe.htm |archive-date=5 December 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and other South American countries.\n\nCuritiba's biggest expansion occurred after the 1960s, with innovative [[urban planning]] that allowed the population to grow from some hundreds of thousands to more than a million people.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dados do IBGE sobre Curitiba |publisher=IBGE |language=Portuguese |accessdate=31 July 2011 |url=http://www.ibge.gov.br/cidadesat/painel/painel.php?codmun=410690# |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602180952/http://www.ibge.gov.br/cidadesat/painel/painel.php?codmun=410690 |archive-date=2 June 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Curitiba's economy is based on industry and services and is the fourth largest in [[Economy of Brazil|Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cidades Brasileiras, Curitiba |publisher=SuaPesquisa |language=Portuguese |accessdate=31 July 2011 |url=http://www.suapesquisa.com/cidadesbrasileiras/cidade_curitiba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918054320/http://www.suapesquisa.com/cidadesbrasileiras/cidade_curitiba.htm |archive-date=18 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Economic growth occurred in parallel to a substantial inward flow of Brazilians from other parts of the country, as approximately half of the city's population was not born in Curitiba.<ref name=\"estra\">{{cite web |title=Quase metade de Curitiba \u00e9 dos \"estrangeiros\" |publisher=Bem Paran\u00e1 |language=Portuguese |accessdate=6 August 2008 |url=http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=23799&t=quase-metade-de-curitiba-e-dosestrangeiros |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922092532/http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=23799&t=quase-metade-de-curitiba-e-dosestrangeiros |archive-date=22 September 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCuritiba is one of the few Brazilian cities with a high [[Human Development Index]] (0.856) and in 2010 it was awarded the Global Sustainable City Award, given to cities and municipalities that excel in sustainable urban development.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://globeaward.org/winner-city-2010.html |title=The Brazilian city Curitiba awarded the Globe Sustainable City Award 2010 |publisher=globeforum.com |accessdate=7 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714212832/http://globeaward.org/winner-city-2010.html |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> According to US magazine ''[[Reader's Digest]]'', Curitiba is the best \"Brazilian Big City\" in which to live.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nearshoreamericas.com/brazil-outsourcing-curibita-comes-on-strong-as-silicon-valley-south/ |title=Brazil Outsourcing: Curitiba Comes on Strong as 'Silicon Valley South' |publisher=Nearshore Americas |accessdate=3 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014133919/http://nearshoreamericas.com/brazil-outsourcing-curibita-comes-on-strong-as-silicon-valley-south/ |archive-date=14 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bestcitiestolivein.net/curitiba-brazil-the-best-city-to-live-in-south-america-a-melhor-cidade-do-brasil.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723101730/http://www.bestcitiestolivein.net/curitiba-brazil-the-best-city-to-live-in-south-america-a-melhor-cidade-do-brasil.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 July 2012 |title=Bestcitiestolivein.net |publisher=Bestcitiestolivein.net |accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref> Curitiba's crime rate is considered low by Brazilian standards and the city is considered one of the safest cities in Brazil for youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planetasustentavel.abril.com.br/album/10-capitais-mais-seguras-jovens-brasil-indice-vulnerabilidade-violencia-734424.shtml?&foto=4|title=As 10 capitais mais seguras para os jovens do Brasil|website=Planetasustentavel.abril.com.br|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102042801/http://planetasustentavel.abril.com.br/album/10-capitais-mais-seguras-jovens-brasil-indice-vulnerabilidade-violencia-734424.shtml?&foto=4|archive-date=2 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The city is also regarded as the best in which to invest in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/noticias/economia/20150918/curitiba-eleita-melhor-cidade-brasil-pelo-ranking-istoe-austin-ratings/300248|title=Curitiba \u00e9 eleita a melhor cidade do Brasil pelo ranking Isto\u00e9/Austin Ratings \u2013 ISTO\u00c9 DINHEIRO|date=18 September 2015|website=Istoedinheiro.com.br|accessdate=9 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201145311/https://www.istoedinheiro.com.br/noticias/economia/20150918/curitiba-eleita-melhor-cidade-brasil-pelo-ranking-istoe-austin-ratings/300248|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Curitiba was one of the host cities of the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]], and again for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]. Despite its good social indicators, the city has a higher unemployment rate than other cities in the state.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/economia/pos-e-carreira/por-que-o-mercado-de-trabalho-de-curitiba-ainda-continua-demitindo-868i7lb2m3rmofjytl3yhy1l5 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714193243/https://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/economia/pos-e-carreira/por-que-o-mercado-de-trabalho-de-curitiba-ainda-continua-demitindo-868i7lb2m3rmofjytl3yhy1l5 |archive-date=14 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Name==\n[[File:Curitiba Centro.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial view of Batel and \u00c1gua Verde neighborhoods]]\nOne theory is that the name \"Curitiba\" comes from the [[Tupi language|Tupi]] words ''kur\u00ed tyba'', \"many pine seeds\" due to the large number of pinecones of [[Araucaria angustifolia|Paran\u00e1 pines]] in the region prior to its founding.<ref name=autogenerated2>Fenianos, E. (2003) ''Almanaque Kur'yt'yba'', Curitiba: Univer Cidade, p.6</ref> Another version, also using words from the Tupi language, is that it originates in the combination of ''kurit'' (pine tree) and ''yba'' (large amount).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inf.ufpr.br/sibgrapi2004/site.html |title=Curitiba name origin |publisher=Inf.ufpr.br |date=20 October 2004 |accessdate=7 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706162138/http://www.inf.ufpr.br/sibgrapi2004/site.html |archive-date=6 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Portuguese, who founded a settlement on the site in 1693, named it \"Vila da Nossa Senhora da Luz dos Pinhais\" (Village of \"Our Lady of the Light\" of the Pines). The name was changed to \"Curitiba\" in 1721. Curitiba officially became a town in 1812, spelling its name as \"Curityba.\" An alternative spelling was \"Coritiba.\" This was used in press and state documents. A state decree in 1919 settled the dispute by adopting \"Curitiba.\"<ref name=autogenerated2/>\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Timeline of Curitiba}}\n[[File:Mapa Curitiba 1894 CR493.jpg|thumb|left|Map of Curitiba in 1894 (Portuguese edition).]]\nAt the end of the 17th century, Curitiba's agriculture was only for subsistence and its main economic activities were mineral extraction.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} Waves of European immigrants arrived after 1850, mainly Poles, Italians, Germans (mostly from Russia) and Ukrainians.<ref name=\"curitiba-parana\"/>\n\nCattlemen drove their herds from [[Rio Grande do Sul]] to the state of [[State of S\u00e3o Paulo|S\u00e3o Paulo]], turning Curitiba into an important intermediate trading post.<ref name=\"pr2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/idioma/ingles/historia|title=History of the City|publisher=Curitiba|accessdate=24 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425122309/http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/idioma/ingles/historia|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Curitiba-view.jpg|thumb|right|Nossa Senhora da Luz Cathedral and Downtown Curitiba in 1900.]]\nThe [[Paranagu\u00e1]]-Curitiba railroad was opened in 1885.<ref name=\"pr2\"/>\n\nAround the beginning of the 20th century, Curitiba benefited from the wealth of the [[yerba mate]] mills. The owners (known as ''\"bar\u00f5es da erva-mate\"'') built mansions in the capital. These have mostly been preserved in the districts of Batel and Alto da Gl\u00f3ria.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/haus/estilo-cultura/as-casas-dos-baroes-curitibanos/|title=Palacetes suntuosos do in\u00edcio do s\u00e9culo foram inspirados em refer\u00eancias trazidas pelos ervateiros de suas viagens \u00e0 Europa|date=2015-11-03|work=[[Gazeta do Povo]]|publisher=grp.com|access-date=2018-05-21|language=pt-BR|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170412224516/http://www.gazetadopovo.com.br/haus/estilo-cultura/as-casas-dos-baroes-curitibanos/|archive-date=12 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1940s and 1950s, [[Alfred Agache (architect)|Alfred Agache]], co-founder of the French Society for Urban Studies, was hired to produce its first [[city plan]]. It emphasized a \"star\" of [[boulevard]]s, with public amenities downtown, an industrial district and sanitation. It was followed in part, but the plan was too expensive to complete.<ref name=\"agac\">{{cite web |title=The Agache Plan|publisher=Prefeitura Municipal de Curitiba|accessdate=12 August 2008 |url=http://www.curitiba.pr.gov.br/Paginas/ENG/Default.aspx?idf=532&servico=40}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Climate===\n[[File:AmorMaternoJBCuritiba.JPG|thumb|Fog in the Botanical Garden.]]\nCuritiba has an always humid [[subtropical highland climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Cfb),'' with some characteristics of the [[oceanic climate]] due to its abundant precipitation all year round and the relatively warm, but not hot, summer. The city's mild winters, due to its low latitude, differentiate its climate from typically [[Temperate climate|temperate]] ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=4838&cityname=Curitiba-Parana-Brazil|title=Curitiba, Parana Travel Weather Averages (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase|access-date=2019-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013639/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=4838&cityname=Curitiba-Parana-Brazil|archive-date=1 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It is located on a plateau and the flat terrain with flooded areas<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://multimidia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/2017/00211750.pdf|title=Plano Diretor de Drenagem Urbana de Curitiba. Volume II \u2013 Volume T\u00e9cnico.: Tomo 2 \u2013 Politicas e A\u00e7\u00f5es N\u00e3o Estruturais|year=2012|publisher=City Hall of Curitiba|access-date=31 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013608/http://multimidia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/2017/00211750.pdf|archive-date=1 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://multimidia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/2018/00238308.pdf|title=Plano Diretor de Drenagem Urbana de Curitiba. Volume II \u2013 Volume T\u00e9cnico; Tomo 4: Caracteriza\u00e7\u00f5es e Medidas de Controle Estruturais|year=2012|publisher=City Hall of Curitiba|access-date=31 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013642/http://multimidia.curitiba.pr.gov.br/2018/00238308.pdf|archive-date=1 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> contribute to its mild and damp winter, with an average minimum temperature of {{convert|7|C|F}} in the coldest month, occasionally falling below {{convert|0|C|F}} on the coldest nights. During summertime, the average temperature is around {{convert|25|C|F}} at daytime, but it can get above {{convert|30|C|F}} on the hottest days. Snowfall was experienced in 1889, 1892, 1912, 1928 (two days), 1942, 1955, 1957, 1962, 1975, 1988 and again in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=SYNOP: SUMMARIZED DATA FOR CURITIBA|url=http://www.mundomanz.com/meteo_p/byind?countr=BRASIL&ind=83840&year=2013&month=07&day=24&n_days=3&time=all&l=1&trans=PA&action=display|publisher=Mundomanz|accessdate=25 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712081521/http://www.mundomanz.com/meteo_p/byind?countr=BRASIL&ind=83840&year=2013&month=07&day=24&n_days=3&time=all&l=1&trans=PA&action=display|archive-date=12 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=METAR: Weather History for Curitiba, Brazil|url=http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/SBCT/2013/7/23/DailyHistory.html?theprefset=SHOWMETAR&theprefvalue=1|publisher=Weather Underground|accessdate=25 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202235705/http://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/SBCT/2013/7/23/DailyHistory.html?theprefset=SHOWMETAR&theprefvalue=1|archive-date=2 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe terrain's flatness hinders water drainage after rain, therefore providing water vapor for the atmosphere. Cold fronts come year round, often from [[Antarctica]] and Argentina, bringing tropical storms in summer and cold winds in the winter. They can move very quickly, with no more than one day between the start of the southern winds and the start of rain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=75493&t=frente-fria-traz-chuva-ao-parana-e-aumenta-taxas-de-umidade |title=Frente fria traz chuva ao Paran\u00e1 e aumenta taxas de umidade |publisher=Bemparana.com.br |accessdate=7 March 2011 |language=Portuguese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706151735/http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=75493&t=frente-fria-traz-chuva-ao-parana-e-aumenta-taxas-de-umidade |archive-date=6 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Curitiba's weather is also influenced by the dry air masses that dominate Brazil's midwest most of the year, bringing hot and dry weather, sometimes even in winter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.rpc.com.br/gazetadopovo/vidaecidadania/conteudo.phtml?tl=1&id=778839&tit=Inverno-vai-ser-mais-seco-e-mais-frio-que-o-do-ano-passado |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120731124345/http://portal.rpc.com.br/gazetadopovo/vidaecidadania/conteudo.phtml?tl=1&id=778839&tit=Inverno-vai-ser-mais-seco-e-mais-frio-que-o-do-ano-passado |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |title=Winter of Curitiba is dry and cold |publisher=Portal.rpc.com.br |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location = Curitiba (Downtown), elevation: 923.5 m, 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1885\u2013present\n|metric first = yes\n|width = 100%\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 34.3\n|Feb record high C = 34.8\n|Mar record high C = 33.9\n|Apr record high C = 32.6\n|May record high C = 29.4\n|Jun record high C = 28.2\n|Jul record high C = 28.2\n|Aug record high C = 31.6\n|Sep record high C = 33.7\n|Oct record high C = 33.1\n|Nov record high C = 35.2\n|Dec record high C = 33.6\n|year record high C = 35.2\n|Jan high C = 26.8\n|Feb high C = 26.8\n|Mar high C = 26.0\n|Apr high C = 24.0\n|May high C = 20.8\n|Jun high C = 20.1\n|Jul high C = 19.7\n|Aug high C = 21.5\n|Sep high C = 21.4\n|Oct high C = 23.1\n|Nov high C = 25.0\n|Dec high C = 26.2\n|year high C = 23.5\n|Jan mean C = 20.9\n|Feb mean C = 21.0\n|Mar mean C = 20.1\n|Apr mean C = 18.3\n|May mean C = 15.1\n|Jun mean C = 13.9\n|Jul mean C = 13.5\n|Aug mean C = 14.6\n|Sep mean C = 15.3\n|Oct mean C = 17.1\n|Nov mean C = 18.9\n|Dec mean C = 20.2\n|year mean C = 17.4\n|Jan low C = 17.2\n|Feb low C = 17.4\n|Mar low C = 16.5\n|Apr low C = 14.6\n|May low C = 11.2\n|Jun low C = 9.7\n|Jul low C = 9.0\n|Aug low C = 9.6\n|Sep low C = 11.1\n|Oct 