o e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160132/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado05.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**January 18\u201319, 2006, Bras\u00edlia - Official state visit<ref name=\"PREx06\">[http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado06.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160140/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado06.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**April 25\u201326, 2006, Bras\u00edlia - Presidential meeting with Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva<ref name=\"PREx06\"/>\n*[[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner|Cristina Kirchner]]\n**May 23, 2008, Bras\u00edlia - 1st [[Union of South American Nations|UNASUL]] summit<ref>[http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/ultimas/20-104721-2008-05-23.html Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez participa de la cumbre de Unasur] [[P\u00e1gina/12]]. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n**September 6\u20138, 2008, Bras\u00edlia - Official state visit<ref>[http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado08.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160155/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado08.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**March 20, 2009, [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] - Presidential meeting with Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva<ref>[http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado09.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160217/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado09.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**November 18, 2009, Bras\u00edlia - Presidential meeting with Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva<ref name=\"MREpdf\">[http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/temas/temas-politicos-e-relacoes-bilaterais/america-do-sul/argentina/pdf Cronologia das Rela\u00e7\u00f5es Bilaterais] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716154402/http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/temas/temas-politicos-e-relacoes-bilaterais/america-do-sul/argentina/pdf |date=2011-07-16 }} Minist\u00e9rio das Rela\u00e7\u00f5es Exteriores. Retrieved on 2010-11-20. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref>\n**July 29, 2011, Brasilia, new Argentine embassy opening ceremony \n**December 7, 2012, Brasilia- Presidential meeting with [[Dilma Rousseff|Dilma Rouseff]]\n**July 14\u201316, 2014, [[Fortaleza]], 6th [[BRICS]] Summit\n**July 13\u201316, 2015, Brasilia, 2015 Mercosur Summit\n*[[Mauricio Macri]] \n** January 16, 2019, Official State Visit<ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-16/all-smiles-in-brasilia-as-macri-and-bolsonaro-reset-relationship</ref>\n\n==Diplomacy==\n[[Diplomatic mission]]s:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Of Argentina\n* [[Bras\u00edlia]] (Embassy)\n* [[Porto Alegre]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[Rio de Janeiro]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[Belo Horizonte]] (Consulate)\n* [[Curitiba]] (Consulate)\n* [[Florian\u00f3polis]] (Consulate)\n* [[Foz do Igua\u00e7u]] (Consulate)\n* [[Recife]] (Consulate)\n* [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]] (Consulate)\n* [[Uruguaiana]] (Consulate)\n{{col-2}}\n[[File:Brazilian Embassy Buenos Aires.png|thumb|right|200px|The Brazilian Embassy in Buenos Aires.]]\n;Of Brazil\n* [[Buenos Aires]] (Embassy)\n* [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[Paso de los Libres]] (Vice-Consulate)\n* [[Puerto Iguaz\u00fa]] (Vice-Consulate)\n* [[Bah\u00eda Blanca]] (Honorary Consulate)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Argentine Brazilian]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Argentina]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Brazil]]\n*[[Mercosul]]\n*[[Union of South American Nations]]\n*[[Argentina and Brazil football rivalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090729104552/http://www.brasil.org.ar/ Embassy of Brazil in Buenos Aires]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090803122759/http://www.brasil.embajada-argentina.gov.ar/ Embassy of Argentina in Bras\u00edlia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070607000356/http://www.mre.gov.br/ingles/index.htm Ministry of Foreign Relations of Brazil]\n*[http://www.mrecic.gov.ar/ Ministry of Foreign Relations, International Trade and Cult of Argentina]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080515210104/http://www.abacc.org/ Brazilian-Argentine Agency for Accounting and Control of Nuclear Materials]\n\n{{Foreign relations of Argentina}}\n{{Foreign relations of Brazil}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Argentina-Brazil Relations}}\n[[Category:Argentina\u2013Brazil relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Argentina|Brazil]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Argentine Republic and the Federative Republic of Brazil}}\n{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Argentine\u2013Brazilian|Argentina|Brazil|filetype=svg}}\n[[File:Macri Bolsonaro.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Argentinian President [[Mauricio Macri]] with Brazilian President [[Jair Bolsonaro]] in the [[Pal\u00e1cio do Planalto]], January 2019.]]\n[[File:Iguacu-004.jpg|thumb|220px|The [[Iguazu Falls]] are one of the [[New7Wonders of Nature]] and the largest waterfalls system in the world. The waterfalls are in the [[Argentina\u2013Brazil border|border between Argentina and Brazil]] and are the most significant symbol of the relations of both countries.{{sfn|Dominic Couzens|2008}}]]\n[[Argentina]] and [[Brazil]]'s relationship is both close and historical and encompasses all possible dimensions: [[economy]], [[trade]], [[culture]], [[education]], and [[tourism]].<ref>[http://www.en.argentina.ar/_en/special/C1148-useful-guide-for-brazilians.php Useful Guide for Brazilians] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824225713/http://www.en.argentina.ar/_en/special/C1148-useful-guide-for-brazilians.php |date=2011-08-24 }} Argentina - Official Promotion Portal for Argentina. Retrieved on 2010-11-28.</ref> From war and rivalry to friendship and alliance, this complex relationship has spanned more than two centuries.\n\n[[Rio de Janeiro]] was the first capital to recognize Argentinian independence, whereas Buenos Aires\u2019 was the first government to recognize Brazil\u2019s independence.<ref> http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/images/ficha_pais/artigo-argentina.pdf Argentina, primeiro pa\u00eds a reconhecer a independ\u00eancia do Brasil - Rodrigo Wiese Randig</ref> After achieving independence from the [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberian]] crowns in the early nineteenth century, [[Argentina]] and [[Brazil]] inherited a series of unresolved territorial disputes from their colonial powers. The most serious breach in the relationship was the [[Cisplatine War]] (1825&ndash;1828), led by the Brazilian invasion and annexation of the [[Banda Oriental]]. Despite the numerous periods of muted hostility, the Argentine\u2013Brazilian relationship was not defined by open hostility for most of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. There was competition on many levels, and their respective defense policies reflected mutual suspicion, but the Brazilian economic rise in the 1980s led to the accommodation of Argentina as a secondary regional power and increasing cooperation.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/12944490/Unveiling_the_South_American_Balance]</ref>\n\nWith the creation of the [[Brazilian\u2013Argentine Agency for Accounting and Control of Nuclear Materials]] in 1991, the two countries turned their nuclear competition into cooperation through mutual confidence.<ref>[http://www.carnegieendowment.org/publications/index.cfm?fa=view&id=22597 Brazil and Argentina's Nuclear Cooperation] Carnegie Endowment. Retrieved on 2010-11-28.</ref> A high volume of trade and migration between Argentina and Brazil has generated closer ties, especially after the implementation of [[Mercosur]] in 1991.<ref name=\"Rudderless\">[http://www.fas.org/irp/world/argentina/rudderless.pdf Argentina: Rudderless] Lugar, Richard G. Report: Committee on Foreign Relations of the United States Senate. Retrieved on 2010-11-28.</ref> Today, the strategic relationship between Argentina and Brazil is considered to be \"at the highest point in history\".<ref>[http://english.telam.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10673:qno-journalistic-speculation-can-tarnish-the-strategic-relation-between-argentina-and-brazil&catid=42:politics No journalistic speculation can tarnish the strategic relation between Argentina and Brazil] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706082659/http://english.telam.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10673%3Aqno-journalistic-speculation-can-tarnish-the-strategic-relation-between-argentina-and-brazil&catid=42%3Apolitics |date=2011-07-06 }} Telam. Retrieved on 2010-11-28.</ref> Argentine foreign policy has given special emphasis in \"deepening the [[strategic alliance]] with Brazil in all its aspects\".<ref>[http://www.mrecic.gov.ar/portal/seree/home.html Secretar\u00eda de Relaciones Exteriores - Objetivos estrat\u00e9gicos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127022342/http://mrecic.gov.ar/portal/seree/home.html |date=2010-11-27 }} Secretar\u00eda de Relaciones Exteriores. Retrieved on 2010-11-29. {{in lang|es}}.</ref> Likewise, Argentina has been \"an absolute priority\" for Brazilian [[foreign policy]].<ref>[http://english.telam.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10497:relationship-with-argentina-shall-be-a-priority-for-rousseff-said-brazilian-foreign-minister-&catid=42:politics Relationship with Argentina shall be a priority for Rousseff, said Brazilian Foreign Minister] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706082708/http://english.telam.com.ar/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10497%3Arelationship-with-argentina-shall-be-a-priority-for-rousseff-said-brazilian-foreign-minister-&catid=42%3Apolitics |date=2011-07-06 }} Telam. Retrieved on 2010-11-28.</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nArgentina and Brazil are neighbouring countries of South America, and two of the most important economies in South America. The two countries combined represent 63% of the total area of South America, 60% of its population and 61% of its [[Gross domestic product|GDP]].<ref>[http://www.planalto.gov.br/gsi/saei/paginas/evento_brasil_e_argentina.pdf Brasil-Argentina: uma rela\u00e7\u00e3o estrat\u00e9gica] Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica Federativa do Brasil. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Independence and consolidation===\n{{See also|Spanish American wars of independence|Brazilian Independence}}\nArgentina and Brazil share the [[R\u00edo de la Plata]] [[La Plata Basin|basin]]\u2013 an area where Portuguese and Spanish [[conquistadors]] collided in their ambition to conquer new land for their respective crowns. After achieving independence from the [[Iberians|Iberian]] crowns in the early nineteenth century, the Argentine Republic and the [[Brazilian Empire]] inherited a series of unresolved territorial disputes from their colonial powers, involving [[Paraguay]] and [[Uruguay]], the other two nations of the R\u00edo de la Plata basin.\n[[File:Juncal MuratureJose 1865.png|thumb|left|250px|The battle of Juncal, during the [[Cisplatine War]].]]\n\nIt was during this time that the [[Cisplatine War]], the first armed conflict between both countries, started. From 1825 to 1828 the forces of the [[United Provinces of the R\u00edo de la Plata]] outfought those of the Brazilian Empire, until the signing of the [[1828 Treaty of Montevideo|Treaty of Montevideo]] that gave independence to Uruguay from both countries. Given the high cost of the war for both sides and the burdens it imposed on trade between the United Provinces and the United Kingdom, the latter pressed the two belligerent parties to engage in peace negotiations in Rio de Janeiro. Under British and French mediation, the United Provinces of River Plate and the Empire of Brazil signed the 1828 Treaty of Montevideo, which acknowledged the independence of the Cisplatine Province under the name Eastern Republic of Uruguay. Troops of both countries would face each other once again later, during the [[Platine War]], when a coalition of Brazil, Uruguay and Argentine rebels managed to defeat Rosas (helped in turn by Uruguayan rebels led by [[Manuel Oribe]]). Another war almost happened during the 1870s when Brazil refused to accept Argentina's desire to take all the Chaco region for itself after the end of the [[Paraguayan War]] (also known as the War of the Triple Alliance) when both countries were allies against Paraguay.\n\nBrazil did not settle disputes with Argentina over its precise national boundaries until the early twentieth century. It had settled with Uruguay in 1851, with Peru in 1851 and 1874, with Colombia in 1853, with Venezuela in 1859, with Bolivia in 1867 and with Paraguay in 1872,<ref>Vainfas, Ronaldo. Dicion\u00e1rio do Brasil Imperial. Rio de Janeiro: Objetiva, 2002, p. 302</ref> but not with Argentina, Guyana, French Guyana and Suriname. However, it had consolidated most of its vast territory under a single authority by the middle of the nineteenth century, achieved as the result of the work of the empire's political [[elite]].\nIn contrast, the Argentine Republic's nineteenth century experience was marked by infighting between contending factions\u2014those favoring a [[Federales (Argentina)|federalist]] republic\u2014struggling against the strong centralist tendencies of the city of [[Buenos Aires]] ([[Unitarian Party|Unitarians]]). Argentina's unification and territorial consolidation under a single authority was completed by the 1880s.\n\n===Consolidated states===\n[[Image:Alegor\u00eda Brasil y Argentina.jpg|thumb|200px|This 1890 allegoric drawing depicts the friendship between the Argentine Republic and the newly formed Brazilian Republic.]]\nDespite this inheritance of unresolved territorial disputes and numerous periods of muted hostility, the Argentine\u2013Brazilian relationship was not defined by open hostility for most of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. There was competition on many levels, and their respective defense policies reflected mutual suspicion, but their [[bilateralism|bilateral relationship]] was not adversarial. After the mid-1850s, neither country resorted to coercion or the use of force to resolve territorial disputes, and during the only general war that took place in the Plata region\u2013 the [[Paraguayan War]] (1864\u20131870)\u2013 Argentina and Brazil were allied against Paraguay.\n\nNonetheless, at later part of 19th century, concerns from Argentina over Brazil's possible imperialistic ambition remained, as well as Brazil's close commercial tie with [[Chile]], the rival of Argentina. Fear from possible Brazilian intervention in support for Chile amidst the [[War of the Pacific]] had led to Argentina maintaining status quo with Brazil.\n\n===Twentieth Century===\n{{see also|South American dreadnought race}}\n[[Image:Campos Salles, General Julio Roca e o Bar\u00e3o do Rio Branco em viagem \u00e0 Petr\u00f3polis, 1907.jpg|thumb|200px|Visit of the President of Argentina, General [[Julio Argentino Roca]], Brazil, March, 1907.]]\n\nIn Brazil, the liberal revolution of 1930 overthrew the oligarchic coffee plantation owners and brought to power an urban middle class that and business interests that promoted industrialization and modernization.  Aggressive promotion of new industry turned around the economy by 1933.  Brazil's leaders in the 1920s and 1930s decided that Argentina's implicit foreign policy goal was to isolate Portuguese-speaking Brazil from Spanish-speaking neighbors, thus facilitating the expansion of Argentine economic and political influence in South America.  Even worse, was the fear that a more powerful Argentine Army would launch a surprise attack on the weaker Brazilian Army. To counter this threat, President [[Get\u00falio Vargas]] forged closer links with the United States. Meanwhile, Argentina moved in the opposite direction. During World War II, Brazil was a staunch ally of the United States and sent its military to Europe. The United States provided over $100 million in [[Lend-Lease]] grants, in return for free rent on air bases used to transport American soldiers and supplies across the Atlantic, and naval bases for anti-submarine operations.  In sharp contrast, Argentina was officially neutral and at times favored Germany.<ref>Stanley E. Hilton, \"The Argentine Factor in Twentieth-Century Brazilian Foreign Policy Strategy.\" ''Political Science Quarterly'' 100.1 (1985): 27-51.</ref><ref>Stanley E. Hilton, \"Brazilian Diplomacy and the Washington-Rio de Janeiro 'Axis' during the World War II Era,\" ''Hispanic American Historical Review'' (1979) 59#2 pp. 201-231 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2514412 in JSTOR]</ref>\n\nCommunication and physical integration between the two neighbors was limited. The benefits of developing closer economic, political, and cultural relations were not considered until late in the 20th century.\n \nSince 1945, the most acrimonious bilateral dispute concerned the control of water resources along the [[Paran\u00e1 River|Alto Paran\u00e1]] basin. In 1966, Brazil and Paraguay concluded the ''Igua\u00e7u Act'', announcing their intention to build a Brazilian\u2013Paraguayan [[hydroelectric plant]], [[Itaip\u00fa dam]], on the Paran\u00e1 River, on the Argentina\u2013Brazil\u2013Paraguay border. The [[Treaty of Itaip\u00fa]] was signed in [[Bras\u00edlia]] in 1973. However, Buenos Aires feared that Brazil's project would hinder its own plans for the water resources development in the area. For almost a decade, the dispute soured bilateral relations and hampered efforts to forge closer economic and political links.\n<!-- missing military governments, [[Operation Condor]] -->\n\nThe dispute over water resources was finally resolved by intense diplomatic negotiations. In October 1979, the Itaip\u00fa\u2013Corpus Multilateral Treaty on Technical Cooperation was concluded, ending the dispute to the satisfaction of all three neighbors and opening the way for a dramatic improvement in relations. After the conclusion of the Itaipu\u2013Corpus Treaty, Brazilian president [[Jo\u00e3o Figueiredo]] visited Argentina, the first Brazilian leader to do so in more than four decades.\n\nFigueiredo, the last president of the military rulers who had governed Brazil for 21 years, visited Buenos Aires in May 1980 and signed, among other agreements, a series of accords to collaborate on [[Nuclear power|nuclear]] issues. Reflecting their shared opposition to the [[Nuclear proliferation|nuclear non-proliferation]] regime, Argentina and Brazil agreed to co-operate and exchange technical information, materials, and products on all aspects of the nuclear fuel cycle.\n\nFollowing the resolution of the water resources dispute and the Brazilian president's successful visit, an unexpected and traumatic event took place in Argentina that further improved bilateral relations: the 1982 [[Falklands War]].\n\n====Falklands War====\n\nThree years after calling off the [[Operation Soberania]] in order to invade the [[Beagle Channel cartography since 1881|Picton, Nueva and Lennox]] islands, Argentina invaded the [[Falkland Islands]] ({{lang-es|Islas Malvinas|links=no}}) in April 1982, starting a brief but important war with the United Kingdom. Brazil supported the Argentine claim over the Falkland Islands:\n{{quote|After reviewing the issue regarding the Falkland Islands, His Excellency the President of the Federative Republic of Brazil expressed the support of his Government to the Argentine Republic, reaffirming his belief that the negotiations in progress will yield satisfactory results within a brief amount of time.|[[Ministry of External Relations (Brazil)|Ministry of External Relations of Brazil]]<ref>[[Ministry of External Relations (Brazil)|Ministry of External Relations]]. Resenha de Pol\u00edtica Exterior do Brasil, n\u00ba 25, 1980, p. 54 [http://www4.fapa.com.br/monographia/artigos/2edicao/artigo10mg2.pdf As Rela\u00e7\u00f5es Brasil-Argentina Durante o Governo Figueiredo (1979-1985): as etapas de um projeto necess\u00e1rio (p.157)] {{in lang|pt}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Image:Argentine S-2 Tracker crew aboard Brazilian carrier Sao Paulo 2003.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The crew of an Argentine Navy Grumman S-2 Tracker aboard the Brazilian aircraft carrier S\u00e3o Paulo (A12), in 2003.]]\nOn June 3, 1982, a British [[Avro Vulcan|Vulcan]] diverted to an emergency landing in Brazil when its in-flight refueling probe broke en route to [[Ascension Island]] after bombing Argentine positions in the Falkland Islands. The crew sent a \"Mayday\" signal, jettisoned classified documents, and attempted to ditch its missile armament, but all bar one malfunctioned and remained on the pylons. The Vulcan was intercepted by Brazilian [[Northrop F-5|F-5 Tiger II]] jets and escorted to the [[Gale\u00e3o Air Force Base]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], where the crew and aircraft were interned.<ref>[http://www.users.zetnet.co.uk/mongsoft/black_buck_page.htm Operation Black Buck]</ref><ref>[http://www.ibge.gov.br/ibgeteen/datas/fab/aeronaves.html F-5 Tiger II] IBGE.gov.br. Retrieved on 2010-11-20 {{in lang|pt}}.</ref><ref name =\"Vulcan\">[http://www.users.zetnet.co.uk/mongsoft/images/Brazil4.jpg Um Vulcan ingl\u00eas apanhado na rede do Cindacta] Veja: June 09, 1982. Retrieved on 2010-11-20. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref> After diplomatic negotiations with the United Kingdom, the aircraft and crew were released on June 11. However, the remaining [[Sidewinder missile|Sidewinder]] and [[AGM-45 Shrike]] missiles on board the aircraft were confiscated by the Brazilian authorities.\nAfter hostilities ended in June 1982, Buenos Aires chose Brazil to [[protecting power|represent its interests]] in London until full [[diplomatic relations]] with United Kingdom were restored in 1990. Thus, despite rivalry and historical suspicions, Brazil's actions and policies during the most traumatic period of Argentina's recent history\u2014objectionable military rule, near-conflict with Chile and the Falklands War\u2014were fundamental to build trust between the two countries.\n\n[[File:Argentina-Brazil border.jpg|thumb|200px|International border between Argentina (Puerto Iguaz\u00fa) and Brazil (Foz do Igua\u00e7\u00fa)]]\nArgentina's defeat in the war against Britain hastened the end of its domestic military rule. General elections were held in October 1983, and President [[Raul Alfons\u00edn]] was elected with a mandate to ensure that Argentina's recent past was not repeated. Among his main achievements, President Alfons\u00edn started to resolve the enduring territorial conflict with Chile during his six-year term, and significantly improved relations with Brazil.\n\nArgentina's intention to forge a closer relationship with Brazil was matched by Brazil's intention to do the same. While still under [[dictatorship|military rule]], Brazil initiated a policy of improving relations with its South American neighbors, and Argentina was considered the key country in this effort. The initiative was accelerated after 1985 when [[Jos\u00e9 Sarney]], became the first civilian president of Brazil since 1964. Soon after taking power, President Sarney met with President Alfons\u00edn, and thereafter a series of diplomatic initiatives and presidential visits took place. The aim of these exchanges was to deepen the process of cultural, political, and economic rapprochement between Argentina and Brazil.\n\n====Democratization (1985)====\n\nAfter democratization, a strong integration and partnership began between the two countries. In 1985 they signed the basis for the [[Mercosur]], a regional [[trade pact|trade agreement]].\n\nIn the field of science, the two regional giants had been rivals since the 1950s when both governments launched parallel nuclear and space programs, however, several agreements were signed since then such as the creation of the [[Brazilian-Argentine Agency for Accounting and Control of Nuclear Materials]] (ABACC) to verify both countries' pledges to use nuclear energy only for peaceful purposes.\n\nAlso on the military side there has been greater rapprochement. In accordance with the friendship policy, both armies dissolved or moved major units previously located at their common border  (e.g. [[Argentine Army|Argentine]]'s 7th Jungle and 3rd Motorized Infantry Brigades). Brazilian soldiers are embedded in the Argentine [[peacekeeping]] contingent at [[UNFICYP]] in [[Cyprus]] and they are working together at [[MINUSTAH]] in [[Haiti]] and, as another example of collaboration, [[Argentine Navy]] aircraft routinely operates from the [[Brazilian Navy]] carrier [[NAe S\u00e3o Paulo]].\n\n===Recent years===\n[[File:Dilma Rousseff e Cristina Kirchner em 2015.jpg|left|thumb|295x295px|Former [[President of Brazil]], [[Dilma Rousseff|Dilma Rouseff]], and former [[President of Argentina|Argentine president]] [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner|Cristina Kirchner]], in 2015]]\nThe [[N\u00e9stor Kirchner]] administration placed Brazil as a foreign policy priority and relations with Brazil were considered strategic.<ref name=\"Vadell\">[http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/358/35849111.pdf A Pol\u00edtica Internacional, a Conjuntura Econ\u00f4mica e a Argentina de N\u00e9stor Kirchner] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923061406/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/pdf/358/35849111.pdf |date=2012-09-23 }} Vadell, Javier Alberto. Revista Brasileira de Pol\u00edtica Internacional. p. 204-211. Retrieved on 2010-11-30. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref> This was met with reciprocity in Brazil, as [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva|Lula da Silva]] placed Argentina as the main priority of his foreign policy.<ref name=\"Moraes\" /> The first foreign visit of Lula da Silva, as president-elect, was to Argentina in December 2002.<ref name=\"Moraes\">[http://www.lume.ufrgs.br/bitstream/handle/10183/25894/000755381.pdf A Coopera\u00e7\u00e3o Brasil-Argentina na \u00e1rea militar: da autonomia das For\u00e7as Armadas \u00e0s rela\u00e7\u00f5es estrat\u00e9gicas (1978-2009)] Moraes, Rodrigo Fracalossi. UFRS. Retrieved on 2010-11-30. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref> From the Brazilian perspective, only with this [[strategic alliance]] would it be possible to transform South America into a [[Polarity in international relations|world power bloc]], one of the goals of Lula da Silva's foreign policy.<ref name=\"Cervo\">[http://www.scielo.br/pdf/rbpi/v46n1/a01v46n1.pdf A pol\u00edtica exterior: de Cardoso a Lula] Cervo, Amado Luiz. Revista Brasileira de Pol\u00edtica Internacional. Retrieved on 2010-11-30. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref>\n\nSince 2003, Argentina and Brazil have coordinated their positions in the [[Intergovernmental organization|multilateral fora]], as can be seen by their joint participation in the agricultural negotiations at the [[World Trade Organization Ministerial Conference of 2003|WTO meeting]] in [[Canc\u00fan]], their joint position in regards to the creation of the [[Free Trade Area of the Americas]], and their articulation at the [[G-20 major economies|G-20]] to reform the [[Global financial system|international financial system]].<ref name=\"Moraes\" /> The creation of the [[Union of South American Nations]], in 2008, was a landmark in the new foreign policies of Brazil and Argentina.<ref name=\"Moraes\" /> In another sign of mutual trust, since 2003, diplomats from both countries occupy a single seat in the [[United Nations Security Council]] when either of them hold a [[List of members of the United Nations Security Council|non-permanent seat]].<ref>[http://www.mrecic.gov.ar/portal/prensa/ver_articulo.php?id=54&sec=2 El vecino como oportunidad] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127042111/http://mrecic.gov.ar/portal/prensa/ver_articulo.php?id=54&sec=2 |date=2010-11-27 }} Secretar\u00eda de Relaciones Exteriores. Retrieved on 2010-11-30. {{in lang|es}}.</ref>\n\nIn the economic arena, Argentina and Brazil dropped the [[United States dollar|U.S. dollar]] and started using their own currencies on all bilateral commercial transactions in 2008.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-03/16/content_7800121.htm Argentina, Brazil to drop U.S. dollar in bilateral commercial transactions] [[Xinhua News Agency|Xinhua]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-14.</ref>\n\nOn September 6, 2008, the President of Argentina, [[Cristina Kirchner]], traveled to Brazil to consolidate relations between the two countries. She was the guest of honor at the Independence Day celebrations that took place on September 7, 2008 and witnessed the military parade in [[Bras\u00edlia]]. The following day, she held discussions with President Lula on a variety of bilateral issues including energy, defense and nuclear cooperation.<ref name=\"G15\">[http://www.g15.org/bulletinseptember08.pdf Argentina, Brazil consolidate relations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726011617/http://www.g15.org/bulletinseptember08.pdf |date=2011-07-26 }} [[G15]]. Retrieved on January 17, 2008.</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2010 president Lula da Silva traveled to Buenos Aires to give his condolences for [[N\u00e9stor Kirchner]]'s death.<ref>[http://www.buenosairesherald.com/BreakingNews/View/49530 Lula: 'Kirchner was able to pull Argentina out of the pit it was in'] Buenos Aires Herald. Retrieved on 2010-10-28.</ref> The Brazilian Government declared three days of national mourning.<ref>[http://www.estadao.com.br/noticias/internacional,lula-decreta-luto-de-tres-dias-e-diz-que-kirchner-era-fraternal-amigo,630642,0.htm Lula decreta luto de tr\u00eas dias e diz que Kirchner era 'fraternal amigo'] Estad\u00e3o. Retrieved on 2010-10-28. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref>\n\n{{quote box|width=216px|quote=\"Our alliance with Brazil is indestructible\"|source=&mdash; Foreign Minister [[H\u00e9ctor Timerman]].<ref>[http://www.buenosairesherald.com/article/57697/our-alliance-with-brazil-is-indestructible-timerman-says 'Our alliance with Brazil is indestructible,' Timerman says] Buenos Aires Herald. Retrieved on 2011-01-31.</ref>}}\n\nPresident [[Dilma Rousseff]] chose Argentina as the first foreign trip of her presidency, in a demonstration of the \"special and strategic\" ties between the two countries.<ref>[http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_world/view/1107912/1/.html Rousseff to make first foreign visit in Argentina] Channel News Asia. Retrieved on 2011-01-31.</ref> During her state visit to Buenos Aires on January 31, 2011, Rousseff stated that \"it was not a casual decision to pick Argentina as my first foreign destination\" and praised Argentina as a \"strategic ally\" to her country.<ref>[http://www.buenosairesherald.com/article/57686/im-here-to-make-our-relationship-stronger-than-ever-rousseff 'I'm here to make our relationship stronger than ever,' Rousseff] Buenos Aires Herald. Retrieved on 2011-01-31.</ref> \"The Brazilian government assumes, once again, a true commitment with the Argentine government as well as a joint policy intended to promote a development strategy for the region. For me the main idea is that of a strategic relationship with Argentina, which should shine itself in all areas of interest of both countries\", said Rousseff in conversations with local newspapers before arriving in Buenos Aires.<ref>[http://en.mercopress.com/2011/01/30/dilma-rousseff-makes-first-trip-abroad-as-president-to-argentina Dilma Rousseff Makes First Trip Abroad As President to Argentina] MercoPress. Retrieved on 2011-01-31.</ref>\n\n==Current issues==\n\n===Military cooperation===\n[[File:Gaucho VLEGA 2007.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Armored version of the \"Gaucho\" vehicle]]\n[[File:Sat\u00e9lites SABIA-Mar 1 y SABIA-Mar 2.jpg|thumb|200px|The [[SABIA-Mar]], scheduled to be launched in 2022, is a '''Brazilian/Argentine''' earth observation satellite.]]\n\nBrazil and Argentina are engaged in several [[joint venture]] projects in the military field, such as the [[VLEGA Gaucho|Gaucho armored vehicle]] and the [[Embraer KC-390]] military transport aircraft. The Gaucho is a [[Light Strike Vehicle]] capable of [[reconnaissance]], [[air assault]], [[command and control]], [[transport]] and [[Emergency evacuation|evacuation]] missions.<ref name=\"WarWheels\" /> The Gaucho project started in 2004 and entered production in 2006.<ref name=\"WarWheels\" /> Argentina is responsible for the design and construction of the chassis, engine mounts, transmission, steering and suspension.<ref name=\"WarWheels\" /> Brazil, for its part,  developed and installed the brake system, engine, transmission and transfer case, as well as the cooling system, electrical system, fuel, armament and accessories.<ref name=\"WarWheels\">[http://www.warwheels.net/images/GauchoDataSheet.pdf Gaucho vehicle data sheet] WarWheels. Retrieved on 2011-01-22.</ref>\n\nBrazil and Argentina have also entered a partnership to jointly develop the [[Embraer KC-390|KC-390]] twin-engine [[military transport aircraft]].<ref name=\"MercoPress\">[http://en.mercopress.com/2010/11/02/argentina-joins-brazil-s-development-of-military-cargo-aircraft Argentina joins Brazil\u2019s development of military cargo aircraft] MercoPress. Retrieved on 2011-01-22.</ref> Argentina has agreed to manufacture KC-390 components and possibly purchase six of the aircraft.<ref name=\"MercoPress\" />\n\nThe [[Argentine Army]] has shown interest in a possible version of the 8x8 armored vehicles [[VBTP-MR|VBTP-MR Guaran\u00ed]] developed by the [[Brazilian Army]] with the support of [[Iveco]]. The [[Argentine military]] are also operators of the Brazilian military [[Agrale Marru\u00e1]] vehicle.\n\n===Scientific cooperation===\nArgentina and Brazil have close cooperation in the field of [[space science]] \u2013 the [[Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales|National Space Activities Commission]] of Argentina and the [[Brazilian Space Agency]] have been working together since the 1990s. In 2007, Brazil and Argentina successfully launched a rocket into space, in the first joint space mission by the two countries. The [[VS-30]] rocket was launched from the [[Barreira do Inferno Launch Center]] and carried experiments from both countries.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/topstories/2007-12-16-369182213_x.htm Brazil, Argentina launch space rocket] [[USA Today]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-14.</ref>\n\nThe [[Brazilian\u2013Argentine Agency for Accounting and Control of Nuclear Materials]] was created in 1991.  During President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva|Lula]]'s [[state visit]] to Buenos Aires on February 22, 2008, the two countries established a binational commission on pursuing joint [[uranium enrichment]] for nuclear energy purposes.<ref name=\"G15\"/><ref>[https://www.forbes.com/feeds/afx/2008/02/22/afx4686939.html Argentina, Brazil pledge nuclear ties] [[Forbes]]. Retrieved on 2009-07-14.</ref>\n\n===Falkland Islands===\n{{Further|Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute}}\n[[File:CarlosGanemVS-30.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The [[VS-30]], Argentina and Brazil cooperated on this sounding rocket.]]\nThe [[Government of Brazil|Brazilian government]] has been a strong supporter of the Argentine claim over the [[Falkland Islands]]<ref>[http://en.mercopress.com/2010/11/24/falklands-malvinas-brazil-joins-argentina-in-criticizing-uk-s-unilateral-actions Falklands/Malvinas: Brazil joins Argentina in criticizing UK\u2019s \"unilateral actions\"] Mercopress. Retrieved on 2010-11-27.</ref> \u2013 which both countries term Malvinas (Brazil: ''Ilhas Malvinas'' / Argentina: ''Islas Malvinas'').<ref>[http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/sala-de-imprensa/selecao-diaria-de-noticias/midias-nacionais/brasil/agencia-brasil/2010/06/25/onu-convoca-reino-unido-e-argentina-para-negociar-posse-das-malvinas ONU convoca Reino Unido e Argentina para negociar posse das Malvinas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716154536/http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/sala-de-imprensa/selecao-diaria-de-noticias/midias-nacionais/brasil/agencia-brasil/2010/06/25/onu-convoca-reino-unido-e-argentina-para-negociar-posse-das-malvinas |date=2011-07-16 }} Minist\u00e9rio das Rela\u00e7\u00f5es Exteriores. Retrieved on 2010-11-30. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref>\n\nIn a joint communiqu\u00e9 issued by the Brazilian and Argentine governments on August 3, 2010, \"the President of the Federative Republic of Brazil reiterated the support of his country to the legitimate rights of Argentina in the sovereignty dispute regarding the Falkland Islands, South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands and the surrounding maritime areas\".<ref name=\"Communique\">[http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/sala-de-imprensa/notas-a-imprensa/declaracoes-adotadas-no-encontro-do-presidente-luiz-inacio-lula-da-silva-com-a-presidenta-da-argentina-cristina-fernandez-de-kirchner-san-juan-3-de-agosto-de-2010 Declara\u00e7\u00f5es adotadas no encontro do Presidente Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva com a Presidenta da Argentina, Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner - San Juan, 3 de agosto de 2010: Declara\u00e7\u00e3o Conjunta sobre Malvinas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716154427/http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/sala-de-imprensa/notas-a-imprensa/declaracoes-adotadas-no-encontro-do-presidente-luiz-inacio-lula-da-silva-com-a-presidenta-da-argentina-cristina-fernandez-de-kirchner-san-juan-3-de-agosto-de-2010 |date=2011-07-16 }} Minist\u00e9rio das Rela\u00e7\u00f5es Exteriores. Retrieved on 2010-11-27. {{in lang|pt|es}}.</ref> The Brazilian government also stressed that the exploration of [[Offshore drilling|offshore]] [[Oil reserves|oil]] that the United Kingdom carries out in the [[Argentine Sea|Argentine continental shelf]] is \"illegal\" and \"inconsistent with what determines the United Nations\".<ref name=\"Communique\" />\n\nBrazilian authorities have also voiced their support for the Argentine claim at the multilateral fora, including the [[United Nations]], the [[Rio Group]], [[Mercosur]], the [[Organization of American States]], and [[Union of South American Nations|Unasur]].<ref>[http://www.mrecic.gov.ar/portal/prensa/comunicado.php?buscar=4434 Cuesti\u00f3n Malvinas: Brasil ratific\u00f3 su apoyo a los leg\u00edtimos derechos Argentinos de soberan\u00eda sobre las Islas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127140729/http://mrecic.gov.ar/portal/prensa/comunicado.php?buscar=4434 |date=2010-11-27 }} Ministerio de Relaciones Exteriores, Comercio Internacional y Culto. Retrieved on 2010-11-27. {{in lang|es}}.</ref> Brazil has criticized the United Nations for not acting on the sovereignty of the Falkland Islands,<ref name=\"TimesOnline\">[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article7039257.ece Brazil attacks UN over Falklands stand-off] Times Online. Retrieved on 2010-11-27.</ref> and accused the United Kingdom of using its status as permanent member of the [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]] to prevent the debate from being reopened.<ref name=\"TimesOnline\" />\n\nIn accordance with a resolution adopted at the [[2010 South American Summit]] prohibiting British vessels operating under the \"illegal flag of the ''Malvinas'' (Falkland Islands)\" from docking at South American ports,<ref name=\"MercoPress2\">[http://en.mercopress.com/2010/11/27/unasur-unable-to-agree-on-secretary-closes-all-ports-to-illegal-malvinas-flagged-vessels Unasur unable to agree on secretary; closes all ports to \u2018illegal\u2019 Malvinas flagged vessels] Mercopress. Retrieved on 2010-11-27.</ref> the government of Brazil denied the British ship {{HMS|Clyde|P257|6}} access to [[Rio de Janeiro]] on January 11, 2011.<ref>[http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/222613/Falklands-ship-ban-by-Brazil Falklands ship ban by Brazil] Express.co.uk. Retrieved on 2011-01-13.</ref> In a statement, the Brazilian [[Ministry of Defence (Brazil)|Minister of Defense]], [[Nelson Jobim]], noted that Brazil \"recognizes Argentine sovereignty over the ''Malvinas'' (Falkland Islands) and not the British claim\" and therefore \"will not authorize any requests made from British ships or aircraft in military operations in the Falklands\".<ref>[http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/noticias/0,,OI4887173-EI306,00-Jobim+diz+que+veto+a+navio+britanico+vindo+das+Malvinas+e+padrao.html Jobim diz que veto a navio brit\u00e2nico vindo das Malvinas \u00e9 padr\u00e3o] Terra.com.br. Retrieved on 2011-01-13. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref>\n\n==Trade and investment==\n\n===Trade===\nBrazil accounts for Argentina's largest export and import market,<ref name=\"MREpdf\" /> while Argentina accounts for Brazil's fourth largest export and import market. Total trade between the two countries amounted to the sum of US$22.5 billion in 2016.<ref>https://globaledge.msu.edu/countries/brazil/tradestats</ref> Argentine exports to Brazil amounted to US$9.1 billion while Brazilian exports to Argentina totaled US$13.4 billion. In recent years, trade between the two countries decreased as commodity prices fell and Brazil experienced slower economic growth.<ref>https://worldview.stratfor.com/article/difficulties-facing-brazils-new-export-plan</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n! 2004\n! 2005\n! 2006\n! 2007\n! 2008\n! 2009\n! 2010\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Argentina}} '''Argentine exports to Brazil'''\n| $5.6 billion\n| $6.2 billion\n| $8 billion\n| $10.4 billion\n| $13.3 billion\n| $11.3 billion\n| $14.4 billion\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} '''Brazilian exports to Argentina'''\n| $7.4 billion\n| $9.9 billion\n| $11.7 billion\n| $14.4 billion\n| $17.6 billion\n| $12.8 billion\n| $18.5 billion\n|-\n| '''Total trade'''\n| $13 billion\n| $16.1 billion\n| $19.7 billion\n| $24.8 billion\n| $30.9 billion\n| $24.1 billion\n| $32.9 billion\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" | <small>Note: All values are in U.S. dollars. Source: MRE<ref name=\"MREpdf\" />/SECEX.<ref name=\"SECEX\">[http://www.desenvolvimento.gov.br/sitio/interna/interna.php?area=5&menu=2081 Interc\u00e2mbio Comercial Brasileiro - Argentina] SECEX. Retrieved on 2011-01-22. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref></small>\n|}\n\n===Investment===\nArgentina is the main destination for Brazilian [[Foreign direct investment|investment]] in South America.<ref name=\"Rudderless\" /> Brazilian investments in Argentina are mostly in oil, cement, mining, steel, textiles, cosmetics, banks, food, and beverages.<ref name=\"Rudderless\" /> According to the [[United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean]], forty percent of direct investment in Argentina comes from Brazil.<ref name=\"Rudderless\" />\n\n==State visits==\n\nSince 2003, Presidential meetings are held every six months alternately in each country,<ref>[http://www.presidencia.gov.ar/informacion/conferencias/20716 'y luego visitar\u00e1 la Rep\u00fablica Argentina en la mec\u00e1nica, que hemos adoptado desde la gesti\u00f3n que comenz\u00f3 con mi mandato, que son precisamente reuniones cada seis meses, donde monitoreamos todas y cada una de las pol\u00edticas']</ref> and besides those there are more for other reasons (UNASUR, Mercosur, G20, etc.).\n\n;Recent visits by the [[President of Brazil]] to Argentina\n[[File:Lula Kirchner137075.jpg|thumb|right|260px|Former President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva|Lula]] with Former President [[N\u00e9stor Kirchner]] in 2004.]]\n[[File:Macri Temer 5.jpg|thumb|286x286px|Former President [[Michel Temer]] and President Mauricio Macri in 2016.]]\n\n*[[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]]\n**May 22\u201325, 2003, [[Buenos Aires]] - [[Inauguration]] o