nload/pdf/chefeestado03.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160108/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado03.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n*[[N\u00e9stor Kirchner]]\n**June 11, 2003, Bras\u00edlia - Official state visit<ref name=\"PREx03\"/>\n**March 15\u201316, 2004, Bras\u00edlia - Official state visit<ref>[http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado04.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160119/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado04.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**May 9, 2005, Bras\u00edlia - South America-Arab Countries summit and private meeting with President Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva<ref>[http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado05.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160132/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado05.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**January 18\u201319, 2006, Bras\u00edlia - Official state visit<ref name=\"PREx06\">[http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado06.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160140/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado06.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**April 25\u201326, 2006, Bras\u00edlia - Presidential meeting with Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva<ref name=\"PREx06\"/>\n*[[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner|Cristina Kirchner]]\n**May 23, 2008, Bras\u00edlia - 1st [[Union of South American Nations|UNASUL]] summit<ref>[http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/ultimas/20-104721-2008-05-23.html Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez participa de la cumbre de Unasur] [[P\u00e1gina/12]]. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n**September 6\u20138, 2008, Bras\u00edlia - Official state visit<ref>[http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado08.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160155/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado08.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**March 20, 2009, [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] - Presidential meeting with Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva<ref>[http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado09.PDF Chefes de Estado e de Governo recebidos pelo Presidente Lula] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706160217/http://www.info.planalto.gov.br/download/pdf/chefeestado09.PDF |date=2011-07-06 }} Presid\u00eancia da Rep\u00fablica. Retrieved on 2009-06-23. {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n**November 18, 2009, Bras\u00edlia - Presidential meeting with Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva<ref name=\"MREpdf\">[http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/temas/temas-politicos-e-relacoes-bilaterais/america-do-sul/argentina/pdf Cronologia das Rela\u00e7\u00f5es Bilaterais] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716154402/http://www.itamaraty.gov.br/temas/temas-politicos-e-relacoes-bilaterais/america-do-sul/argentina/pdf |date=2011-07-16 }} Minist\u00e9rio das Rela\u00e7\u00f5es Exteriores. Retrieved on 2010-11-20. {{in lang|pt}}.</ref>\n**July 29, 2011, Brasilia, new Argentine embassy opening ceremony \n**December 7, 2012, Brasilia- Presidential meeting with [[Dilma Rousseff|Dilma Rouseff]]\n**July 14\u201316, 2014, [[Fortaleza]], 6th [[BRICS]] Summit\n**July 13\u201316, 2015, Brasilia, 2015 Mercosur Summit\n*[[Mauricio Macri]] \n** January 16, 2019, Official State Visit<ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-16/all-smiles-in-brasilia-as-macri-and-bolsonaro-reset-relationship</ref>\n\n==Diplomacy==\n[[Diplomatic mission]]s:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Of Argentina\n* [[Bras\u00edlia]] (Embassy)\n* [[Porto Alegre]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[Rio de Janeiro]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[Belo Horizonte]] (Consulate)\n* [[Curitiba]] (Consulate)\n* [[Florian\u00f3polis]] (Consulate)\n* [[Foz do Igua\u00e7u]] (Consulate)\n* [[Recife]] (Consulate)\n* [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]] (Consulate)\n* [[Uruguaiana]] (Consulate)\n{{col-2}}\n[[File:Brazilian Embassy Buenos Aires.png|thumb|right|200px|The Brazilian Embassy in Buenos Aires.]]\n;Of Brazil\n* [[Buenos Aires]] (Embassy)\n* [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]] (Consulate-General)\n* [[Paso de los Libres]] (Vice-Consulate)\n* [[Puerto Iguaz\u00fa]] (Vice-Consulate)\n* [[Bah\u00eda Blanca]] (Honorary Consulate)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Argentine Brazilian]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Argentina]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Brazil]]\n*[[Mercosul]]\n*[[Union of South American Nations]]\n*[[Argentina and Brazil football rivalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090729104552/http://www.brasil.org.ar/ Embassy of Brazil in Buenos Aires]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090803122759/http://www.brasil.embajada-argentina.gov.ar/ Embassy of Argentina in Bras\u00edlia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070607000356/http://www.mre.gov.br/ingles/index.htm Ministry of Foreign Relations of Brazil]\n*[http://www.mrecic.gov.ar/ Ministry of Foreign Relations, International Trade and Cult of Argentina]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080515210104/http://www.abacc.org/ Brazilian-Argentine Agency for Accounting and Control of Nuclear Materials]\n\n{{Foreign relations of Argentina}}\n{{Foreign relations of Brazil}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Argentina-Brazil Relations}}\n[[Category:Argentina\u2013Brazil relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Argentina|Brazil]]\n", "name_user": "Logan", "label": "safe", "comment": "bad link repair", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentina%E2%80%93Brazil_relations"}
{"title_page": "Florian Froehlich", "text_new": "'''Florian Froehlich''' (born December 17, 1959 in [[Pf\u00e4ffikon, Zurich|Pfaeffikon]] in Switzerland), is a contemporary artist who creates paintings, sculptures, stained-glass, and installations.\n\n== The artist ==\n[[File:Florian Froehlich - Golgotha.jpg|thumb|''Golgotha'' \u2013 Stained glass and steel sculptures, 400 cm. Back-lighting with 2000 W. Part of the Saignel\u00e9gier project.|left|upright=0.9]]\n\nFlorian Froehlich was, when starting out in art, strongly influenced<ref name=\"pharts2007\">''phArt'' October/November 2007, article ''Florian Froehlich -Un ordre subtil''</ref> by the [[School of Paris]], in particular by artists such as [[Maurice Est\u00e8ve]], [[Charles Lapicque]] and [[Nicolas de Sta\u00ebl]]. He had had contacts with the world of art on a regular basis from childhood on, as he is related to the famous Zurich art dealer Peter Nathan.<ref>[[NZZ]], article January 5, 2002, [http://www.nzz.ch/aktuell/startseite/article7VV69-1.354300 \u00ab Ein Leben f\u00fcr die Kunst \u2013 Zum Tod von Peter Nathan \u00bb]</ref> He trained in medicine at the Universities of Zurich and Lausanne until 1996 and thereafter developed a progressive and lasting activity as an artist in tandem with his professional life.<ref name=\"pharts2007\" /> He is living since 1996 in [[Porrentruy]] in the Swiss Jura. His close friendship and collaboration<ref name=\"FF-JM\">''phArt'' 2002, article [https://archive.today/20130809162537/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/2002PHART.jpg \u00ab La connivence cr\u00e9atrice de Jacques Minala et Florian Froehlich \u00bb] \u2013 exposition in Del\u00e9ment in 2002</ref> with the Swiss artist Jacques Minala<ref>[http://www.xn--visarte-neuchtel-8mb.ch/jacquesminala.html Web page] Jacques Minala on Visarte website</ref> lead him to become familiar with the technique of stained glass. Since 2003, he is member of the Swiss Stained Glass Artists Society Verarte.ch<ref>[http://www.verarte.ch Web site] of the Swiss Stained Glass Artists Society</ref> which led to several group exhibitions in the Vitromus\u00e9e Suisse de Romont,<ref>[http://www.vitromusee.ch/ Web site] of the Vitromus\u00e9e Suisse de Romont</ref> in particular in 2009.<ref>''Le Temps'' August 22, 2009, article [https://archive.today/20130809162541/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/Le-Temps-22-aout-2009.jpg \u00ab Actualit\u00e9 de l\u2019art du verre \u00bb] wrote by Laurence Chauvy</ref>\n\nFrom 2003 to 2009, Froehlich worked intensely on the \"Saignel\u00e9gier Steles\" for the catholic church in [[Saignel\u00e9gier]], Jura Switzerland, project which received national funding from the Swiss Confederation,<ref name=\"phart022009\">''Illustr\u00e9,'' February 25th 2009 article [http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/illustre25_2_2009.jpg Vitraux \u00e0 l'air libre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512223916/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/illustre25_2_2009.jpg |date=May 12, 2014 }} wrote by Blaise Calame</ref> and which was executed in collaboration with the glass master-craftsman Roland B\u00e9guin<ref>[http://www.beguin-vitraux.ch Web site] of Roland B\u00e9guin</ref>), and the metalwork artist J.-P. Scheuner using experimental techniques.<ref name=\"phart022009\" /> The novel concept of the stele allows keeping all the church's luminosity by occupying only a very limited space.<ref name=\"phart022009\" /> In contrast to normal stained glass which is not lit, Froehlich is using in Saignel\u00e9gier artificial light: indeed, three steles, called the [[Calvary|Golgotha]] group, are strongly backlit.<ref name=\"phart022009\" /> Every of the 21 four-meter high steles is associated with a text from the bible<ref name=phart022009 /> commented by Father Bernard Miserez.<ref>[http://www.exultet.net/eshop/pages-manufacturers_about/manufacturers_about_id-749/index.html Web page] devoted to Father Bernard Miserez on Exulnet</ref> The dalle glass was produced specifically for this project, in Waldsassen (Germany).<ref name=\"phart022009\" /> The [[Saignel\u00e9gier]] Steles are a novel contribution to contemporary sacred glasswork.<ref>[http://vimeo.com/3467166 Florian Froehlich \u2013 Inauguration of the Saignel\u00e9gier Steles], canal Alpha TV program, February 19th 2009 program</ref><ref>''Glaswelt'' October 2008, article [http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/Glasweltoctobre2008.jpg Dallglas ist wieder im Kommen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054310/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/Glasweltoctobre2008.jpg |date=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOccasionally, Froehlich creates in relation to world events, such as for the Jura leg of the [[Tour de France 2012]]: he showed an art installation exhibited to thousands of spectators over a 24-hour period on July 8, 2012.<ref name=\"video tdf\">{{YouTube|esw8Br3oyBY|Movie of the Tour de France installation}}</ref> In 2012 and 2013, his work was presented at the ''Berliner Liste'',<ref>[http://berliner-liste.org/ Web site] of the Berliner Liste</ref> a reputed and selective international art fair.<ref>[http://berliner-liste.org/wordpress/portfolio-item/achtzig-galerie-fur-zeitgenossische-kunst/ Web page] showing the ''ACHTZIG'' gallery which includes Froehlich</ref>\n\nSince 2010, Froehlich has worked very regularly with the ACHTZIG Gallery for Contemporary Fine Art in [[Berlin]].<ref>[http://www.dianaachtzig.de Web site] of the ACHTZIG gallery in Berlin</ref> The ACHTZIG Gallery staged a solo exhibition of Froehlich's work in December 2013, entitled \"World Theatre-Theatre World\". At his occasion a book with his same title has been published by Editions Le Renard par la Queue,<ref>[http://lerenardparlaqueue.com/ Web site] of editions ''Le Renard par la Queue''</ref> Lausanne, directed by the author [[Ferenc R\u00e1k\u00f3czy]] in a contemporary design by Chlo\u00e9 Donz\u00e9 and contributions by the journalist Jos\u00e9 Ribeaud.\nCurrently, Froehlich's work is focusing on the human being and the interaction between individual and crowds.<ref>book ''Florian Froehlich: World Theatre \u2013 Theatre World''. Editions ''Le renard par la queue'', CH-1005 Lausanne. No {{ISBN|978-2-940533-00-8}}.</ref> Froehlich creates a kind of virtual human microcosmos notably by micro-sculptures integrated in painting-sculptures and sculpture-paintings.\n[[File:Two prisoners.jpg|thumb|328x328px|'''Two prisoners'''. Mixed media on canvas. 50 x 150 cm, 2018]]\nIn fall 2013, Froehlich had the novel idea to suggest the scenic integration of microsculptures in watches. This idea was officially presented to Swiss watchmakers,<ref name=\"lqj micro watch\">Article [http://lqj.ch/region/art-et-horlogerie Art et horlogerie] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430003216/http://lqj.ch/region/art-et-horlogerie |date=April 30, 2014 }} about the integration of microsculptures in watches, ''Quotidien Jurassien'', 2013</ref> with the support of Pascal Bourquard and BIWI.\n[[File:Last judgement Froehlich.jpg|thumb|'''Last judgement.''' Mixed media on canvas, 40 x 50 cm, 2017]]\nFrom 2015 on, Froehlich has gradually begun to change his focus from crowds to the human being in all their various individualities, with the [[Renaissance]] as his gateway to the subject, having concentrated mainly on sketching over a period of two years. The artist has, for example, used a pre-existing drawing or art work which he has magnified, while often focussing on amplifying a specific detail<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=H\u00fcgli|first=Pierre|date=October and November 2018|title=Quand Florian Froehlich d\u00e9poussi\u00e8re la Renaissance|url=http://www.pharts.ch/index.php/sommaire/47-pharts-136/557-delemont|journal=ph+arts|volume=136|pages=7|via=}}</ref> . This has given his compositions an amplitude and a liberty which bring them into line with the spirit of our times,<ref name=\":0\" /> using a multitude of techniques: pencil, charcoal, water colour, collage, acrylics and even [[encaustic painting]], &nbsp;a very ancient technique using beeswax. The spirit of the Renaissance pervades his work: the intellectual excursion into [[humanism]], a perfect mastery of the use of [[Perspective (graphical)|perspective]] and the magic that is beauty. Froehlich rejuvenates this era with an artistic vision which is both new and contemporary.\n[[File:Sign up with heaven.jpg|thumb|'''Sign up with heaven'''. Mixed media on canvas. 50 x 60 cm, 2018 ]]\nOne of the focuses of Froehlich\u2019s work is the Biblical character, [[Haman]], taking as his base a small sketch by [[Bartolomeo Passarotti]] whose subject was used in the painting of the ceiling of the [[Sistine Chapel]] by [[Michelangelo]]. [[Peter Paul Rubens|Peter-Paul Rubens]] took up the subject of this sketch during the following century, reworking it in his manner. What liberty this inter-inspiration between artists permits! Pierre H\u00fcgli, an art magazine publisher wrote: \u201cWho of the contemporary artists will show a passion for the sketches of the old masters, these riches hidden away in the archives, to the point of making them the starting point of a one-of-a-kind artistic creation?\u00bb<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choulat|first=Elise|date=September 2018|title=Florian Froehlich revisite la gr\u00e2ce de la Renaissance|url=|journal=L'Ajoie|volume=466|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n[[File:Guerrier avec casque.jpg|thumb|'''Warrior with helmet'''. Mixed media on canvas. 30 x 30 cm , 2018]]\nThe culmination of Froehlich\u2019s work can be seen in this autumn 2018\u2019s exhibition \u00ab Renaissance Magic \u00bb at the [[:fr:Fondation_Anne_et_Robert_Bloch|BLOCH Foundation]] (FARB) in Del\u00e9mont. Two concerts will take place in tandem with the exhibition, featuring among others the works of the Romantic composer, [[:de:Friedrich_Theodor_Fr\u00f6hlich|Friedrich Th\u00e9odor Froehlich]] (1803\u20131836), friend of Franz Schubert and an ancestor of the artist.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n=== Individual exhibitions ===\n[[File:Life Score.jpg|thumb|''Life score'' \u2013 Sculpture, mixed media, cardboard. Canvas 30 x 30 cm|upright=0.7]]\n\n* 2018 : Magie de la Renaissance&nbsp; Fondation Anne et Robert Bloch (FARB), Del\u00e9mont (Suisse) <ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Traversini|first=Dominique|date=October 2018|title=Florian Froehlich, Magie de la Renaissance|url=http://www.accrochages.ch/f/main.php?action=getArticle&articleId=1080|journal=Accrochage|volume=201|pages=11|via=}}</ref>\n\n* 2013 : ''World Theatre-Theatre World'', Achtzig Gallery for Contemporary Art,Berlin, Allemagne (d\u00e9cembre 2013).\n* 2012 : ''Tour de France, Jura stage on July 8, 2012: \"Finishing line\"'' : an installation with multiple sculptures and an old dusty bike.<ref name=\"video tdf\" />\n* 2007 : ''Galerie FARB'', Del\u00e9mont, Suisse<ref name=\"pharts2007\" />\n* 2005 : ''Galerie du Solstice'', Yverdon/Treycovagnes, Suisse\n* 2004 : ''Galerie du Solstice'', Yverdon/Treycovagnes, Suisse\n* 2003 : ''Galerie Catherine Clerc'', Lausanne, Suisse<ref>Article [https://archive.today/20130809162539/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/2003PhArtCathClerc.jpg Lausanne: Florian Froehlich by Catherine Clerc], ''phArt'' September 2003</ref>\n* 2002 : ''Galerie Paul Bov\u00e9e'', Del\u00e9mont, Suisse<ref name=\"FF-JM\" />\n* 1998 : ''Galerie Courant d'Art'', Chevenez, Suisse;<ref>Article [https://archive.today/20130809162516/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/1998QJCourantd'Art.jpg Du paysage \u00e0 l'abstraction], \u00e0 propos de l'exposition en 1998 \u00e0 la galerie Courant d'Art, ''Quotidien Jurassien'' 1998</ref> ''Galerie Paul Bov\u00e9e'', Del\u00e9mont, Suisse<ref>Article [https://archive.today/20130809162516/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/1998BoveeQJ.jpg Florian Froehlich -Entre Abstraction et figuration], \u00e0 propos de l'exposition en 1998 \u00e0 la Galerie Bov\u00e9e \u00e0 Del\u00e9mont, ''Quotidien Jurassien'', 1998</ref>\n* 1997 : ''Galerie Pingeot-Gerbi'', Paris, France ; ''Galerie Catherine Clerc'', Lausanne, Suisse\n* 1994 : ''Galerie Catherine Clerc'', Lausanne, Suisse\n* 1993 : ''Galerie de l'Evole99, Neuch\u00e2tel, Suisse\n* 1992 : ''Fondation du Grand-Cachot-de-Vent'', Vall\u00e9e de La Br\u00e9vine, Suisse \n* 1991 : ''Galerie Jasmin'', Zurich, Suisse ; ''Galerie Black'', Lausanne, Suisse\n* 1989 : ''Galerie Jasmin'', Zurich, Suisse.\n\n=== Group exhibitions ===\n\n[[File:Lives in parallel.jpg|thumb|''Lives in parallel'' \u2013 Mixed media and ink. Canvas, 40x60 cm|upright=0.8]]\n[[File:Human Grape.jpg|thumb|''Human grape'' \u2013 Sculpture on wires. 19x 82 cm|upright=0.8]]\n\n* 2015 et 2017&nbsp;: Biennale de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Peintres et Sculpteurs Jurassiens SPSJ&nbsp; (<nowiki>http://www.spsj.ch</nowiki>)\n\n* 2015 : Galerie Dukan Contemporary Art, Leipzig\n\n* 2014: Group exhibitions, Achtzig Gallery for Contemporary Art, Berlin, Germany\n* 2013: MicroArt: Exhibition of recent work to suggest the use of microsculptures in Swiss watchmaking. Plejouse, October 29, 2013<ref name=\"lqj micro watch\" />\n* 2013 : ''Galerie FARB'', [[Del\u00e9mont]], Switzerland\n* 2011\u20132013 : ''Achtzig Gallery for Contemporary Art'', [[Berlin]] (plusieurs expositions en groupe)\n* 2010 : Exposition ''City Landscapes'', Achtzig Gallery for Contemporary Art, Berlin, Germany\n* 2009 : ''Swiss Museum of Stained Glass and Glass Art'', Romont (Vitromus\u00e9e), Romont. Verarte.ch exhibition; du 4 avril au 20 septembre 2009 ; ''Galerie Meistersch\u00fcler'', Berlin, Germany\n* 2007 : ''Galerie Art Service'', Ch\u00e2teau d'Eguilly, Eguilly, France ; ''Galerie Bleu de Chine'', Fleurier, Switzerland\n* 2006 : Permanent exhibition of artworks, ''Galerie Alain Aubry'', Paris, France\n* 2005 : ''Verarte.ch : Exhibition of Glass Art'', Elisabethenkirche, B\u00e2le, Switzerland\n* 2004 : ''Exposition au Mus\u00e9e suisse du vitrail et des arts du verre'', organis\u00e9 par Verarte.ch, Romont, Switzerland\n* 2002 : Invitation to take part in a nationwide exhibition Expo 02 ; Kunstmuseum, [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], Switzerland\n* 1998 : ''Centre d'Art en Face'', [[Porrentruy]], Switzerland\n* 1994 : ''120 artistes jurassiens'' (120 Jura artists), Del\u00e9mont, Switzerland\n* 1992 : ''Galerie 67'', [[Bern]], Switzerland\n\n== Publications ==\n* Florian FROEHLICH : Magie de la Renaissance. Un retour aux sources de la beaut\u00e9. octobre 2018. {{ISBN|978-2-8399-2487-0}} \n*Florian Froehlich : ''World Theatre \u2013 Theatre World''. \u00c9ditions Le renard par la queue, CH-1005 Lausanne, {{ISBN|978-2-940533-00-8}}\n* ''Glasmalerei f\u00fcr das 21. Jahrhundert : Malen mit Glas und Licht'', {{ISBN|978-3-00-040422-1}}\n* ''Biographisches Lexikon der Schweizer Kunst'', Verlag Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung, {{ISBN|3-85823-673-X}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://florianfroehlich.com/}}\n\n{{Orphan|date=September 2013}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Froehlich, Florian}}\n[[Category:Swiss contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Swiss painters]]\n[[Category:Swiss male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swiss painters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pf\u00e4ffikon, Z\u00fcrich]]\n", "text_old": "'''Florian Froehlich''' (born December 17, 1959 in [[Pf\u00e4ffikon, Zurich|Pfaeffikon]] in Switzerland), is a contemporary artist who creates paintings, sculptures, stained-glass, and installations.\n\n== The artist ==\n[[File:Florian Froehlich - Golgotha.jpg|thumb|''Golgotha'' \u2013 Stained glass and steel sculptures, 400 cm. Back-lighting with 2000 W. Part of the Saignel\u00e9gier project.|left|upright=0.9]]\n\nFlorian Froehlich was, when starting out in art, strongly influenced<ref name=\"pharts2007\">''phArt'' October/November 2007, article ''Florian Froehlich -Un ordre subtil''</ref> by the [[School of Paris]], in particular by artists such as [[Maurice Est\u00e8ve]], [[Charles Lapicque]] and [[Nicolas de Sta\u00ebl]]. He had had contacts with the world of art on a regular basis from childhood on, as he is related to the famous Zurich art dealer Peter Nathan.<ref>[[NZZ]], article January 5, 2002, [http://www.nzz.ch/aktuell/startseite/article7VV69-1.354300 \u00ab Ein Leben f\u00fcr die Kunst \u2013 Zum Tod von Peter Nathan \u00bb]</ref> He trained in medicine at the Universities of Zurich and Lausanne until 1996 and thereafter developed a progressive and lasting activity as an artist in tandem with his professional life.<ref name=\"pharts2007\" /> He is living since 1996 in [[Porrentruy]] in the Swiss Jura. His close friendship and collaboration<ref name=\"FF-JM\">''phArt'' 2002, article [https://archive.today/20130809162537/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/2002PHART.jpg \u00ab La connivence cr\u00e9atrice de Jacques Minala et Florian Froehlich \u00bb] \u2013 exposition in Del\u00e9ment in 2002</ref> with the Swiss artist Jacques Minala<ref>[http://www.xn--visarte-neuchtel-8mb.ch/jacquesminala.html Web page] Jacques Minala on Visarte website</ref> lead him to become familiar with the technique of stained glass. Since 2003, he is member of the Swiss Stained Glass Artists Society Verarte.ch<ref>[http://www.verarte.ch Web site] of the Swiss Stained Glass Artists Society</ref> which led to several group exhibitions in the Vitromus\u00e9e Suisse de Romont,<ref>[http://www.vitromusee.ch/ Web site] of the Vitromus\u00e9e Suisse de Romont</ref> in particular in 2009.<ref>''Le Temps'' August 22, 2009, article [https://archive.today/20130809162541/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/Le-Temps-22-aout-2009.jpg \u00ab Actualit\u00e9 de l\u2019art du verre \u00bb] wrote by Laurence Chauvy</ref>\n\nFrom 2003 to 2009, Froehlich worked intensely on the \"Saignel\u00e9gier Steles\" for the catholic church in [[Saignel\u00e9gier]], Jura Switzerland, project which received national funding from the Swiss Confederation,<ref name=\"phart022009\">''Illustr\u00e9,'' February 25th 2009 article [http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/illustre25_2_2009.jpg Vitraux \u00e0 l'air libre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512223916/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/illustre25_2_2009.jpg |date=May 12, 2014 }} wrote by Blaise Calame</ref> and which was executed in collaboration with the glass master-craftsman Roland B\u00e9guin<ref>[http://www.beguin-vitraux.ch Web site] of Roland B\u00e9guin</ref>), and the metalwork artist J.-P. Scheuner using experimental techniques.<ref name=\"phart022009\" /> The novel concept of the stele allow to keep all the church's luminosity by occupying only a very limited space.<ref name=\"phart022009\" /> In contrast to normal stained glass which is not lit, Froehlich is using in Saignel\u00e9gier artificial light: indeed, three steles, called the [[Calvary|Golgotha]] group, are strongly backlit.<ref name=\"phart022009\" /> Every of the 21 four-meter high steles is associated with a text from the bible<ref name=phart022009 /> commented by Father Bernard Miserez.<ref>[http://www.exultet.net/eshop/pages-manufacturers_about/manufacturers_about_id-749/index.html Web page] devoted to Father Bernard Miserez on Exulnet</ref> The dalle glass was produced specifically for this project, in Waldsassen (Germany).<ref name=\"phart022009\" /> The [[Saignel\u00e9gier]] Steles are a novel contribution to contemporary sacred glasswork.<ref>[http://vimeo.com/3467166 Florian Froehlich \u2013 Inauguration of the Saignel\u00e9gier Steles], canal Alpha TV program, February 19th 2009 program</ref><ref>''Glaswelt'' October 2008, article [http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/Glasweltoctobre2008.jpg Dallglas ist wieder im Kommen] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921054310/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/Glasweltoctobre2008.jpg |date=September 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOccasionally, Froehlich creates in relation to world events, such as for the Jura leg of the [[Tour de France 2012]]: he showed an art installation exhibited to thousands of spectators over a 24-hour period on July 8, 2012.<ref name=\"video tdf\">{{YouTube|esw8Br3oyBY|Movie of the Tour de France installation}}</ref> In 2012 and 2013, his work was presented at the ''Berliner Liste'',<ref>[http://berliner-liste.org/ Web site] of the Berliner Liste</ref> a reputed and selective international art fair.<ref>[http://berliner-liste.org/wordpress/portfolio-item/achtzig-galerie-fur-zeitgenossische-kunst/ Web page] showing the ''ACHTZIG'' gallery which includes Froehlich</ref>\n\nSince 2010, Froehlich has worked very regularly with the ACHTZIG Gallery for Contemporary Fine Art in [[Berlin]].<ref>[http://www.dianaachtzig.de Web site] of the ACHTZIG gallery in Berlin</ref> The ACHTZIG Gallery staged a solo exhibition of Froehlich's work in December 2013, entitled \"World Theatre-Theatre World\". At his occasion a book with his same title has been published by Editions Le Renard par la Queue,<ref>[http://lerenardparlaqueue.com/ Web site] of editions ''Le Renard par la Queue''</ref> Lausanne, directed by the author [[Ferenc R\u00e1k\u00f3czy]] in a contemporary design by Chlo\u00e9 Donz\u00e9 and contributions by the journalist Jos\u00e9 Ribeaud.\nCurrently, Froehlich's work is focusing on the human being and the interaction between individual and crowds.<ref>book ''Florian Froehlich : World Theatre \u2013 Theatre World''. Editions ''Le renard par la queue'', CH-1005 Lausanne. No {{ISBN|978-2-940533-00-8}}.</ref> Froehlich creates a kind of virtual human microcosmos notably by micro-sculptures integrated in painting-sculptures and sculpture-paintings.\n[[File:Two prisoners.jpg|thumb|328x328px|'''Two prisoners'''. Mixed media on canvas. 50 x 150 cm, 2018]]\nIn fall 2013, Froehlich had the novel idea to suggest the scenic integration of microsculptures in watches. This idea was officially presented to Swiss watchmakers,<ref name=\"lqj micro watch\">Article [http://lqj.ch/region/art-et-horlogerie Art et horlogerie] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430003216/http://lqj.ch/region/art-et-horlogerie |date=April 30, 2014 }} about the integration of microsculptures in watches, ''Quotidien Jurassien'', 2013</ref> with the support of Pascal Bourquard and BIWI.\n[[File:Last judgement Froehlich.jpg|thumb|'''Last judgement.''' Mixed media on canvas, 40 x 50 cm, 2017]]\nFrom 2015 on, Froehlich has gradually begun to change his focus from crowds to the human being in all their various invidualities, with the [[Renaissance]] as his gateway to the subject, having concentrated mainly on sketching over a period of two years. The artist has for example used a pre-existing drawing or art work which he has magnified, while often focussing on amplifying a specific detail<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=H\u00fcgli|first=Pierre|date=October and November 2018|title=Quand Florian Froehlich d\u00e9poussi\u00e8re la Renaissance|url=http://www.pharts.ch/index.php/sommaire/47-pharts-136/557-delemont|journal=ph+arts|volume=136|pages=7|via=}}</ref> . This has given his compositions an amplitude and a liberty which bring them into line with the spirit of our times<ref name=\":0\" /> , using a multitude of techniques: pencil, charcoal, water colour, collage, acrylics and even [[encaustic painting]], &nbsp;a very ancient technique using beeswax. The spirit of the Renaissance pervades his work: the intellectual excursion into [[humanism]], a perfect mastery of the use of [[Perspective (graphical)|perspective]] and the magic that is beauty. Froehlich rejuvenates this era with an artistic vision which is both new and contemporary.\n[[File:Sign up with heaven.jpg|thumb|'''Sign up with heaven'''. Mixed media on canvas. 50 x 60 cm, 2018 ]]\nOne of the focuses of Froehlich\u2019s work is the Biblical character, [[Haman]], taking as his base a small sketch by [[Bartolomeo Passarotti]] whose subject was used in the painting of the ceiling of the [[Sistine Chapel]] by [[Michelangelo]]. [[Peter Paul Rubens|Peter-Paul Rubens]] took up the subject of this sketch during the following century, reworking it in his manner. What liberty this inter-inspiration between artists permits! Pierre H\u00fcgli, an art magazine publisher wrote: \u201cWho of the contemporary artists will show a passion for the sketches of the old masters, these riches hidden away in the archives, to the point of making them the starting point of a one-of-a-kind artistic creation?\u00bb<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choulat|first=Elise|date=September 2018|title=Florian Froehlich revisite la gr\u00e2ce de la Renaissance|url=|journal=L'Ajoie|volume=466|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n[[File:Guerrier avec casque.jpg|thumb|'''Warrior with helmet'''. Mixed media on canvas. 30 x 30 cm , 2018]]\nThe culmination of Froehlich\u2019s work can be seen in this autumn 2018\u2019s exhibition \u00ab Renaissance Magic \u00bb at the [[:fr:Fondation_Anne_et_Robert_Bloch|BLOCH Foundation]] (FARB) in Del\u00e9mont. Two concerts will take place in tandem with the exhibition, featuring among others the works of the Romantic composer, [[:de:Friedrich_Theodor_Fr\u00f6hlich|Friedrich Th\u00e9odor Froehlich]] (1803-1836), friend of Franz Schubert and an ancestor of the artist <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n=== Individual exhibitions ===\n[[File:Life Score.jpg|thumb|''Life score'' \u2013 Sculpture, mixed media, cardboard. Canvas 30 x 30 cm|upright=0.7]]\n\n* 2018 : Magie de la Renaissance&nbsp; Fondation Anne et Robert Bloch (FARB), Del\u00e9mont (Suisse) <ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Traversini|first=Dominique|date=October 2018|title=Florian Froehlich, Magie de la Renaissance|url=http://www.accrochages.ch/f/main.php?action=getArticle&articleId=1080|journal=Accrochage|volume=201|pages=11|via=}}</ref>\n\n* 2013 : ''World Theatre-Theatre World'', Achtzig Gallery for Contemporary Art,Berlin, Allemagne (d\u00e9cembre 2013).\n* 2012 : ''Tour de France, Jura stage on July 8, 2012: \"Finishing line\"'' : an installation with multiple sculptures and an old dusty bike.<ref name=\"video tdf\" />\n* 2007 : ''Galerie FARB'', Del\u00e9mont, Suisse<ref name=\"pharts2007\" />\n* 2005 : ''Galerie du Solstice'', Yverdon/Treycovagnes, Suisse\n* 2004 : ''Galerie du Solstice'', Yverdon/Treycovagnes, Suisse\n* 2003 : ''Galerie Catherine Clerc'', Lausanne, Suisse<ref>Article [https://archive.today/20130809162539/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/2003PhArtCathClerc.jpg Lausanne: Florian Froehlich by Catherine Clerc], ''phArt'' September 2003</ref>\n* 2002 : ''Galerie Paul Bov\u00e9e'', Del\u00e9mont, Suisse<ref name=\"FF-JM\" />\n* 1998 : ''Galerie Courant d'Art'', Chevenez, Suisse;<ref>Article [https://archive.today/20130809162516/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/1998QJCourantd'Art.jpg Du paysage \u00e0 l'abstraction], \u00e0 propos de l'exposition en 1998 \u00e0 la galerie Courant d'Art, ''Quotidien Jurassien'' 1998</ref> ''Galerie Paul Bov\u00e9e'', Del\u00e9mont, Suisse<ref>Article [https://archive.today/20130809162516/http://www.florianfroehlich.com/img/articles/1998BoveeQJ.jpg Florian Froehlich -Entre Abstraction et figuration], \u00e0 propos de l'exposition en 1998 \u00e0 la Galerie Bov\u00e9e \u00e0 Del\u00e9mont, ''Quotidien Jurassien'', 1998</ref>\n* 1997 : ''Galerie Pingeot-Gerbi'', Paris, France ; ''Galerie Catherine Clerc'', Lausanne, Suisse\n* 1994 : ''Galerie Catherine Clerc'', Lausanne, Suisse\n* 1993 : ''Galerie de l'Evole99, Neuch\u00e2tel, Suisse\n* 1992 : ''Fondation du Grand-Cachot-de-Vent'', Vall\u00e9e de La Br\u00e9vine, Suisse \n* 1991 : ''Galerie Jasmin'', Zurich, Suisse ; ''Galerie Black'', Lausanne, Suisse\n* 1989 : ''Galerie Jasmin'', Zurich, Suisse.\n\n=== Group exhibitions ===\n\n[[File:Lives in parallel.jpg|thumb|''Lives in parallel'' \u2013 Mixed media and ink. Canvas, 40x60 cm|upright=0.8]]\n[[File:Human Grape.jpg|thumb|''Human grape'' \u2013 Sculpture on wires. 19x 82 cm|upright=0.8]]\n\n* 2015 et 2017&nbsp;: Biennale de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Peintres et Sculpteurs Jurassiens SPSJ&nbsp; (<nowiki>http://www.spsj.ch</nowiki>)\n\n* 2015 : Galerie Dukan Contemporary Art, Leipzig\n\n* 2014: Group exhibitions, Achtzig Gallery for Contemporary Art, Berlin, Germany\n* 2013: MicroArt: Exhibition of recent work to suggest the use of microsculptures in Swiss watchmaking. Plejouse, October 29, 2013<ref name=\"lqj micro watch\" />\n* 2013 : ''Galerie FARB'', [[Del\u00e9mont]], Switzerland\n* 2011\u20132013 : ''Achtzig Gallery for Contemporary Art'', [[Berlin]] (plusieurs expositions en groupe)\n* 2010 : Exposition ''City Landscapes'', Achtzig Gallery for Contemporary Art, Berlin, Germany\n* 2009 : ''Swiss Museum of Stained Glass and Glass Art'', Romont (Vitromus\u00e9e), Romont. Verarte.ch exhibition; du 4 avril au 20 septembre 2009 ; ''Galerie Meistersch\u00fcler'', Berlin, Germany\n* 2007 : ''Galerie Art Service'', Ch\u00e2teau d'Eguilly, Eguilly, France ; ''Galerie Bleu de Chine'', Fleurier, Switzerland\n* 2006 : Permanent exhibition of artworks, ''Galerie Alain Aubry'', Paris, France\n* 2005 : ''Verarte.ch : Exhibition of Glass Art'', Elisabethenkirche, B\u00e2le, Switzerland\n* 2004 : ''Exposition au Mus\u00e9e suisse du vitrail et des arts du verre'', organis\u00e9 par Verarte.ch, Romont, Switzerland\n* 2002 : Invitation to take part in a nationwide exhibition Expo 02 ; Kunstmuseum, [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], Switzerland\n* 1998 : ''Centre d'Art en Face'', [[Porrentruy]], Switzerland\n* 1994 : ''120 artistes jurassiens'' (120 Jura artists), Del\u00e9mont, Switzerland\n* 1992 : ''Galerie 67'', [[Bern]], Switzerland\n\n== Publications ==\n* Florian FROEHLICH : Magie de la Renaissance. Un retour aux sources de la beaut\u00e9. octobre 2018. {{ISBN|978-2-8399-2487-0}} \n*Florian Froehlich : ''World Theatre \u2013 Theatre World''. \u00c9ditions Le renard par la queue, CH-1005 Lausanne, {{ISBN|978-2-940533-00-8}}\n* ''Glasmalerei f\u00fcr das 21. Jahrhundert : Malen mit Glas und Licht'', {{ISBN|978-3-00-040422-1}}\n* ''Biographisches Lexikon der Schweizer Kunst'', Verlag Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung, {{ISBN|3-85823-673-X}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://florianfroehlich.com/}}\n\n{{Orphan|date=September 2013}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Froehlich, Florian}}\n[[Category:Swiss contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Swiss painters]]\n[[Category:Swiss male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swiss painters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pf\u00e4ffikon, Z\u00fcrich]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florian_Froehlich"}
{"title_page": "Frank S. Black", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician and governor}}\n{{redirect|Governor Black|the short-serving Governor of Kentucky|James D. Black}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n|name          = Frank Swett Black\n|image         = Frank S Black.jpg\n|order         = 32nd\n|office        = Governor of New York\n|term_start    = January 1, 1897\n|term_end      = December 31, 1898\n|lieutenant    = [[Timothy L. Woodruff]]\n|predecessor   = [[Levi P. Morton]]\n|successor     = [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n|state2        =  [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district2     =  {{ushr|New York|19|19th}}\n|term_start2   = March 4, 1895\n|term_end2     = January 7, 1897\n|predecessor2  = [[Charles D. Haines]]\n|successor2    = [[Aaron Van Schaick Cochrane]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = near [[Limington, Maine]], U.S. \n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1913|3|22|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Troy, New York]], U.S.\n|resting_place = Frank S. Black Farm, [[Freedom, New Hampshire]]\n|spouse        = Lois B. Hamlin (m. 1879-1913, his death)\n|children      = 1\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education     = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|occupation    = Newspaper editor<br/>Attorney\n}}\n\n'''Frank Swett Black''' (March 8, 1853{{spnd}}March 22, 1913) was an American newspaper editor, lawyer and politician. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1895 to 1897, and the [[List of Governors of New York|32nd Governor of New York]] from 1897 to 1898.\n\nA native of [[Limington, Maine]], Black graduated from [[Dartmouth College]] in 1875 and moved to [[New York (state)|New York]], where he edited and reported for newspapers in [[Johnstown, New York|Johnstown]] and [[Troy, New York|Troy]]. He studied law, attained admission to the bar in 1879, and practiced in Troy.\n\nBlack became involved in politics by giving speeches for Republican candidates and serving as chairman of the party in [[Rensselaer County, New York|Rensselaer County]]. In 1894, he was a successful candidate for the [[United States House of Representatives]], and he served a partial term, March 1895 to January 1897. Black resigned before the end of his term because he had been elected governor.\n\nIn 1896, Black was the successful Republican nominee for governor. He served one term, January 1897 to December 1898. He was an unsuccessful candidate for renomination in 1898, losing at the party's state convention to [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who went on to win the general election.\n\nAfter leaving office, Black resumed the practice of law and remained active in politics as a campaign speaker for Republican candidates. He died in Troy on March 22, 1913 and was buried at his summer home, a farm in [[Freedom, New Hampshire]].\n\n==Early life==\nBlack was born near [[Limington, Maine]] on March 8, 1853, one of eleven children born to farmer Jacob Black and Charlotte (Butters) Black.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} His father moved the family to [[Alfred, Maine]] after accepting an appointment as keeper of the [[York County, Maine|York County]] jail.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black graduated from [[Lebanon, Maine|Lebanon]] Academy in 1871, then taught school while attending [[Dartmouth College]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1875, was an editor of all three of the school's student publications, and won prizes for oratory.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}} While in college, Black joined the [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] fraternity.{{sfn|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}}\n\n==Start of career==\nAfter completing his education, Black moved [[Rome, New York]], where he sold [[Chromolithography|chromolithographs]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He soon moved to [[Johnstown (city), New York|Johnstown, New York]] to become editor of the ''Johnstown Journal'', the editor of which was a member of the [[Stalwarts (politics)|Stalwart]] faction of Republicans who were loyal to [[Roscoe Conkling]].{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}} A member of the [[Half-Breeds (politics)|Half-Breed]] faction of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and follower of [[James G. Blaine]],{{sfn|''Bulletin to the Schools''}} Black changed the political stance of the paper while its publisher was out of town, for which he was promptly fired.{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}} He then moved to [[Troy, New York]], where he worked for the ''Troy Whig'' and ''Troy Times''.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} While working as a night reporter, clerk in the Troy post office, and [[process server]], he [[reading law|studied law]] at the firm of Robertson & Foster.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}} Black attained [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admission to the bar]] in 1879 and began to practice in Troy.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nIn 1888, Black campaigned for [[Benjamin Harrison]] for president.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In 1892, he campaigned for Harrison's reelection, but Harrison was defeated by former President [[Grover Cleveland]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} His continued political activities included serving as chairman of the Republican Party in [[rensselaer County, New York|Rensselaer County]].{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}} In March 1894, an election day dispute between Republicans and Democrats in Troy culminated with the [[murder of Robert Ross]], a Republican.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black assisted in the prosecution of the defendants, Democrats Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea and John McGough, who were convicted.{{sfn|\"'Electrical' Execution of 'Bat' Shea - 1896\"}}{{sfn|\"1896: Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea\"}} McGough was sentenced to 20 years in prison, and Shea was executed.{{sfn|\"'Electrical' Execution of 'Bat' Shea - 1896\"}}\n\n==U.S. House==\nLargely as the result of publicity from the Ross murder case,{{sfn|\"Excellent prospects\"}} in November 1894, Black was elected to the [[54th United States Congress]], representing [[New York's 19th congressional district]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He served from March 4, 1895 to January 7, 1897, when he resigned because he had been elected governor.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} During his House term, Black was a member of the Committee on Pacific Railroads and the [[United States Court of Private Land Claims#Origins|Committee on Private Land Claims]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He was a delegate to the [[1896 Republican National Convention]] and supported [[William McKinley]] for president.{{sfn|''New York State Men''}}\n\n==Governor==\nBlack was elected governor [[New York state election, 1896|in 1896]] and served from January 1, 1897 to December 31, 1898.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} A highlight of his governorship was completion of construction on the [[New York State Capitol]], which had fallen far behind schedule and had been plagued with cost overruns.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''New York State Men''}}\n\nAs governor, Black advocated for conservation of the area now known as the [[Adirondack State Park]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} As part of this effort, he oversaw the establishment of the [[History of the New York State College of Forestry]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} During Black's governorship, the boroughs that now make up [[New York City]] were consolidated into one municipality.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nBlack also oversaw New York's participation in the [[Spanish-American War]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Under his leadership, 16,000 soldiers were raised, trained, and equipped for accession into the [[United States Army]] as it expanded for the war.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In addition, he successfully advocated for election reforms, including allowing soldiers to vote while they were out of state or outside the United States.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nIn his 1894 and 1896 campaigns, Black had been nominated at Republican conventions by political operative Louis F. Payn, who was widely regarded as a corrupt associate of [[Thomas C. Platt]], the boss of New York State's Republican Party.{{sfn|\"The Appointment of Payn\"}} As governor, Black caused a controversy when appointed Payn as [[New York State Insurance Department|state insurance superintendent]].{{sfn|\"The Appointment of Payn\"}} Despite criticism from advocates of good government and civil service reform, Black continued to support Payn.{{sfn|\"The Appointment of Payn\"}} Even though he backed Payn, Black incurred Platt's displeasure when Black successfully opposed a bill Platt favored, which would have banned from newspapers editorial cartoons critical of state government officials.{{sfn|\"Obituary Notes: Frank S. Black\"}} (As governor, [[Theodore Roosevelt]] won a showdown with Platt over Payn's reappointment, which resulted in the selection of another candidate.{{sfn|''Theodore Roosevelt Takes Charge''}})\n\nLate in Black's term, state officials were accused of squandering taxpayer money on a project to expand the [[Erie Canal]], which had come to be regarded as a [[boondoggle]] because of delays and excessive costs.{{sfn|\"Is Black's Gang Trying to Paralyze the Erie Canal?\"}} Black's chances for reelection were jeopardized, so Republicans replaced him as their 1898 gubernatorial nominee with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who had recently attained hero status in Cuba during the [[Spanish-American War]].{{sfn|\"Roosevelt and Woodruff\"}} Roosevelt won the November general election by narrowly defeating Democratic nominee [[Augustus Van Wyck]].{{sfn|\"Roosevelt Upsets Crokerism!\"}} In 1899, an investigating commission appointed by Black, in conjunction with two special counsels appointed by Roosevelt, exonerated those involved of criminal wrongdoing.{{sfn|\"Report on the Canals\"}}\n\n==Later life==\n[[File:Frank Swett Black (New York governor).jpg|thumb|Portrait by artist George Hughes of [[Albany, New York]]]]\nAfter leaving office, Black resumed his law practice.{{sfn|\"Murder Trials Unsought\"}} Among the noteworthy cases in which he was involved, Black took part in the defense of Roland B. Molineaux in the famed ''[[People v. Molineux]]'' case.{{sfn|\"Murder Trials Unsought\"}} After Molineaux was convicted of murder, the conviction was overturned and he won an acquittal at retrial.{{sfn|\"Murder Trials Unsought\"}} The case was the source of the well-known \"[[Molineux hearing|Molineux rule]]\" which limits the ability of prosecutors to use prior crimes as proof that a defendant committed the crime with which he is charged{{sfn|\"The 'Molineux Rule'\"}}. Black also took part in the defense of [[Caleb Powers]] for the assassination of Kentucky governor [[William Goebel]].{{sfn|\"The Case of Caleb Powers\"}}\n\nBlack maintained his interest in politics even after leaving office.{{sfn|\"Odell Yields to Depew\"}} He was a delegate to the [[1904 Republican National Convention]], and nominated President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] for election to a full term.{{sfn|\"Speech Made by Frank S. Black\"}} Later that year, he was a candidate for the Republican nomination for [[United States Senator]], but withdrew in favor of incumbent [[Chauncey Depew]], who went on to win reelection.{{sfn|\"Odell Yields to Depew\"}} [[1908 Republican National Convention|In 1908]], Black, who had fallen out with Roosevelt, supported [[Charles Evans Hughes]] for president over Roosevelt's choice, [[William Howard Taft]].{{sfn|\"This Day in 1908\"}}\n\nBlack remained a popular and sought-after speaker for political events and other occasions.{{sfn|\"Ex-Gov. Black at the Lyric Tonight\"}} Among his best-known orations was a 1903 commemorative eulogy for [[Abraham Lincoln]] delivered to the Republican Club of the City of New York during its annual Lincoln's Birthday celebration.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''Proceedings at the Seventeenth Annual Lincoln Dinner''}}\n\n==Death and burial==\nBlack died from heart disease at his home in Troy on March 22, 1913.{{sfn|Sulzer in Tribute to Frank S. Black}} He was cremated and his ashes were buried at his summer home, a farm in [[Freedom, New Hampshire]].{{sfn|''New Hampshire Farms''}}{{sfn|''Artwork Restoration Project''}}\n\n==Family==\nIn 1879, Black married Lois B. Hamlin (1858-1931) of [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]], whom he had met while teaching school.{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}}{{sfn|\"Death Notice, Mrs. Lois Hamlin Black\"}} They were the parents of a son, Arthur (1880-1953).{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}}{{sfn|\"Arthur Black, Referee in Bankruptcy\"}}\n\n==Honors==\nIn 1898, Black received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from Dartmouth College.{{sfn|''New York State Men''}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |last=Artwork Restoration Committee |date=2001 |title=Artwork Restoration Project |url=https://www.nycourts.gov/history/legal-history-new-york/documents/Courthouse_Rensselear-County-Artwork-Restoration.pdf |location=Troy, NY |publisher=Friends of the Rensselaer County Court House |page=6 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Artwork Restoration Project''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bachelder |first=N. J., Secretary |date=1909 |title=New Hampshire Farms for Summer Homes |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XAh2tp0SKT8C&pg=PA45 |location=Concord, NH |publisher=State Board of Agriculture |page=45 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''New Hampshire Farms''}}}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Cutter |editor-first=William Richard |date=1918 |title=American Biography: A New Cyclopedia |volume=II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tmoKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA347 |location=New York, NY |publisher=The American Historical Society |pages=347-348 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''American Biography''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity |date=1890 |title=Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Feo140qPrb4C&pg=PA675 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Council Publishing Company |page=675 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}}}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Manning |editor1-first=James Hilton |editor2-last=Hills |editor2-first=Frederick Simon |date=1906 |title=New York State Men: Biographic Studies and Character Portraits |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F-I-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA26 |location=Albany, NY |publisher=The Argus Company |page=26 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''New York State Men''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Murlin |first=Edgar L. |date=1898 |title=The New York Red Book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yW5IAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA91 |location=Albany, NY |publisher=James B. Lyon |page=91 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''The New York Red Book''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Republican Club of the City of New York |date=1903 |title=Proceedings at the Seventeenth Annual Lincoln Dinner |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PG0DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA15 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Freytag Printing |page=15 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Proceedings at the Seventeenth Annual Lincoln Dinner''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Whitelaw |first=Nancy |date=1992 |title=Theodore Roosevelt Takes Charge |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=txSkrdW3sIIC&pg=PA99 |location=Morton Grove, IL |publisher=Albert Whitman & Company |pages=99-100 |isbn=978-0-8075-7849-0 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Theodore Roosevelt Takes Charge''}}}}\n\n===Magazines===\n*{{cite magazine |date=March 29, 2013 |title=Obituary Notes: Frank S. Black |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Px87AQAAMAAJ&pg=PR102 |magazine=Editor and Publisher |location=New York, NY |page=102 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Obituary Notes: Frank S. Black\"}}}}\n*{{cite magazine |date=September 15, 1923 |title=Governors of New York: Frank S. Black, 1897-98 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U1QwAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA61 |magazine=Bulletin to the Schools |location=Albany, NY |publisher=The University of the State of New York |page=61 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Bulletin to the Schools''}}}}\n\n===Internet===\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/northcountry/html/crimes/batshea3.htm |title='Electrical' Execution of 'Bat' Shea - 1896 |website=Correction History.org |publisher=New York Correction History Society |access-date=April 23, 2020 |ref={{sfnRef|\"'Electrical' Execution of 'Bat' Shea - 1896\"}}}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.executedtoday.com/2014/02/11/1896-bartholomew-bat-shea/ |title=1896: Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea, political machine ballot-stuffer |last=Headsman |date=February 11, 2014 |website=Executed Today.com |access-date=April 23, 2020 |ref={{sfnRef|\"1896: Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea\"}}}}\n\n===Newspapers===\n*{{cite news |date=October 8, 1894 |title=Excellent prospects for an honest election in Troy |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49367824/honest-election/ |work=[[New-York Tribune]] |location=New York, NY |page=6 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Excellent prospects\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=February 13, 1897 |title=The Appointment of Payn |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tu85AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA456 |work=The Literary Digest |location=New York, NY |page=456 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"The Appointment of Payn\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=May 16, 1898 |title=Is Black's Gang Trying to Paralyze the Erie Canal? |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49439068/blacks-gang/ |work=Buffalo Evening Times |location=Buffalo, NY |page=7 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Is Black's Gang Trying to Paralyze the Erie Canal?\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=September 28, 1898 |title=Roosevelt and Woodruff Will Lead to Victory |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49439552/roosevelt-and-woodruff/ |work=Buffalo Evening News |location=Buffalo, NY |page=1 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Roosevelt and Woodruff\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=November 3, 1898 |title=Roosevelt Upsets Crokerism! |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49439830/roosevelt-upsets-crokerism/ |work=Buffalo Evening News |location=Buffalo, NY |page=1 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Roosevelt Upsets Crokerism!\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=July 21, 1899 |title=Report on the Canals: Commission Says testimony Does Not Warrant Prosecutions |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49440792/report-on-the-canals/ |work=[[The Herald-Mail|The Mail]] |location=Hagerstown, MD |page=14 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Report on the Canals\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=June 23, 1904 |title=Speech Made by Frank S. Black Nominating Theodore Roosevelt for the Presidency |url=https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/?a=d&d=kingstondaily19040623.2.33 |work=[[Daily Freeman]] |location=Kingston, NY |page=3 |via=Hudson River Valley Heritage |ref={{sfnRef|\"Speech Made by Frank S. Black\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=December 30, 1904 |title=Odell Yields to Depew; Senatorship Fight Ends |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/12/30/101174295.html?pageNumber=1 |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York, NY |page=1 |via=TimesMachine |ref={{sfnRef|\"Odell Yields to Depew\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=May 1, 1905 |title=Murder Trials Unsought |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j1EbAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA5-PA35 |work=The Bar |location=Morgantown, WV |page=35 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Murder Trials Unsought\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |last= |first= |date=June 24, 1905 |title=The Case of Caleb Powers |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXdPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA829 |work=The Christian Work and Evangelist |location=New York, NY |page=829 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"The Case of Caleb Powers\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=November 3, 1906 |title=Ex-Gov. Black at the Lyric Tonight |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49441616/ex-gov-black/ |work=Buffalo Evening News |location=Buffalo, NY |page=13 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Ex-Gov. Black at the Lyric Tonight\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=March 22, 1913 |title=Sulzer in Tribute to Frank S. Black |url= |work=[[Brooklyn Eagle]] |location=New York, NY |page=3 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|Sulzer in Tribute to Frank S. Black}}}}\n*{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 11, 1931 |title=Death Notice, Mrs. Lois Hamlin Black |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49436643/obituary-for-lois-hamlin-hamlin-aged/ |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |location=Boston, MA |page=21 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Death Notice, Mrs. Lois Hamlin Black\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=May 5, 1953 |title=Arthur Black, Referee in Bankruptcy, 73, Died in Winchester |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49434387/obituary-for-arthur-black-referee-aged/ |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |location=Boston, MA |page=16 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Arthur Black, Referee in Bankruptcy\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |last=Gilbert |first=Kevin |date=January 18, 2008 |title=This Day in 1908 in The Record: Jan. 18 |url=https://www.troyrecord.com/news/this-day-in-1908-in-the-record-jan-18/article_1a13f2cf-b2a5-5337-ae78-f200b43c9251.html |work=[[The Record (Troy)|The Record]] |location=Troy, NY |ref={{sfnRef|\"This Day in 1908\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |last=Friedman |first=Rose |date=January 29, 2020 |title=How The 'Molineux Rule' Permits Certain Witnesses In The Harvey Weinstein Trial |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800938076/how-the-molineux-rule-permits-certain-witnesses-in-the-harvey-weinstein-trial |work=NPR.org |location=Washington, DC |ref={{sfnRef|\"The 'Molineux Rule'\"}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|B000496}}\n*{{Findagrave|6848745}}\n*[https://www.nga.org/governor/frank-swett-black/ Biography, Frank Swett Black] at National Governors Association\n*[https://empirestateplaza.ny.gov/hall-governors/frank-s-black Frank S. Black] at New York State Hall of Governors\n*[http://masonrytoday.com/index.php?new_month=03&new_day=8&new_year=2015 Today in Masonic History: Frank Swett Black is Born] at MasonryToday.com\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York |\n  district=19 |\n  before=[[Charles Delemere Haines|Charles D. Haines]] |\n  after=[[Aaron V. S. Cochrane]] |\n  years=1895\u20131897\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Governor of New York]] | before = [[Levi P. Morton]] | after = [[Theodore Roosevelt]] | years = 1897\u20131898}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of New York}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Frank Swett}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Limington, Maine]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Troy, New York]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governors of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Burials in New Hampshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician and governor}}\n{{redirect|Governor Black|the short-serving Governor of Kentucky|James D. Black}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n|name          = Frank Swett Black\n|image         = Frank S Black.jpg\n|order         = 32nd\n|office        = Governor of New York\n|term_start    = January 1, 1897\n|term_end      = December 31, 1898\n|lieutenant    = [[Timothy L. Woodruff]]\n|predecessor   = [[Levi P. Morton]]\n|successor     = [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n|state2        =  [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district2     =  {{ushr|New York|19|19th}}\n|term_start2   = March 4, 1895\n|term_end2     = January 7, 1897\n|predecessor2  = [[Charles D. Haines]]\n|successor2    = [[Aaron Van Schaick Cochrane]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = near [[Limington, Maine]], U.S. \n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1913|3|22|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Troy, New York]], U.S.\n|resting_place = Frank S. Black Farm, [[Freedom, New Hampshire]]\n|spouse        = Lois B. Hamlin (m. 1879-1913, his death)\n|children      = 1\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education     = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|occupation    = Newspaper editor<br/>Attorney\n}}\n\n'''Frank Swett Black''' (March 8, 1853{{spnd}}March 22, 1913) was an American newspaper editor, lawyer and politician. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1895 to 1897, and the [[List of Governors of New York|32nd Governor of New York]] from 1897 to 1898.\n\nA native of [[Limington, Maine]], Black graduated from [[Dartmouth College]] in 1875 and moved to [[New York (state)|New York]], where he edited and reported for newspapers in [[Johnstown, New York|Johnstown]] and [[Troy, New York|Troy]]. He studied law, attained admission to the bar in 1879, and practiced in Troy.\n\nBlack became involved in politics by giving speeches for Republican candidates and serving as chairman of the party in [[Rensselaer County, New York|Rensselaer County]]. In 1894, he was a successful candidate for the [[United States House of Representatives]], and he served a partial term, March 1895 to January 1897. Black resigned before the end of his term because he had been elected governor.\n\nIn 1896, Black was the successful Republican nominee for governor. He served one term, January 1897 to December 1898. He was an unsuccessful candidate for renomination in 1898, losing at the party's state convention to [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who went on to win the general election.\n\nAfter leaving office, Black resumed the practice of law and remained active in politics as a campaign speaker for Republican candidates. He died in Troy on March 22, 1913 and was buried at his summer home, a farm in [[Freedom, New Hampshire]].\n\n==Early life==\nBlack was born near [[Limington, Maine]] on March 8, 1853, one of eleven children born to farmer Jacob Black and Charlotte (Butters) Black.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} His father moved the family to [[Alfred, Maine]] after accepting an appointment as keeper of the [[York County, Maine|York County]] jail.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black graduated from [[Lebanon, Maine|Lebanon]] Academy in 1871, then taught school while attending [[Dartmouth College]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1875, was an editor of all three of the school's student publications, and won prizes for oratory.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}} While in college, Black joined the [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] fraternity.{{sfn|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}}\n\n==Start of career==\nAfter completing his education, Black moved [[Rome, New York]], where he sold [[Chromolithography|chromolithographs]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He soon moved to [[Johnstown (city), New York|Johnstown, New York]] to become editor of the ''Johnstown Journal'', the editor of which was a member of the [[Stalwarts (politics)|Stalwart]] faction of Republicans who were loyal to [[Roscoe Conkling]].{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}} A member of the [[Half-Breeds (politics)|Half-Breed]] faction of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and follower of [[James G. Blaine]],{{sfn|''Bulletin to the Schools''}} Black changed the political stance of the paper while its publisher was out of town, for which he was promptly fired.{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}} He then moved to [[Troy, New York]], where he worked for the ''Troy Whig'' and ''Troy Times''.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} While working as a night reporter, clerk in the Troy post office, and [[process server]], he [[reading law|studied law]] at the firm of Robertson & Foster.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}} Black attained [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admission to the bar]] in 1879 and began to practice in Troy.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nIn 1888, Black campaigned for [[Benjamin Harrison]] for president.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In 1892, he campaigned for Harrison's reelection, but Harrison was defeated by former President [[Grover Cleveland]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} His continued political activities included serving as chairman of the Republican Party in [[rensselaer County, New York|Rensselaer County]].{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}} In March 1894, an election day dispute between Republicans and Democrats in Troy culminated with the [[murder of Robert Ross]], a Republican.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Black assisted in the prosecution of the defendants, Democrats Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea and John McGough, who were convicted.{{sfn|\"'Electrical' Execution of 'Bat' Shea - 1896\"}}{{sfn|\"1896: Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea\"}} McGough was sentenced to 20 years in prison, and Shea was executed.{{sfn|\"'Electrical' Execution of 'Bat' Shea - 1896\"}}\n\n==U.S. House==\nLargely as the result of publicity from the Ross murder case, in November 1894,{{sfn|\"Excellent prospects\"}} Black was elected to the [[54th United States Congress]], representing [[New York's 19th congressional district]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He served from March 4, 1895 to January 7, 1897, when he resigned because he had been elected governor.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} During his House term, Black was a member of the Committee on Pacific Railroads and the [[United States Court of Private Land Claims#Origins|Committee on Private Land Claims]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} He was a delegate to the [[1896 Republican National Convention]] and supported [[William McKinley]] for president.{{sfn|''New York State Men''}}\n\n==Governor==\nBlack was elected governor [[New York state election, 1896|in 1896]] and served from January 1, 1897 to December 31, 1898.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} A highlight of his governorship was completion of construction on the [[New York State Capitol]], which had fallen far behind schedule and had been plagued with cost overruns.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''New York State Men''}}\n\nAs governor, Black advocated for conservation of the area now known as the [[Adirondack State Park]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} As part of this effort, he oversaw the establishment of the [[History of the New York State College of Forestry]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} During Black's governorship, the boroughs that now make up [[New York City]] were consolidated into one municipality.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nBlack also oversaw New York's participation in the [[Spanish-American War]].{{sfn|''American Biography''}} Under his leadership, 16,000 soldiers were raised, trained, and equipped for accession into the [[United States Army]] as it expanded for the war.{{sfn|''American Biography''}} In addition, he successfully advocated for election reforms, including allowing soldiers to vote while they were out of state or outside the United States.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}\n\nIn his 1894 and 1896 campaigns, Black had been nominated at Republican conventions by political operative Louis F. Payn, who was widely regarded as a corrupt associate of [[Thomas C. Platt]], the boss of New York State's Republican Party.{{sfn|\"The Appointment of Payn\"}} As governor, Black caused a controversy when appointed Payn as [[New York State Insurance Department|state insurance superintendent]].{{sfn|\"The Appointment of Payn\"}} Despite criticism from advocates of good government and civil service reform, Black continued to support Payn.{{sfn|\"The Appointment of Payn\"}} Even though he backed Payn, Black incurred Platt's displeasure when Black successfully opposed a bill Platt favored, which would have banned from newspapers editorial cartoons critical of state government officials.{{sfn|\"Obituary Notes: Frank S. Black\"}} (As governor, [[Theodore Roosevelt]] won a showdown with Platt over Payn's reappointment, which resulted in the selection of another candidate.{{sfn|''Theodore Roosevelt Takes Charge''}})\n\nLate in Black's term, state officials were accused of squandering taxpayer money on a project to expand the [[Erie Canal]], which had come to be regarded as a [[boondoggle]] because of delays and excessive costs.{{sfn|\"Is Black's Gang Trying to Paralyze the Erie Canal?\"}} Black's chances for reelection were jeopardized, so Republicans replaced him as their 1898 gubernatorial nominee with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who had recently attained hero status in Cuba during the [[Spanish-American War]].{{sfn|\"Roosevelt and Woodruff\"}} Roosevelt won the November general election by narrowly defeating Democratic nominee [[Augustus Van Wyck]].{{sfn|\"Roosevelt Upsets Crokerism!\"}} In 1899, an investigating commission appointed by Black, in conjunction with two special counsels appointed by Roosevelt, exonerated those involved of criminal wrongdoing.{{sfn|\"Report on the Canals\"}}\n\n==Later life==\n[[File:Frank Swett Black (New York governor).jpg|thumb|Portrait by artist George Hughes of [[Albany, New York]]]]\nAfter leaving office, Black resumed his law practice.{{sfn|\"Murder Trials Unsought\"}} Among the noteworthy cases in which he was involved, Black took part in the defense of Roland B. Molineaux in the famed ''[[People v. Molineux]]'' case.{{sfn|\"Murder Trials Unsought\"}} After Molineaux was convicted of murder, the conviction was overturned and he won an acquittal at retrial.{{sfn|\"Murder Trials Unsought\"}} The case was the source of the well-known \"[[Molineux hearing|Molineux rule]]\" which limits the ability of prosecutors to use prior crimes as proof that a defendant committed the crime with which he is charged{{sfn|\"The 'Molineux Rule'\"}}. Black also took part in the defense of [[Caleb Powers]] for the assassination of Kentucky governor [[William Goebel]].{{sfn|\"The Case of Caleb Powers\"}}\n\nBlack maintained his interest in politics even after leaving office.{{sfn|\"Odell Yields to Depew\"}} He was a delegate to the [[1904 Republican National Convention]], and nominated President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] for election to a full term.{{sfn|\"Speech Made by Frank S. Black\"}} Later that year, he was a candidate for the Republican nomination for [[United States Senator]], but withdrew in favor of incumbent [[Chauncey Depew]], who went on to win reelection.{{sfn|\"Odell Yields to Depew\"}} [[1908 Republican National Convention|In 1908]], Black, who had fallen out with Roosevelt, supported [[Charles Evans Hughes]] for president over Roosevelt's choice, [[William Howard Taft]].{{sfn|\"This Day in 1908\"}}\n\nBlack remained a popular and sought-after speaker for political events and other occasions.{{sfn|\"Ex-Gov. Black at the Lyric Tonight\"}} Among his best-known orations was a 1903 commemorative eulogy for [[Abraham Lincoln]] delivered to the Republican Club of the City of New York during its annual Lincoln's Birthday celebration.{{sfn|''American Biography''}}{{sfn|''Proceedings at the Seventeenth Annual Lincoln Dinner''}}\n\n==Death and burial==\nBlack died from heart disease at his home in Troy on March 22, 1913.{{sfn|Sulzer in Tribute to Frank S. Black}} He was cremated and his ashes were buried at his summer home, a farm in [[Freedom, New Hampshire]].{{sfn|''New Hampshire Farms''}}{{sfn|''Artwork Restoration Project''}}\n\n==Family==\nIn 1879, Black married Lois B. Hamlin (1858-1931) of [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]], whom he had met while teaching school.{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}}{{sfn|\"Death Notice, Mrs. Lois Hamlin Black\"}} They were the parents of a son, Arthur (1880-1953).{{sfn|''The New York Red Book''}}{{sfn|\"Arthur Black, Referee in Bankruptcy\"}}\n\n==Honors==\nIn 1898, Black received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from Dartmouth College.{{sfn|''New York State Men''}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |last=Artwork Restoration Committee |date=2001 |title=Artwork Restoration Project |url=https://www.nycourts.gov/history/legal-history-new-york/documents/Courthouse_Rensselear-County-Artwork-Restoration.pdf |location=Troy, NY |publisher=Friends of the Rensselaer County Court House |page=6 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Artwork Restoration Project''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bachelder |first=N. J., Secretary |date=1909 |title=New Hampshire Farms for Summer Homes |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XAh2tp0SKT8C&pg=PA45 |location=Concord, NH |publisher=State Board of Agriculture |page=45 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''New Hampshire Farms''}}}}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Cutter |editor-first=William Richard |date=1918 |title=American Biography: A New Cyclopedia |volume=II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tmoKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA347 |location=New York, NY |publisher=The American Historical Society |pages=347-348 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''American Biography''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity |date=1890 |title=Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Feo140qPrb4C&pg=PA675 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Council Publishing Company |page=675 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Catalogue of the Delta Kappa Epsilon Fraternity''}}}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Manning |editor1-first=James Hilton |editor2-last=Hills |editor2-first=Frederick Simon |date=1906 |title=New York State Men: Biographic Studies and Character Portraits |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F-I-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA26 |location=Albany, NY |publisher=The Argus Company |page=26 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''New York State Men''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Murlin |first=Edgar L. |date=1898 |title=The New York Red Book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yW5IAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA91 |location=Albany, NY |publisher=James B. Lyon |page=91 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''The New York Red Book''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Republican Club of the City of New York |date=1903 |title=Proceedings at the Seventeenth Annual Lincoln Dinner |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PG0DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA15 |location=New York, NY |publisher=Freytag Printing |page=15 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Proceedings at the Seventeenth Annual Lincoln Dinner''}}}}\n*{{cite book |last=Whitelaw |first=Nancy |date=1992 |title=Theodore Roosevelt Takes Charge |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=txSkrdW3sIIC&pg=PA99 |location=Morton Grove, IL |publisher=Albert Whitman & Company |pages=99-100 |isbn=978-0-8075-7849-0 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Theodore Roosevelt Takes Charge''}}}}\n\n===Magazines===\n*{{cite magazine |date=March 29, 2013 |title=Obituary Notes: Frank S. Black |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Px87AQAAMAAJ&pg=PR102 |magazine=Editor and Publisher |location=New York, NY |page=102 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Obituary Notes: Frank S. Black\"}}}}\n*{{cite magazine |date=September 15, 1923 |title=Governors of New York: Frank S. Black, 1897-98 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U1QwAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA61 |magazine=Bulletin to the Schools |location=Albany, NY |publisher=The University of the State of New York |page=61 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|''Bulletin to the Schools''}}}}\n\n===Internet===\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.correctionhistory.org/northcountry/html/crimes/batshea3.htm |title='Electrical' Execution of 'Bat' Shea - 1896 |website=Correction History.org |publisher=New York Correction History Society |access-date=April 23, 2020 |ref={{sfnRef|\"'Electrical' Execution of 'Bat' Shea - 1896\"}}}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.executedtoday.com/2014/02/11/1896-bartholomew-bat-shea/ |title=1896: Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea, political machine ballot-stuffer |last=Headsman |date=February 11, 2014 |website=Executed Today.com |access-date=April 23, 2020 |ref={{sfnRef|\"1896: Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea\"}}}}\n\n===Newspapers===\n*{{cite news |date=October 8, 1894 |title=Excellent prospects for an honest election in Troy |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49367824/honest-election/ |work=[[New-York Tribune]] |location=New York, NY |page=6 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Excellent prospects\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=February 13, 1897 |title=The Appointment of Payn |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tu85AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA456 |work=The Literary Digest |location=New York, NY |page=456 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"The Appointment of Payn\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=May 16, 1898 |title=Is Black's Gang Trying to Paralyze the Erie Canal? |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49439068/blacks-gang/ |work=Buffalo Evening Times |location=Buffalo, NY |page=7 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Is Black's Gang Trying to Paralyze the Erie Canal?\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=September 28, 1898 |title=Roosevelt and Woodruff Will Lead to Victory |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49439552/roosevelt-and-woodruff/ |work=Buffalo Evening News |location=Buffalo, NY |page=1 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Roosevelt and Woodruff\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=November 3, 1898 |title=Roosevelt Upsets Crokerism! |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49439830/roosevelt-upsets-crokerism/ |work=Buffalo Evening News |location=Buffalo, NY |page=1 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Roosevelt Upsets Crokerism!\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=July 21, 1899 |title=Report on the Canals: Commission Says testimony Does Not Warrant Prosecutions |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49440792/report-on-the-canals/ |work=[[The Herald-Mail|The Mail]] |location=Hagerstown, MD |page=14 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Report on the Canals\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=June 23, 1904 |title=Speech Made by Frank S. Black Nominating Theodore Roosevelt for the Presidency |url=https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/?a=d&d=kingstondaily19040623.2.33 |work=[[Daily Freeman]] |location=Kingston, NY |page=3 |via=Hudson River Valley Heritage |ref={{sfnRef|\"Speech Made by Frank S. Black\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=December 30, 1904 |title=Odell Yields to Depew; Senatorship Fight Ends |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/12/30/101174295.html?pageNumber=1 |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York, NY |page=1 |via=TimesMachine |ref={{sfnRef|\"Odell Yields to Depew\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=May 1, 1905 |title=Murder Trials Unsought |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j1EbAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA5-PA35 |work=The Bar |location=Morgantown, WV |page=35 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Murder Trials Unsought\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |last= |first= |date=June 24, 1905 |title=The Case of Caleb Powers |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXdPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA829 |work=The Christian Work and Evangelist |location=New York, NY |page=829 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"The Case of Caleb Powers\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=November 3, 1906 |title=Ex-Gov. Black at the Lyric Tonight |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49441616/ex-gov-black/ |work=Buffalo Evening News |location=Buffalo, NY |page=13 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Ex-Gov. Black at the Lyric Tonight\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=March 22, 1913 |title=Sulzer in Tribute to Frank S. Black |url= |work=[[Brooklyn Eagle]] |location=New York, NY |page=3 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|Sulzer in Tribute to Frank S. Black}}}}\n*{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 11, 1931 |title=Death Notice, Mrs. Lois Hamlin Black |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49436643/obituary-for-lois-hamlin-hamlin-aged/ |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |location=Boston, MA |page=21 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Death Notice, Mrs. Lois Hamlin Black\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=May 5, 1953 |title=Arthur Black, Referee in Bankruptcy, 73, Died in Winchester |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/49434387/obituary-for-arthur-black-referee-aged/ |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |location=Boston, MA |page=16 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Arthur Black, Referee in Bankruptcy\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |last=Gilbert |first=Kevin |date=January 18, 2008 |title=This Day in 1908 in The Record: Jan. 18 |url=https://www.troyrecord.com/news/this-day-in-1908-in-the-record-jan-18/article_1a13f2cf-b2a5-5337-ae78-f200b43c9251.html |work=[[The Record (Troy)|The Record]] |location=Troy, NY |ref={{sfnRef|\"This Day in 1908\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |last=Friedman |first=Rose |date=January 29, 2020 |title=How The 'Molineux Rule' Permits Certain Witnesses In The Harvey Weinstein Trial |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/29/800938076/how-the-molineux-rule-permits-certain-witnesses-in-the-harvey-weinstein-trial |work=NPR.org |location=Washington, DC |ref={{sfnRef|\"The 'Molineux Rule'\"}}}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|B000496}}\n*{{Findagrave|6848745}}\n*[https://www.nga.org/governor/frank-swett-black/ Biography, Frank Swett Black] at National Governors Association\n*[https://empirestateplaza.ny.gov/hall-governors/frank-s-black Frank S. Black] at New York State Hall of Governors\n*[http://masonrytoday.com/index.php?new_month=03&new_day=8&new_year=2015 Today in Masonic History: Frank Swett Black is Born] at MasonryToday.com\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York |\n  district=19 |\n  before=[[Charles Delemere Haines|Charles D. Haines]] |\n  after=[[Aaron V. S. Cochrane]] |\n  years=1895\u20131897\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Governor of New York]] | before = [[Levi P. Morton]] | after = [[Theodore Roosevelt]] | years = 1897\u20131898}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of New York}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Frank Swett}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Limington, Maine]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Troy, New York]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governors of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Burials in New Hampshire]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eU.S. House", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_S._Black"}
{"title_page": "Bharwad", "text_new": "{{short description|Hindu caste found in the state of Gujarat in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Member of the Bharwad community of India.jpg|thumb|Member of the Bharwad community of India]]\nThe '''Bharwad''' are a [[Hindu]] YADAV [[caste]] found in the state of [[Gujarat]] in India.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=1nVCAAAAYAAJ&q=%E0%A4%AD%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A1+%E0%A4%9C%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF&dq=%E0%A4%AD%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A1+%E0%A4%9C%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF | title=Vanyaj\u0101ti, \u092d\u093e\u0917 16,\u0938\u092e\u0938\u094d\u092f\u093e 2 | year=1968 | publisher=Bharatiya Adimjati Sevak Sangh., 1968| accessdate=23 Apr 2009| page=79}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe Bharwad name may derive from the [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] word ''bharawad'', constructed from ''bhara'' (sheep) and ''wad'' (a compound or enclosure). ''[[Gadaria]]'' is another word that may have the same origin. In the [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra region]] of western Gujarat they exist as two [[endogamy|endogamous]] groups, known as the Mota Bhai (Motabhai) and the Nana Bhai (Nanabhai). According to the [[Anthropological Survey of India]]'s ''People of India'' series, Bharwads in the Saurashtra region often append ''[[Ahir]]'' to their names, while in south Gujarat it is common to see ''[[Patel]]'' appended.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n== Origin ==\nThe Bharwads consider themselves to be descended from the mythological [[Nandvanshi]] line that began with [[Nanda (mythology)|Nanda]], the foster-father of [[Krishna]]. Legend has it that Nanda came from [[Gokul]], in [[Mathura district]], and passed through Saurashtra on his way to [[Dwarka]].{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|p=84|ps=}} According to their traditions, the Bharwads were at some time based around [[Mathura]] and migrated to [[Mewar]] before later spreading out in Gujarat.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}} Sudipta Mitra considers their move to Gujarat to have been predicated by a desire to keep away from the [[Muslim]] invasion of [[Sind]]. They arrived in the northern town of [[Banaskantha]] in 961 CE and later spread out to Saurashtra and other areas.{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|p=84|ps=}}\n\nThere are other theories of origin. These include that they are an offshoot of the [[Bharude]] cattle-herders of [[Madhya Pradesh]] and that they are descendants of Anavil Bharwad, who helped a [[Chavda]] prince regain his kingdom. It is also possible that they are related to the Ahirs of Gujarat, with whom they share a common traditional occupation.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n== Divisions ==\nOf the various reasons given for the division between Motabhai and Nanabhai, the most popular is that two shepherd brothers were ordered by [[Krishna]] to take their flocks to different places. The older of the brothers went on to marry a Bharwad woman while the other married a [[Koli people|Koli]]. Since the latter was a marriage outside the community, the offspring were deemed to be [[untouchability|ritually polluted]]. Thus the Motabhai (literally, \"big brother\") descend from the first and the Nanabhai (\"little brother\") from the latter.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=147|ps=}}\n\nThe Bharwads have numerous subgroups known as ''ataks'' or ''guls'' (clans) whose main purpose is to determine eligibility for marriage. A constrained [[exogamy]] is practised between clans{{efn|For example, the Rathadia, Jadav and Yadav clans of the Mota Bhai consider that they are socially superior to the other clans and will only marry between themselves.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}}} but endogamy exists between the two Saurashtrian divisions despite there being no other social constraints on mixing. The Saurashtra Bharwads also hold a higher status than those in the south and thus marriage between the two regional groups operates in one direction only: daughters of southern Bharwads can marry into the family of those from Saurashtra.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n<!--PLEASE DO NOT ADD ANY FURTHER CLANS HERE UNLESS THEY ARE SOURCED-->\nClans of the Mota Bhai Bharwads include the Babha, Bathela, Colthar, Dabi, Dhangia, Dharangia, Garia, Gomara, Jadav, Kathodi, Ker, Lambari, Matia, Mundhva, Pancha, Rathadia, Sania, Sasda, Tota and Yadav.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\nAmong the Bharwad of south Gujarat, their main clans are the Chandulka, Dahika, Gundarya, Jodika, Kalwamia, Khohadya, Kuhadiya and Rokadka.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n<!--PLEASE DO NOT ADD ANY FURTHER CLANS HERE UNLESS THEY ARE SOURCED-->\n\n== Varna and socio-economic status ==\nThe [[Varna (Hinduism)|varna]] system of Hinduism is a traditional ritual ranking system based on levels of purported religious purity. Within this four-fold scheme, the Bharwads consider themselves to be [[Vaishya]] but they also believe themselves to be equal to [[Rajput]] communities that are generally considered to be of the more pure [[Kshatriya]] varna. They also believe themselves to be of a higher ritual status than [[artisan]] groups such as the [[Lohar]]s and [[Suthar]]s.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\nDespite their own beliefs, the Bharwads are generally treated within regional society as being somewhat below the [[Brahmin]], [[Bania (caste)|Vania]], [[Lohana]], Patel, [[Charan]] and [[Dharjee]] communities.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}} Mitra notes that they are generally considered to be among the lowest of the pastoral castes, being engaged primarily in the herding of goats and sheep.{{efn|Some Bharwads are cattle-herders but their number is declining.{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|p=84|ps=}}}} However, although one of the [[Maldhari]] nomadic communities, they are also among the most urbanised of the region and, combined with their niche position in the supply of milk, which forms their main source of income, this has enabled them to improve their traditional social position.{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|pp=65, 84|ps=}}\n\n== Customs ==\n\n=== Religion ===\nThe Bharwad are Hindu, and like other Hindu pastoral communities pay special reverence to Krishna. Each clan also has its own deity, while their chief goddess is Masai Mata. Their most sacred place is at [[Morvi]] and they also make pilgrimages to place such as Dwarka. Some Bharwads in the south have become [[vegetarian]] as a consequence of outside influences.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n=== Family arrangements ===\nMembers of the community practice [[monogamy]] and [[arranged marriage]]s are traditional, usually accompanied by a ritualised exchange of gifts between the partners.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}} There is anecdotal evidence that ''pet chandla'' (marriage of children while they are still in the womb) is practised by some members of the community.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=272|ps=}} In other cases, a ''sagai'' (engagement) ceremony takes place when children are aged 2\u20133, with the marriage age usually being between 18-20 for women and 20-22 for men.{{efn|Marriages of six-year-olds have been recorded but most do not marry so young.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|pp=155, 253|ps=}}}} Remarriage in situations where the couple are childless requires the consent of the wife, and divorce is not usually tolerated except in this situation and that of mental infirmity. Remarriage upon widowhood is also accepted but men are expected generally to prefer a younger unmarried sister of their late wife.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\nMarried couples live in a [[patrilocal]] arrangement. The Bharwads practice male [[equigeniture]], meaning that property is inherited equally by the male children, and it is the eldest son who becomes head of household on the death of the father. Women have no rights of inheritance over property. Although consulted, they also have no final say in the making of significant decisions.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n=== Clothing ===\nThe Bharwads practice \"sartorial conservatism\", according to Emma Tarlo, and it is not enough to be born a Bharwad if a person wants to be accepted as one: conforming with standards of dress and other customs is a necessity if a person is not to be considered a deserter from the community.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|pp=258, 262-263|ps=}} The details of clothing&nbsp;\u2014 in terms of style, colour and material&nbsp;\u2014 have changed over time while retaining a distinct Bharwad character. Despite it being a relatively recent practice, the wearing of pink and red shawls by both women and men is one of the most obvious identifiers of the modern community and they are worn even by those who shun the other aspects of the Bharwadi dress code in favour of Western styles.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=271-272|ps=}} The desire to identify through clothing and also through [[tattoo]]s may be a reflection of the community's traditional itinerant lifestyle, whereby a means of recognising their fellows was a significant social factor.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=273|ps=}}\n\nThe clothing worn by Bharwad women was traditionally made from coarse wool woven by members of local [[Untouchability|untouchable]] communities. In addition, they embroidered their own open-backed [[bodice]]s. The garments at that time&nbsp;\u2014 as late as the early 20th century&nbsp;\u2014 comprised the bodice, an unstitched black or red waist-cloth, known as a ''jimi'', and a veil. Motabhai clothing was made from thicker wool than that of the Nanabhai, leading to the two groups referring to themselves as \"thick cloth\" and \"thin cloth\". The veil was dyed black and bore red dots if the woman was a Motabhai and yellow if she was Nanabhai. While the styles and colours remain similar, modern Bharwad women use [[man-made fibre]]s, such as [[polyester]], and cotton. This change may be in part because the modern materials are of finer texture but it is more likely than it came about because of their relative cheapness. Cost is an important factor among the generally penurious community and women could sell the woollen fabric that they had used for clothing for a greater price than they paid for the replacement man-made fabric clothes.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|pp=xiii, 147, 267|ps=}} Tarlo quotes a Bharwad woman saying that \"If you wear a sari then you can no longer be called a Bharwad. That is the way it is among our caste. Better to die than change your clothes.\"{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=257|ps=}}\n\nThe men commonly wear a silver ear-ring, called a ''variya'', and a [[pagri (turban)]]. The length of the turban differs between the two divisions,{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}} and there are numerous ways of tying them. A white turban, rather than the more usual pink or red, is a symbol of seniority.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=271|ps=}} Wearing Western-style clothing is still not generally accepted but the traditional three woollen blankets, worn around the head, waist and shoulders, have in many cases been replaced by a cotton ''[[kediyun]]'' together with a ''[[dhoti]]'' or ''[[chorni]]''.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=151|ps=}} As with the women, Carol Henderson notes that {{quote|[Bharwads] say that if a man doesn't wear their dress, he ceases to be Bharwad. Being Bharwad means dressing Bharwad. Bharwad men wear a distinctive short gathered smock with long, tight sleeves, massive wound turban, gathered pantaloons, and a shawl.{{sfnp|Henderson|2002|p=113|ps=}}}}\n\n== Occupations ==\n[[Image:Map Guj Gir NatPark Sanctuary.png|thumb|right|Many of the Bharwad community are found in the [[Gir Forest National Park]].]]\nBharwads are rarely educated beyond primary level and literacy rates are poor. Many of them live in and around the [[Gir Forest National Park]], where they tend to keep away from the forest itself when grazing their livestock due to the danger of attacks by [[Asiatic lion]]s. Aside from their involvement with livestock, the main source of income is agricultural labouring; few of them own land.{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|pp=65, 84|ps=}}\n\n== Community associations ==\nThere is a hierarchy of ''nyat [[panchayat]]s'' (community councils) for the resolution of disputes. These are headed by chiefs and comprise several other members. The lowest tier of this are those that operate at the level of a single village or of a group of villages if the Bharwad population is small. Matters that cannot be settled at that level are referred upwards to a regional ''panchayat'' and thereafter to a central body based at [[Rajkot]]. If matters are still not resolved after referral to Rajkot then the parties will seek intervention form law enforcement agencies, although this is rare.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\nThere also exists a community welfare association called the Gujarat Rajya Gopalak Sakahari Sangh, which was formed in 1950 at [[Ahmedabad]]. This has worked to document the history and traditions of the Bhardwads and has also established several hundred co-operative societies. In addition, it has worked to bring an end to some traditional social practices that are now deemed to be inappropriate, such as [[bride price]].{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Dhangar]]\n* [[Rabari]]\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n\nBbbiikbv\n\n'''Citations3'''\n\nHhhjj\n\n'''Bibliographyhhhhjj'''\n[[Category:Tribal communities of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Maldhari communities]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Kutch]]\n[[Category:Herding castes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hindu caste found in the state of Gujarat in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Member of the Bharwad community of India.jpg|thumb|Member of the Bharwad community of India]]\nThe '''Bharwad''' are a [[Hindu]] [[Adivasi]] [[caste]] found in the state of [[Gujarat]] in India.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=1nVCAAAAYAAJ&q=%E0%A4%AD%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A1+%E0%A4%9C%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF&dq=%E0%A4%AD%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A1+%E0%A4%9C%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF | title=Vanyaj\u0101ti, \u092d\u093e\u0917 16,\u0938\u092e\u0938\u094d\u092f\u093e 2 | year=1968 | publisher=Bharatiya Adimjati Sevak Sangh., 1968| accessdate=23 Apr 2009| page=79}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe Bharwad name may derive from the [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] word ''bharawad'', constructed from ''bhara'' (sheep) and ''wad'' (a compound or enclosure). ''[[Gadaria]]'' is another word that may have the same origin. In the [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra region]] of western Gujarat they exist as two [[endogamy|endogamous]] groups, known as the Mota Bhai (Motabhai) and the Nana Bhai (Nanabhai). According to the [[Anthropological Survey of India]]'s ''People of India'' series, Bharwads in the Saurashtra region often append ''[[Ahir]]'' to their names, while in south Gujarat it is common to see ''[[Patel]]'' appended.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n== Origin ==\nThe Bharwads consider themselves to be descended from the mythological [[Nandvanshi]] line that began with [[Nanda (mythology)|Nanda]], the foster-father of [[Krishna]]. Legend has it that Nanda came from [[Gokul]], in [[Mathura district]], and passed through Saurashtra on his way to [[Dwarka]].{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|p=84|ps=}} According to their traditions, the Bharwads were at some time based around [[Mathura]] and migrated to [[Mewar]] before later spreading out in Gujarat.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}} Sudipta Mitra considers their move to Gujarat to have been predicated by a desire to keep away from the [[Muslim]] invasion of [[Sind]]. They arrived in the northern town of [[Banaskantha]] in 961 CE and later spread out to Saurashtra and other areas.{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|p=84|ps=}}\n\nThere are other theories of origin. These include that they are an offshoot of the [[Bharude]] cattle-herders of [[Madhya Pradesh]] and that they are descendants of Anavil Bharwad, who helped a [[Chavda]] prince regain his kingdom. It is also possible that they are related to the Ahirs of Gujarat, with whom they share a common traditional occupation.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n== Divisions ==\nOf the various reasons given for the division between Motabhai and Nanabhai, the most popular is that two shepherd brothers were ordered by [[Krishna]] to take their flocks to different places. The older of the brothers went on to marry a Bharwad woman while the other married a [[Koli people|Koli]]. Since the latter was a marriage outside the community, the offspring were deemed to be [[untouchability|ritually polluted]]. Thus the Motabhai (literally, \"big brother\") descend from the first and the Nanabhai (\"little brother\") from the latter.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=147|ps=}}\n\nThe Bharwads have numerous subgroups known as ''ataks'' or ''guls'' (clans) whose main purpose is to determine eligibility for marriage. A constrained [[exogamy]] is practised between clans{{efn|For example, the Rathadia, Jadav and Yadav clans of the Mota Bhai consider that they are socially superior to the other clans and will only marry between themselves.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}}} but endogamy exists between the two Saurashtrian divisions despite there being no other social constraints on mixing. The Saurashtra Bharwads also hold a higher status than those in the south and thus marriage between the two regional groups operates in one direction only: daughters of southern Bharwads can marry into the family of those from Saurashtra.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n<!--PLEASE DO NOT ADD ANY FURTHER CLANS HERE UNLESS THEY ARE SOURCED-->\nClans of the Mota Bhai Bharwads include the Babha, Bathela, Colthar, Dabi, Dhangia, Dharangia, Garia, Gomara, Jadav, Kathodi, Ker, Lambari, Matia, Mundhva, Pancha, Rathadia, Sania, Sasda, Tota and Yadav.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\nAmong the Bharwad of south Gujarat, their main clans are the Chandulka, Dahika, Gundarya, Jodika, Kalwamia, Khohadya, Kuhadiya and Rokadka.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n<!--PLEASE DO NOT ADD ANY FURTHER CLANS HERE UNLESS THEY ARE SOURCED-->\n\n== Varna and socio-economic status ==\nThe [[Varna (Hinduism)|varna]] system of Hinduism is a traditional ritual ranking system based on levels of purported religious purity. Within this four-fold scheme, the Bharwads consider themselves to be [[Vaishya]] but they also believe themselves to be equal to [[Rajput]] communities that are generally considered to be of the more pure [[Kshatriya]] varna. They also believe themselves to be of a higher ritual status than [[artisan]] groups such as the [[Lohar]]s and [[Suthar]]s.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\nDespite their own beliefs, the Bharwads are generally treated within regional society as being somewhat below the [[Brahmin]], [[Bania (caste)|Vania]], [[Lohana]], Patel, [[Charan]] and [[Dharjee]] communities.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}} Mitra notes that they are generally considered to be among the lowest of the pastoral castes, being engaged primarily in the herding of goats and sheep.{{efn|Some Bharwads are cattle-herders but their number is declining.{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|p=84|ps=}}}} However, although one of the [[Maldhari]] nomadic communities, they are also among the most urbanised of the region and, combined with their niche position in the supply of milk, which forms their main source of income, this has enabled them to improve their traditional social position.{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|pp=65, 84|ps=}}\n\n== Customs ==\n\n=== Religion ===\nThe Bharwad are Hindu, and like other Hindu pastoral communities pay special reverence to Krishna. Each clan also has its own deity, while their chief goddess is Masai Mata. Their most sacred place is at [[Morvi]] and they also make pilgrimages to place such as Dwarka. Some Bharwads in the south have become [[vegetarian]] as a consequence of outside influences.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n=== Family arrangements ===\nMembers of the community practice [[monogamy]] and [[arranged marriage]]s are traditional, usually accompanied by a ritualised exchange of gifts between the partners.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}} There is anecdotal evidence that ''pet chandla'' (marriage of children while they are still in the womb) is practised by some members of the community.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=272|ps=}} In other cases, a ''sagai'' (engagement) ceremony takes place when children are aged 2\u20133, with the marriage age usually being between 18-20 for women and 20-22 for men.{{efn|Marriages of six-year-olds have been recorded but most do not marry so young.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|pp=155, 253|ps=}}}} Remarriage in situations where the couple are childless requires the consent of the wife, and divorce is not usually tolerated except in this situation and that of mental infirmity. Remarriage upon widowhood is also accepted but men are expected generally to prefer a younger unmarried sister of their late wife.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\nMarried couples live in a [[patrilocal]] arrangement. The Bharwads practice male [[equigeniture]], meaning that property is inherited equally by the male children, and it is the eldest son who becomes head of household on the death of the father. Women have no rights of inheritance over property. Although consulted, they also have no final say in the making of significant decisions.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n=== Clothing ===\nThe Bharwads practice \"sartorial conservatism\", according to Emma Tarlo, and it is not enough to be born a Bharwad if a person wants to be accepted as one: conforming with standards of dress and other customs is a necessity if a person is not to be considered a deserter from the community.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|pp=258, 262-263|ps=}} The details of clothing&nbsp;\u2014 in terms of style, colour and material&nbsp;\u2014 have changed over time while retaining a distinct Bharwad character. Despite it being a relatively recent practice, the wearing of pink and red shawls by both women and men is one of the most obvious identifiers of the modern community and they are worn even by those who shun the other aspects of the Bharwadi dress code in favour of Western styles.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=271-272|ps=}} The desire to identify through clothing and also through [[tattoo]]s may be a reflection of the community's traditional itinerant lifestyle, whereby a means of recognising their fellows was a significant social factor.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=273|ps=}}\n\nThe clothing worn by Bharwad women was traditionally made from coarse wool woven by members of local [[Untouchability|untouchable]] communities. In addition, they embroidered their own open-backed [[bodice]]s. The garments at that time&nbsp;\u2014 as late as the early 20th century&nbsp;\u2014 comprised the bodice, an unstitched black or red waist-cloth, known as a ''jimi'', and a veil. Motabhai clothing was made from thicker wool than that of the Nanabhai, leading to the two groups referring to themselves as \"thick cloth\" and \"thin cloth\". The veil was dyed black and bore red dots if the woman was a Motabhai and yellow if she was Nanabhai. While the styles and colours remain similar, modern Bharwad women use [[man-made fibre]]s, such as [[polyester]], and cotton. This change may be in part because the modern materials are of finer texture but it is more likely than it came about because of their relative cheapness. Cost is an important factor among the generally penurious community and women could sell the woollen fabric that they had used for clothing for a greater price than they paid for the replacement man-made fabric clothes.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|pp=xiii, 147, 267|ps=}} Tarlo quotes a Bharwad woman saying that \"If you wear a sari then you can no longer be called a Bharwad. That is the way it is among our caste. Better to die than change your clothes.\"{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=257|ps=}}\n\nThe men commonly wear a silver ear-ring, called a ''variya'', and a [[pagri (turban)]]. The length of the turban differs between the two divisions,{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}} and there are numerous ways of tying them. A white turban, rather than the more usual pink or red, is a symbol of seniority.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=271|ps=}} Wearing Western-style clothing is still not generally accepted but the traditional three woollen blankets, worn around the head, waist and shoulders, have in many cases been replaced by a cotton ''[[kediyun]]'' together with a ''[[dhoti]]'' or ''[[chorni]]''.{{sfnp|Tarlo|1996|p=151|ps=}} As with the women, Carol Henderson notes that {{quote|[Bharwads] say that if a man doesn't wear their dress, he ceases to be Bharwad. Being Bharwad means dressing Bharwad. Bharwad men wear a distinctive short gathered smock with long, tight sleeves, massive wound turban, gathered pantaloons, and a shawl.{{sfnp|Henderson|2002|p=113|ps=}}}}\n\n== Occupations ==\n[[Image:Map Guj Gir NatPark Sanctuary.png|thumb|right|Many of the Bharwad community are found in the [[Gir Forest National Park]].]]\nBharwads are rarely educated beyond primary level and literacy rates are poor. Many of them live in and around the [[Gir Forest National Park]], where they tend to keep away from the forest itself when grazing their livestock due to the danger of attacks by [[Asiatic lion]]s. Aside from their involvement with livestock, the main source of income is agricultural labouring; few of them own land.{{sfnp|Mitra|2005|pp=65, 84|ps=}}\n\n== Community associations ==\nThere is a hierarchy of ''nyat [[panchayat]]s'' (community councils) for the resolution of disputes. These are headed by chiefs and comprise several other members. The lowest tier of this are those that operate at the level of a single village or of a group of villages if the Bharwad population is small. Matters that cannot be settled at that level are referred upwards to a regional ''panchayat'' and thereafter to a central body based at [[Rajkot]]. If matters are still not resolved after referral to Rajkot then the parties will seek intervention form law enforcement agencies, although this is rare.{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\nThere also exists a community welfare association called the Gujarat Rajya Gopalak Sakahari Sangh, which was formed in 1950 at [[Ahmedabad]]. This has worked to document the history and traditions of the Bhardwads and has also established several hundred co-operative societies. In addition, it has worked to bring an end to some traditional social practices that are now deemed to be inappropriate, such as [[bride price]].{{sfnp|Lal|Padmanabham|Krishnan|Mohideen|2003|pp=194-199|ps=}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Dhangar]]\n* [[Rabari]]\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation |title=Culture and Customs of India |first=Carol E. |last=Henderson |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2002 |isbn=9780313305139 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CaRVePXX6vEC}}\n*{{citation |title=People of India Gujarat Volume XXI Part One |editor1-first=Rajendra Behari |editor1-last=Lal |editor2-first=P. B. S. V. |editor2-last=Padmanabham |editor3-first=G. |editor3-last=Krishnan |editor4-first=M. 